    {"id": "growth-stock", "level": "入门", "category": "股票", "title": "Growth stock——In finance, a growth stock is a stock of a company that gene…", "summary": "In finance, a growth stock is a stock of a company that generates substantial and sustainable positive cash flow and whose revenues and earnings are expected to increase at a faster rate than the average company within the same industry.", "takeaways": ["A growth company typically has some sort of competitive advantage (a new product, a breakthrough patent, overseas expansion) that allows it to fend off competitors.", "Growth stocks usually pay smaller dividends, as the companies typically reinvest most retained earnings in capital-intensive projects."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "MSFT"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Growth_stock"},
    {"id": "value-stock", "level": "入门", "category": "股票", "title": "Value investing——Value investing is an investment paradigm that involves buyi…", "summary": "Value investing is an investment paradigm that involves buying securities that appear underpriced by some form of fundamental analysis. Modern value investing derives from the investment philosophy taught by Benjamin Graham and David Dodd at Columbia Business School starting in 1928 and subsequently developed in their…", "takeaways": ["Value investing is an investment paradigm that  involves buying securities that appear underpriced by some form of fundamental analysis.", "Hedge fund manager Seth Klarman has described value investing as rooted in a rejection of the efficient-market hypothesis (EMH).", "The term has also led to misinterpretation of his principles - most notably the notion that Graham simply recommended cheap stocks."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "MSFT"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Value_investing"},
    {"id": "short-selling", "level": "进阶", "category": "股票", "title": "Short (finance)——In finance, being short in an asset means investing in such …", "summary": "In finance, being short in an asset means investing in such a way that the investor will profit if the market value of the asset falls. This is the opposite of the more common long position, where the investor will profit if the market value of the asset rises.", "takeaways": ["In finance, being short in an asset means investing in such a way that the investor will profit if the market value of the asset falls.", "Conversely, if the price has risen then the short seller will bear a loss.", "Nevertheless, research indicates that banning short selling is ineffective and has negative effects on markets."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "MSFT"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Short_%28finance%29"},
    {"id": "margin-trading", "level": "进阶", "category": "股票", "title": "Margin (finance)——In finance, margin is the collateral that a holder of a fina…", "summary": "In finance, margin is the collateral that a holder of a financial instrument has to deposit with a counterparty (most often a broker or an exchange) to cover some or all of the credit risk the holder poses for the counterparty.", "takeaways": ["The collateral for a margin account can be the cash deposited in the account or securities provided, and represents the funds available to the account holder for further share trading.", "On United States futures exchanges, margins were formerly called performance bonds."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "MSFT"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Margin_%28finance%29"},
    {"id": "market-order", "level": "入门", "category": "股票", "title": "Order (exchange)——An order is an instruction to buy or sell on a trading venue…", "summary": "An order is an instruction to buy or sell on a trading venue such as a stock market, bond market, commodity market, financial derivative market or cryptocurrency exchange. These instructions can be simple or complicated, and can be sent to either a broker or directly to a trading venue via direct market access.", "takeaways": ["An order is an instruction to buy or sell on a trading venue such as a stock market, bond market, commodity market, financial derivative market or cryptocurrency exchange.", "These instructions can be simple or complicated, and can be sent to either a broker or directly to a trading venue via direct market access.", "There are some standard instructions for such orders."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "MSFT"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Order_%28exchange%29"},
    {"id": "limit-order", "level": "入门", "category": "股票", "title": "Order (exchange)——An order is an instruction to buy or sell on a trading venue…", "summary": "An order is an instruction to buy or sell on a trading venue such as a stock market, bond market, commodity market, financial derivative market or cryptocurrency exchange. These instructions can be simple or complicated, and can be sent to either a broker or directly to a trading venue via direct market access.", "takeaways": ["An order is an instruction to buy or sell on a trading venue such as a stock market, bond market, commodity market, financial derivative market or cryptocurrency exchange.", "These instructions can be simple or complicated, and can be sent to either a broker or directly to a trading venue via direct market access.", "There are some standard instructions for such orders."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "MSFT"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Limit_order"},
    {"id": "stop-order", "level": "入门", "category": "股票", "title": "Order (exchange)——An order is an instruction to buy or sell on a trading venue…", "summary": "An order is an instruction to buy or sell on a trading venue such as a stock market, bond market, commodity market, financial derivative market or cryptocurrency exchange. These instructions can be simple or complicated, and can be sent to either a broker or directly to a trading venue via direct market access.", "takeaways": ["An order is an instruction to buy or sell on a trading venue such as a stock market, bond market, commodity market, financial derivative market or cryptocurrency exchange.", "These instructions can be simple or complicated, and can be sent to either a broker or directly to a trading venue via direct market access.", "There are some standard instructions for such orders."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "MSFT"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stop_order"},
    {"id": "short-squeeze", "level": "进阶", "category": "股票", "title": "Short squeeze——In the stock market, a short squeeze is a rapid increase in …", "summary": "In the stock market, a short squeeze is a rapid increase in the price of a stock owing primarily to an excess of short selling of a stock rather than underlying fundamentals. A short squeeze occurs when demand has increased relative to supply because short sellers have to buy stock to cover their short positions.", "takeaways": ["In the stock market, a short squeeze is a rapid increase in the price of a stock owing primarily to an excess of short selling of a stock rather than underlying fundamentals.", "A short squeeze occurs when demand has increased relative to supply because short sellers have to buy stock to cover their short positions."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "MSFT"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Short_squeeze"},
    {"id": "income-statement", "level": "入门", "category": "财务报表", "title": "Income statement——An income statement or profit and loss (P&L) account is one …", "summary": "An income statement or profit and loss (P&L) account is one of the financial statements of a company and shows the company's revenues and expenses during a particular period.", "takeaways": ["An income statement or profit and loss (P&L) account is one of the financial statements of a company and shows the company's revenues and expenses dur…", "Revenues and expenses are further categorized in the statement of activities by the donor restrictions on the funds received and expended.", "The final step is to deduct taxes, which finally produces the net income for the period measured."], "marketLinks": ["AAPL", "MSFT", "AMZN"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Income_statement"},
    {"id": "revenue-recognition", "level": "进阶", "category": "财务报表", "title": "Revenue recognition——In accounting, the revenue recognition principle states that…", "summary": "In accounting, the revenue recognition principle states that revenues are earned and recognized when they are realized or realizable, no matter when cash is received. It is a cornerstone of accrual accounting together with the matching principle.", "takeaways": ["In accounting, the revenue recognition principle states that revenues are earned and recognized when they are realized or realizable, no matter when c…", "In contrast, the cash accounting recognizes revenues when cash is received, no matter when goods or services are sold.", "Deferred revenue: Revenue is recognized when cash is received."], "marketLinks": ["AAPL", "MSFT", "AMZN"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Revenue_recognition"},
    {"id": "cogs", "level": "入门", "category": "财务报表", "title": "Cost of goods sold——Cost of goods sold (COGS) (also cost of products sold (COPS)…", "summary": "Cost of goods sold (COGS) (also cost of products sold (COPS), or cost of sales) is the carrying value of goods sold during a particular period. Costs are associated with particular goods using one of several formulas, including specific identification, first-in first-out (FIFO), or average cost.", "takeaways": ["Cost of goods sold (COGS) (also cost of products sold (COPS), or cost of sales) is the carrying value of goods sold during a particular period.", "Costs include all costs of purchase, costs of conversion and other costs that are incurred in bringing the inventories to their present location and c…", "The costs of those goods which are not yet sold are deferred as costs of inventory until the inventory is sold or written down in value."], "marketLinks": ["AAPL", "MSFT", "AMZN"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cost_of_goods_sold"},
    {"id": "gross-profit", "level": "入门", "category": "财务报表", "title": "Gross income——For households and individuals, gross income is the sum of a…", "summary": "For households and individuals, gross income is the sum of all wages, salaries, profits, interest payments, rents, and other forms of earnings, before any deductions or taxes. It is opposed to net income, defined as the gross income minus taxes and other deductions (e.g., mandatory pension contributions).", "takeaways": ["For households and individuals, gross income is the sum of all wages, salaries, profits, interest payments, rents, and other forms of earnings, before…", "This is different from operating profit (earnings before interest and taxes).", "When speaking about a monetary amount, it is technically correct to use the term \"gross profit\", but when referring to a percentage or ratio, it is co…"], "marketLinks": ["AAPL", "MSFT", "AMZN"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gross_income"},
    {"id": "operating-income", "level": "入门", "category": "财务报表", "title": "Earnings before interest and taxes——In accounting and finance, earnings before interest and taxe…", "summary": "In accounting and finance, earnings before interest and taxes (EBIT) is a measure of a firm's profit that includes all incomes and expenses (operating and non-operating) except interest expenses and income tax expenses.", "takeaways": ["了解Earnings before interest and taxes的基本定义和应用场景", "理解Earnings before interest and taxes在金融市场中的作用和影响", "结合市场数据观察Earnings before interest and taxes的实际表现"], "marketLinks": ["AAPL", "MSFT", "AMZN"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Earnings_before_interest_and_taxes"},
    {"id": "net-income", "level": "入门", "category": "财务报表", "title": "Net income——In business and accounting, net income is an entity's income…", "summary": "In business and accounting, net income is an entity's income minus cost of goods sold, expenses, depreciation and amortization, interest, and taxes, and other expenses for an accounting period.", "takeaways": ["In business and accounting, net income is an entity's income minus cost of goods sold, expenses, depreciation and amortization, interest, and taxes, a…", "For households and individuals, net income is the (gross) income minus taxes and other deductions (e.g.", "mandatory pension contributions)."], "marketLinks": ["AAPL", "MSFT", "AMZN"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Net_income"},
    {"id": "eps", "level": "入门", "category": "财务报表", "title": "Earnings per share——Earnings per share (EPS) is the monetary value of earnings p…", "summary": "Earnings per share (EPS) is the monetary value of earnings per outstanding share of common stock for a company during a defined period of time, often a year. It is a key measure of corporate profitability, focusing on the interests of the company's owners (shareholders), and is commonly used to price stocks.", "takeaways": ["Earnings per share (EPS) is the monetary value of earnings per outstanding share of common stock for a company during a defined period of time, often a year.", "It is a key measure of corporate profitability, focusing on the interests of the company's owners (shareholders), and is commonly used to price stocks."], "marketLinks": ["AAPL", "MSFT", "AMZN"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Earnings_per_share"},
    {"id": "balance-sheet", "level": "入门", "category": "财务报表", "title": "Balance sheet——In financial accounting, a balance sheet (also known as stat…", "summary": "In financial accounting, a balance sheet (also known as statement of financial position or statement of financial condition) is a summary of the financial balances of an individual or organization, whether it be a sole proprietorship, a business partnership, a corporation, a private limited company or other…", "takeaways": ["Assets, liabilities and ownership equity are listed as of a specific date, such as the end of its financial year.", "A business can measure its profits by subtracting its expenses from its revenues.", "In other words, businesses also have liabilities."], "marketLinks": ["AAPL", "MSFT", "AMZN"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Balance_sheet"},
    {"id": "current-assets", "level": "入门", "category": "财务报表", "title": "Current asset——In accounting, a current asset is an asset that can reasonab…", "summary": "In accounting, a current asset is an asset that can reasonably be expected to be sold, consumed, or exhausted through the normal operations of a business within the current fiscal year, operating cycle, or financial year. In simple terms, current assets are assets that are held for a short period.", "takeaways": ["In simple terms, current assets are assets that are held for a short period.", "It is frequently used as an indicator of a company's accounting liquidity, which is its ability to meet short-term obligations.", "Quick assets are those that can be quickly turned into cash if necessary and may not be used for a substantial period of time such as twelve months."], "marketLinks": ["AAPL", "MSFT", "AMZN"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Current_asset"},
    {"id": "fixed-assets", "level": "入门", "category": "财务报表", "title": "Fixed asset——Fixed assets (also known as long-lived assets or property, p…", "summary": "Fixed assets (also known as long-lived assets or property, plant and equipment; PP&E) is a term used in accounting for assets and property that may not easily be converted into cash. They are contrasted with current assets, such as cash, bank accounts, and short-term debts receivable.", "takeaways": ["Fixed assets (also known as long-lived assets or property, plant and equipment; PP&E) is a term used in accounting for assets and property that may no…", "In most cases, only tangible assets are referred to as fixed.", "A fixed asset can also be defined as an asset not directly sold to a firm's consumers or end-users."], "marketLinks": ["AAPL", "MSFT", "AMZN"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fixed_asset"},
    {"id": "goodwill", "level": "进阶", "category": "财务报表", "title": "Goodwill (accounting)——In accounting, goodwill is an intangible asset recognized wh…", "summary": "In accounting, goodwill is an intangible asset recognized when a firm is purchased as a going concern. It reflects the premium the buyer pays over the net value of its other assets.", "takeaways": ["In accounting, goodwill is an intangible asset recognized when a firm is purchased as a going concern.", "GAAP and IFRS, goodwill is never amortized for public companies, because it is considered to have an indefinite useful life.", "However, an increase in fair market value would not be recognized in this way, and may instead be attributed to other assets."], "marketLinks": ["AAPL", "MSFT", "AMZN"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goodwill_%28accounting%29"},
    {"id": "current-liabilities", "level": "入门", "category": "财务报表", "title": "Current liability——Current liabilities in accounting refer to the liabilities o…", "summary": "Current liabilities in accounting refer to the liabilities of a business that are expected to be settled in cash within one fiscal year or the firm's operating cycle, whichever is longer. These liabilities are typically settled using current assets or by incurring new current liabilities.", "takeaways": ["Current liabilities in accounting refer to the liabilities of a business that are expected to be settled in cash within one fiscal year or the firm's …", "The proper classification of liabilities is essential for providing accurate financial information to investors and stakeholders.", "The difference between current assets and current liabilities is referred to as trade working capital."], "marketLinks": ["AAPL", "MSFT", "AMZN"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Current_liability"},
    {"id": "long-term-debt", "level": "入门", "category": "财务报表", "title": "Long-term liabilities——Long-term liabilities, or non-current liabilities, are liabi…", "summary": "Long-term liabilities, or non-current liabilities, are liabilities that are due beyond a year or the normal operation period of the company. The normal operation period is the amount of time it takes for a company to turn inventory into cash.", "takeaways": ["Long-term liabilities, or non-current liabilities, are liabilities that are due beyond a year or the normal operation period of the company.", "Long-term liabilities give users more information about the long-term prosperity of the company, while current liabilities inform the user of debt tha…", "Therefore, an account due within eighteen months would be listed before an account due within twenty-four months."], "marketLinks": ["AAPL", "MSFT", "AMZN"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Long-term_liabilities"},
    {"id": "shareholders-equity", "level": "入门", "category": "财务报表", "title": "Equity (finance)——In finance, equity is an ownership interest in property that…", "summary": "In finance, equity is an ownership interest in property that may be subject to debts or other liabilities. Equity is measured for accounting purposes by subtracting liabilities from the value of the assets owned.", "takeaways": ["In finance, equity is an ownership interest in property that may be subject to debts or other liabilities.", "Equity can apply to a single asset, such as a car or house, or to an entire business.", "In government finance or other non-profit settings, equity is known as \"net position\" or \"net assets\"."], "marketLinks": ["AAPL", "MSFT", "AMZN"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equity_%28finance%29"},
    {"id": "cash-flow-statement", "level": "进阶", "category": "财务报表", "title": "Cash flow statement——In financial accounting, a cash flow statement, also known a…", "summary": "In financial accounting, a cash flow statement, also known as statement of cash flows, is a financial statement that shows how changes in balance sheet accounts and income affect cash and cash equivalents, and breaks the analysis down to operating, investing and financing activities.", "takeaways": ["Essentially, the cash flow statement is concerned with the flow of cash in and out of the business.", "As an analytical tool, the statement of cash flows is useful in determining the short-term viability of a company, particularly its ability to pay bills.", "International Accounting Standard 7 (IAS 7) is the International Accounting Standard that deals with cash flow statements."], "marketLinks": ["AAPL", "MSFT", "AMZN"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cash_flow_statement"},
    {"id": "free-cash-flow", "level": "进阶", "category": "财务报表", "title": "Free cash flow——In financial accounting, free cash flow (FCF) or free cash f…", "summary": "In financial accounting, free cash flow (FCF) or free cash flow to firm (FCFF) is the amount by which a business's operating cash flow exceeds its working capital needs and expenditures on fixed assets (known as capital expenditures).", "takeaways": ["It is that portion of cash flow that can be extracted from a company and distributed to creditors and securities holders  without causing issues in it…", "A common measure is to take the earnings before interest and taxes, add depreciation and amortization, and then subtract taxes, changes in working cap…", "Free cash flow may be different from net income, as free cash flow takes into account the purchase of capital goods and changes in working capital and…"], "marketLinks": ["AAPL", "MSFT", "AMZN"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Free_cash_flow"},
    {"id": "operating-cash-flow", "level": "进阶", "category": "财务报表", "title": "Operating cash flow——In financial accounting, operating cash flow (OCF), cash flo…", "summary": "In financial accounting, operating cash flow (OCF), cash flow provided by operations, cash flow from operating activities (CFO) or free cash flow from operations (FCFO), refers to the amount of cash a company generates from the revenues it brings in, excluding costs associated with long-term investment on capital…", "takeaways": ["Operating activities include any spending or sources of cash that’s involved in a company’s day-to-day business activities.", "The difference between the two reflects cash generated from operations.", "Cost of Sales − Stock Variation = Stock out − (Stock out − Stock In) = Stock In = Purchase of goods: Cash Out"], "marketLinks": ["AAPL", "MSFT", "AMZN"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Operating_cash_flow"},
    {"id": "ebitda", "level": "进阶", "category": "财务报表", "title": "Earnings before interest, taxes, depreciation and amortization——Earnings before interest, taxes, depreciation, and amortizat…", "summary": "Earnings before interest, taxes, depreciation, and amortization, commonly known as EBITDA ( EE-bit-dah, EB-it-dah), is a measure of a company's profitability of the operating business only, before any effects of indebtedness, state-mandated payments, and costs required to maintain its asset base.", "takeaways": ["了解Earnings before interest, taxes, depreciation and amortization的基本定义和应用场景", "理解Earnings before interest, taxes, depreciation and amortization在金融市场中的作用和影响", "结合市场数据观察Earnings before interest, taxes, depreciation and amortization的实际表现"], "marketLinks": ["AAPL", "MSFT", "AMZN"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Earnings_before_interest%2C_taxes%2C_depreciation_and_amortization"},
    {"id": "pe-ratio", "level": "入门", "category": "财务比率", "title": "Price–earnings ratio——The price–earnings ratio, also known as P/E ratio, P/E, or P…", "summary": "The price–earnings ratio, also known as P/E ratio, P/E, or PER, is the ratio of a company's share price to the company's earnings per share. The ratio is used for valuing companies and to find out whether they are overvalued or undervalued.", "takeaways": ["The price–earnings ratio, also known as P/E ratio, P/E, or PER, is the ratio of a company's share price to the company's earnings per share.", "Put another way, the purchaser of the share is expecting 8 years to recoup the share price.", "There is a general consensus among most investors that a P/E ratio of around 10 to 20 is \"fairly priced\" but this is sector and business dependent."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "QQQ", "AAPL"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Price%E2%80%93earnings_ratio"},
    {"id": "pb-ratio", "level": "入门", "category": "财务比率", "title": "P/B ratio——The price-to-book ratio, or P/B ratio, (also PBR) is a finan…", "summary": "The price-to-book ratio, or P/B ratio, (also PBR) is a financial ratio used to compare a company's current market value to its book value (where book value is the value of all assets minus liabilities owned by a company). The calculation can be performed in two ways, but the result should be the same.", "takeaways": ["The calculation can be performed in two ways, but the result should be the same.", "Industries that require more infrastructure capital (for each dollar of profit) will usually trade at P/B ratios much lower than, for example, consult…", "In such cases, P/B should also be calculated on a \"diluted\" basis, because stock options may well vest on sale of the company or change of control or …"], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "QQQ", "AAPL"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P/B_ratio"},
    {"id": "ps-ratio", "level": "入门", "category": "财务比率", "title": "Price–sales ratio——The price-to-sales ratio (P/S ratio or PSR) is a financial r…", "summary": "The price-to-sales ratio (P/S ratio or PSR) is a financial ratio used to assess a company's market value relative to its revenue. It is calculated by dividing the company's market capitalization by its total revenue over a specified period, typically the trailing twelve months (TTM), or equivalently, by dividing the…", "takeaways": ["The price-to-sales ratio (P/S ratio or PSR) is a financial ratio used to assess a company's market value relative to its revenue.", "A lower ratio (e.g., below 1.0) may suggest a stock is undervalued, while a higher ratio could indicate overvaluation, though interpretation depends o…", "The ratio can also track a stock's valuation over time or compare companies within the same sector."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "QQQ", "AAPL"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Price%E2%80%93sales_ratio"},
    {"id": "peg-ratio", "level": "进阶", "category": "财务比率", "title": "PEG ratio——The PEG ratio (price/earnings to growth ratio) is a valuatio…", "summary": "The PEG ratio (price/earnings to growth ratio) is a valuation metric for determining the relative trade-off between the price of a stock, the earnings generated per share (EPS), and the company's expected growth. In general, the P/E ratio is higher for a company with a higher growth rate.", "takeaways": ["In general, the P/E ratio is higher for a company with a higher growth rate.", "The PEG ratio is considered to be a convenient approximation.", "The formula can be supported theoretically by reference to the Sum of perpetuities method."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "QQQ", "AAPL"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PEG_ratio"},
    {"id": "ev-ebitda", "level": "进阶", "category": "财务比率", "title": "Enterprise value——Enterprise value (EV), total enterprise value (TEV), or firm…", "summary": "Enterprise value (EV), total enterprise value (TEV), or firm value (FV) is an economic measure reflecting the market value of a business (i.e. as distinct from market price). It is a sum of claims by all claimants: creditors (secured and unsecured) and shareholders (preferred and common).", "takeaways": ["Enterprise value (EV), total enterprise value (TEV), or firm value (FV) is an economic measure reflecting the market value of a business (i.e.", "Enterprise value is one of the fundamental metrics used in business valuation, financial analysis, accounting, portfolio analysis, and risk analysis.", "Therefore, financial analysts often use a comfortable range of EV in their calculations."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "QQQ", "AAPL"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Enterprise_value"},
    {"id": "roe", "level": "入门", "category": "财务比率", "title": "Return on equity——The return on equity (ROE) is a measure of the profitability…", "summary": "The return on equity (ROE) is a measure of the profitability of a business in relation to its equity; where: ROE = ⁠Net Income/Average Shareholders' Equity⁠ Thus, ROE is equal to a fiscal year's net income (after preferred stock dividends, before common stock dividends), divided by total equity (excluding preferred…", "takeaways": ["了解Return on equity的基本定义和应用场景", "理解Return on equity在金融市场中的作用和影响", "结合市场数据观察Return on equity的实际表现"], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "QQQ", "AAPL"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Return_on_equity"},
    {"id": "roa", "level": "入门", "category": "财务比率", "title": "Return on assets——The return on assets (ROA) shows the percentage of how profi…", "summary": "The return on assets (ROA) shows the percentage of how profitable a company's assets are in generating revenue. ROA can be computed as below: R O A = Net Income Average Total Assets {\\displaystyle \\mathrm {ROA} ={\\frac {\\mbox{Net Income}}{\\mbox{Average Total Assets}}}} The phrase return on average assets (ROAA) is…", "takeaways": ["The return on assets (ROA) shows the percentage of how profitable a company's assets are in generating revenue.", "It's a useful number for comparing competing companies in the same industry.", "ROAs over 5% are generally considered good."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "QQQ", "AAPL"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Return_on_assets"},
    {"id": "roic", "level": "进阶", "category": "财务比率", "title": "Return on capital——Return on capital (ROC), or return on invested capital (ROIC…", "summary": "Return on capital (ROC), or return on invested capital (ROIC), is a ratio used in finance, valuation and accounting, as a measure of the profitability and value-creating potential of companies relative to the amount of capital invested by shareholders and other debtholders.", "takeaways": ["It indicates how effective a company is at turning capital into profits.", "The ratio is calculated by dividing the after tax operating income (NOPAT) by the average book-value of the invested capital (IC)."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "QQQ", "AAPL"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Return_on_capital"},
    {"id": "profit-margin", "level": "入门", "category": "财务比率", "title": "Profit margin——Profit margin is a financial ratio that measures the percent…", "summary": "Profit margin is a financial ratio that measures the percentage of profit earned by a company in relation to its revenue. Expressed as a percentage, it indicates how much profit the company makes for every dollar of revenue generated.", "takeaways": ["Profit margin is a financial ratio that measures the percentage of profit earned by a company in relation to its revenue.", "Maintaining a healthy profit margin will help to ensure the financial success of a business, which will improve its ability to obtain loans.", "Profit margins can include risk premiums and monopoly profits."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "QQQ", "AAPL"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Profit_margin"},
    {"id": "current-ratio", "level": "入门", "category": "财务比率", "title": "Current ratio——The current ratio is a liquidity ratio that measures whether…", "summary": "The current ratio is a liquidity ratio that measures whether a firm has enough resources to meet its short-term obligations. It is the ratio of a firm's current assets to its current liabilities, ⁠Current Assets/Current Liabilities⁠. The current ratio is an indication of a firm's accounting liquidity.", "takeaways": ["The current ratio is a liquidity ratio that measures whether a firm has enough resources to meet its short-term obligations.", "However, if a company's current ratio is too high, it may indicate that the company is not efficiently using its current assets.", "To determine liquidity, the quick ratio is also used, which excludes current assets that may not be easily liquidated, like prepaid expenses and inven…"], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "QQQ", "AAPL"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Current_ratio"},
    {"id": "quick-ratio", "level": "入门", "category": "财务比率", "title": "Quick ratio——In finance, the quick ratio, also known as the acid-test rat…", "summary": "In finance, the quick ratio, also known as the acid-test ratio, is a liquidity ratio that measures the ability of a company to use near-cash assets (or 'quick' assets) to extinguish or retire current liabilities immediately. It is the ratio between quick assets and current liabilities.", "takeaways": ["It is the ratio between quick assets and current liabilities.", "A normal liquid ratio is considered to be 1:1.", "A company with a quick ratio of less than 1 cannot currently fully pay back its current liabilities."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "QQQ", "AAPL"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quick_ratio"},
    {"id": "debt-ratio", "level": "入门", "category": "财务比率", "title": "Debt ratio——The debt ratio or debt to assets ratio is a financial ratio …", "summary": "The debt ratio or debt to assets ratio is a financial ratio which indicates the percentage of a company's assets which are funded by debt. It is measured as the ratio of total debt to total assets, which is also equal to the ratio of total liabilities and total assets: Debt ratio = ⁠Total Debts/Total Assets⁠ = ⁠Total…", "takeaways": ["The debt ratio or debt to assets ratio is a financial ratio which indicates the percentage of a company's assets which are funded by debt.", "Companies with high debt to asset ratios are said to be highly leveraged, and are associated with greater risk.", "A high debt to asset ratio may also indicate a low borrowing capacity, which in turn will limit the firm's financial flexibility."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "QQQ", "AAPL"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Debt_ratio"},
    {"id": "debt-to-equity", "level": "入门", "category": "财务比率", "title": "Debt-to-equity ratio——A company's debt-to-equity ratio (D/E) is a financial ratio …", "summary": "A company's debt-to-equity ratio (D/E) is a financial ratio indicating the relative proportion of shareholders' equity and debt used to finance the company's assets. Closely related to leveraging, the ratio is also known as risk ratio, gearing ratio or leverage ratio.", "takeaways": ["A company's debt-to-equity ratio (D/E) is a financial ratio indicating the relative proportion of shareholders' equity and debt used to finance the company's assets.", "Closely related to leveraging, the ratio is also known as risk ratio, gearing ratio or leverage ratio."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "QQQ", "AAPL"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Debt-to-equity_ratio"},
    {"id": "asset-turnover", "level": "入门", "category": "财务比率", "title": "Asset turnover——In finance, asset turnover (ATO), total asset turnover, or a…", "summary": "In finance, asset turnover (ATO), total asset turnover, or asset turns is a financial ratio that measures the efficiency of a company's use of its assets in generating sales revenue or sales income to the company.", "takeaways": ["Asset turnover is considered to be a profitability ratio, which is a group of financial ratios that measure how efficiently a company uses assets.", "Companies in the retail industry tend to have a very high turnover ratio, due mainly to cutthroat and competitive pricing.", "Alternatively, \"Average Total Assets\" can be ending total assets."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "QQQ", "AAPL"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Asset_turnover"},
    {"id": "inventory-turnover", "level": "进阶", "category": "财务比率", "title": "Inventory turnover——In accounting, the inventory turnover is a measure of the nu…", "summary": "In accounting, the inventory turnover is a measure of the number of times inventory is sold or used in a time period such as a year. It is calculated to see if a business has an excessive inventory in comparison to its sales level.", "takeaways": ["In accounting, the inventory turnover is a measure of the number of times inventory is sold or used in a time period such as a year.", "The equation for inventory turnover equals the cost of goods sold divided by the average inventory.", "Inventory turnover is also known as inventory turns, merchandise turnover, stockturn, stock turns, turns, and stock turnover."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "QQQ", "AAPL"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inventory_turnover"},
    {"id": "dividend-yield", "level": "入门", "category": "财务比率", "title": "Dividend yield——The dividend yield of a share is the ratio of annualised cas…", "summary": "The dividend yield of a share is the ratio of annualised cash dividends to the share's current market price. It is usually expressed as a percentage and is commonly calculated by dividing the annual dividend per share by the current share price.", "takeaways": ["The dividend yield of a share is the ratio of annualised cash dividends to the share's current market price.", "At the company level, the same idea can be expressed as total annual dividends divided by the company’s market capitalisation, assuming the number of …", "Because both dividends and prices can change, a high dividend yield can reflect a higher payout, a lower share price, or expectations that dividends w…"], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "QQQ", "AAPL"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dividend_yield"},
    {"id": "dividend-payout-ratio", "level": "进阶", "category": "财务比率", "title": "Dividend payout ratio——The dividend payout ratio is the fraction of net income a fi…", "summary": "The dividend payout ratio is the fraction of net income a firm pays to its stockholders in dividends: Dividend payout ratio = Dividends Net Income for the same period {\\textstyle {\\mbox{Dividend payout ratio}}={\\frac {\\mbox{Dividends}}{\\mbox{Net Income for the same period}}}} The part of earnings not paid to investors…", "takeaways": ["Investors seeking high current income and limited capital growth prefer companies with a high dividend payout ratio.", "As they mature, they tend to return more of the earnings back to investors.", "According to Financial Accounting by Walter T."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "QQQ", "AAPL"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dividend_payout_ratio"},
    {"id": "dupont-analysis", "level": "进阶", "category": "财务比率", "title": "DuPont analysis——Dupont analysis is a tool used in financial analysis, where …", "summary": "Dupont analysis is a tool used in financial analysis, where return on equity (ROE) is separated into its component parts. Useful in several contexts, this \"decomposition\" of ROE allows financial managers to focus on the key metrics of financial performance individually, and thereby to identify strengths and weaknesses…", "takeaways": ["Dupont analysis is a tool used in financial analysis, where return on equity (ROE) is separated into its component parts.", "Similarly, it allows investors to compare the operational efficiency of two comparable firms."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "QQQ", "AAPL"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DuPont_analysis"},
    {"id": "interest-coverage", "level": "进阶", "category": "财务比率", "title": "Times interest earned——Times interest earned (TIE) or interest coverage ratio is a …", "summary": "Times interest earned (TIE) or interest coverage ratio is a measure of a company's ability to honor its debt payments. It may be calculated as either EBIT or EBITDA divided by the total interest expense.", "takeaways": ["Times interest earned (TIE) or interest coverage ratio is a measure of a company's ability to honor its debt payments.", "The company would then have to either use cash on hand to make up the difference or borrow funds.", "Typically, it is a warning sign when interest coverage falls below 2.5x."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "QQQ", "AAPL"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Times_interest_earned"},
    {"id": "beta-coefficient", "level": "入门", "category": "财务比率", "title": "Beta (finance)——In finance, the beta (β or market beta or beta coefficient) …", "summary": "In finance, the beta (β or market beta or beta coefficient) is a statistic that measures the expected increase or decrease of an individual stock price in proportion to movements of the stock market as a whole.", "takeaways": ["Beta can be used to indicate the contribution of an individual asset to the market risk of a portfolio when it is added in small quantity.", "Beta measures the contribution of an individual investment to the risk of the market portfolio that was not reduced by diversification.", "Most stocks have betas between 0 and 3."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "QQQ", "AAPL"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beta_%28finance%29"},
    {"id": "market-cap-to-gdp", "level": "进阶", "category": "财务比率", "title": "Buffett indicator——The Buffett indicator (or the Buffett metric, or the Market …", "summary": "The Buffett indicator (or the Buffett metric, or the Market capitalization-to-GDP ratio) is a valuation multiple used to assess how expensive or cheap the aggregate stock market is at a given point in time.", "takeaways": ["It is widely followed by the financial media as a valuation measure for the US market in both its absolute, and de-trended forms.", "The indicator set an all-time high during the so-called \"everything bubble\", crossing the 200% level in February 2021; a level that Buffett warned if crossed, was \"playing with fire\"."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "QQQ", "AAPL"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buffett_indicator"},
    {"id": "sharpe-ratio", "level": "进阶", "category": "财务比率", "title": "Sharpe ratio——In finance, the Sharpe ratio (also known as the Sharpe index…", "summary": "In finance, the Sharpe ratio (also known as the Sharpe index, the Sharpe measure, and the reward-to-variability ratio) measures the performance of an investment such as a security or portfolio compared to a risk-free asset, after adjusting for its risk.", "takeaways": ["It is defined as the difference between the returns of the investment and the risk-free return, divided by the standard deviation of the investment re…", "It was named after William F.", "Sharpe, who developed it in 1966."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "QQQ", "AAPL"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sharpe_ratio"},
    {"id": "dcf-model", "level": "进阶", "category": "估值方法", "title": "Discounted cash flow——The discounted cash flow (DCF) analysis, in financial analys…", "summary": "The discounted cash flow (DCF) analysis, in financial analysis, is a method used to value a security, project, company, or asset, that incorporates the time value of money.", "takeaways": ["The discounted cash flow (DCF) analysis, in financial analysis, is a method used to value a security, project, company, or asset, that incorporates th…", "Terminal value often represents a large share of total value and is highly sensitive to growth and discount rate assumptions.", "courts began employing the concept in the 1980s and 1990s."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "BRK-B"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Discounted_cash_flow"},
    {"id": "intrinsic-value", "level": "进阶", "category": "估值方法", "title": "Intrinsic value (finance)——In finance, the intrinsic value of an asset or security is i…", "summary": "In finance, the intrinsic value of an asset or security is its value as calculated with regard to an inherent, objective measure. As a distinction, the asset's price is determined relative to other similar assets.", "takeaways": ["In finance, the intrinsic value of an asset or security is its value as calculated with regard to an inherent, objective measure.", "As a distinction, the asset's price is determined relative to other similar assets.", "The intrinsic approach to valuation may be somewhat simplified, in that it ignores elements other than the measure in question."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "BRK-B"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intrinsic_value_%28finance%29"},
    {"id": "wacc", "level": "进阶", "category": "估值方法", "title": "Weighted average cost of capital——The weighted average cost of capital (WACC) is the rate that…", "summary": "The weighted average cost of capital (WACC) is the rate that a company is expected to pay on average to all its security holders to finance its assets. The WACC is commonly referred to as the firm's cost of capital. Importantly, it is dictated by the external market and not by management.", "takeaways": ["The weighted average cost of capital (WACC) is the rate that a company is expected to pay on average to all its security holders to finance its assets…", "The WACC represents the minimum return that a company must earn on an existing asset base to satisfy its creditors, owners, and other providers of cap…", "Companies can use WACC to see if the investment projects available to them are worthwhile to undertake."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "BRK-B"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Weighted_average_cost_of_capital"},
    {"id": "capm", "level": "进阶", "category": "估值方法", "title": "Capital asset pricing model——In finance, the capital asset pricing model (CAPM) is a mode…", "summary": "In finance, the capital asset pricing model (CAPM) is a model used to determine a theoretically appropriate required rate of return of an asset, to make decisions about adding assets to a well-diversified portfolio.", "takeaways": ["了解Capital asset pricing model的基本定义和应用场景", "理解Capital asset pricing model在金融市场中的作用和影响", "结合市场数据观察Capital asset pricing model的实际表现"], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "BRK-B"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_asset_pricing_model"},
    {"id": "equity-risk-premium", "level": "进阶", "category": "估值方法", "title": "Equity premium puzzle——The equity premium puzzle refers to the inability of an impo…", "summary": "The equity premium puzzle refers to the inability of an important class of economic models to explain the average equity risk premium (ERP) provided by a diversified portfolio of equities over that of government bonds, which has been observed for more than 100 years.", "takeaways": ["There is a significant disparity between returns produced by stocks compared to returns produced by government treasury bills.", "It is equal to around 5% to 8% in the United States.", "However, the 5% to 8% premium is considered to be an implausibly high difference and the equity premium puzzle refers to the unexplained reasons drivi…"], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "BRK-B"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equity_risk_premium"},
    {"id": "dividend-discount-model", "level": "进阶", "category": "估值方法", "title": "Dividend discount model——In financial economics, the dividend discount model (DDM) is…", "summary": "In financial economics, the dividend discount model (DDM) is a method of valuing the price of a company's capital stock or business value based on the assertion that intrinsic value is determined by the sum of future cash flows from dividend payments to shareholders, discounted back to their present value.", "takeaways": ["The constant-growth form of the DDM is sometimes referred to as the Gordon growth model (GGM), after Myron J.", "g\n      \n    \n    {\\displaystyle g}\n  \n is the constant growth rate in perpetuity expected for the dividends.", "D\n          \n            1\n          \n        \n      \n    \n    {\\displaystyle D_{1}}\n  \n is the value of dividends at the end of the first period."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "BRK-B"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dividend_discount_model"},
    {"id": "comparable-company-analysis", "level": "进阶", "category": "估值方法", "title": "Valuation using multiples——In economics, valuation using multiples, or \"relative valuat…", "summary": "In economics, valuation using multiples, or \"relative valuation\", is a process that consists of: identifying comparable assets (the peer group) and obtaining market values for these assets.", "takeaways": ["In economics, valuation using multiples, or \"relative valuation\", is a process that consists of:\n\nidentifying comparable assets (the peer group) and o…", "Multiples analysis is one of the oldest methods of analysis.", "\"Comparable company analysis\",  closely related, was introduced by economists  at Harvard Business School in the 1930s."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "BRK-B"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Comparable_company_analysis"},
    {"id": "margin-of-safety", "level": "进阶", "category": "估值方法", "title": "Margin of safety (financial)——A margin of safety (or safety margin) is the difference betw…", "summary": "A margin of safety (or safety margin) is the difference between the intrinsic value of a stock and its market price. Another definition: In break-even analysis, from the discipline of accounting, margin of safety is how much output or sales level can fall before a business reaches its break-even point.", "takeaways": ["A margin of safety (or safety margin) is the difference between the intrinsic value of a stock and its market price.", "Another definition: In break-even analysis, from the discipline of accounting, margin of safety is how much output or sales level can fall before a business reaches its break-even point.", "Break-even point is a no-profit, no-loss scenario."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "BRK-B"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Margin_of_safety_%28financial%29"},
    {"id": "terminal-value", "level": "进阶", "category": "估值方法", "title": "Terminal value (finance)——In finance, the terminal value (also known as “continuing va…", "summary": "In finance, the terminal value (also known as “continuing value” or “horizon value” or \"TV\") of a security is the present value at a future point in time of all future cash flows when we expect stable growth rate forever.", "takeaways": ["It is most often used in multi-stage discounted cash flow analysis, and allows for the limitation of cash flow projections to a several-year period; see Forecast period (finance).", "The terminal value is calculated in accordance with a stream of projected future free cash flows in discounted cash flow analysis.", "For whole-company valuation purposes, there are two methodologies used to calculate the Terminal Value."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "BRK-B"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Terminal_value_%28finance%29"},
    {"id": "enterprise-value-to-revenue", "level": "进阶", "category": "估值方法", "title": "Enterprise value——Enterprise value (EV), total enterprise value (TEV), or firm…", "summary": "Enterprise value (EV), total enterprise value (TEV), or firm value (FV) is an economic measure reflecting the market value of a business (i.e. as distinct from market price). It is a sum of claims by all claimants: creditors (secured and unsecured) and shareholders (preferred and common).", "takeaways": ["Enterprise value (EV), total enterprise value (TEV), or firm value (FV) is an economic measure reflecting the market value of a business (i.e.", "Enterprise value is one of the fundamental metrics used in business valuation, financial analysis, accounting, portfolio analysis, and risk analysis.", "Therefore, financial analysts often use a comfortable range of EV in their calculations."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "BRK-B"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Enterprise_value"},
    {"id": "book-value", "level": "入门", "category": "估值方法", "title": "Book value——In accounting, book value (or carrying value) is the value o…", "summary": "In accounting, book value (or carrying value) is the value of an asset according to its balance sheet account balance. For assets, the value is based on the original cost of the asset less any depreciation, amortization or impairment costs made against the asset.", "takeaways": ["In accounting, book value (or carrying value) is the value of an asset according to its balance sheet account balance.", "However, in practice, depending on the source of the calculation, book value may variably include goodwill, intangible assets, or both.", "In the United Kingdom, the term net asset value may refer to the book value of a company."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "BRK-B"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_value"},
    {"id": "liquidation-value", "level": "进阶", "category": "估值方法", "title": "Liquidation value——Liquidation value is the likely price of an asset when it is…", "summary": "Liquidation value is the likely price of an asset when it is allowed insufficient time to sell on the open market, thereby reducing its exposure to potential buyers. Liquidation value is typically lower than fair market value.", "takeaways": ["Liquidation value is the likely price of an asset when it is allowed insufficient time to sell on the open market, thereby reducing its exposure to po…", "The seller is under extreme compulsion to sell.", "The price represents the normal consideration for the property sold, unaffected by special or creative financing or sales concessions granted by anyon…"], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "BRK-B"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Liquidation_value"},
    {"id": "replacement-cost", "level": "进阶", "category": "估值方法", "title": "Replacement value——The term replacement cost or replacement value is the amount…", "summary": "The term replacement cost or replacement value is the amount that an entity would have to pay to replace an asset (in undamaged condition) at current market prices. In the insurance industry, \"replacement cost\" or \"replacement cost value\" is one of several methods of determining the value of an insured item.", "takeaways": ["The term replacement cost or replacement value is the amount that an entity would have to pay to replace an asset (in undamaged condition) at current …", "To the extent that the carrier has knowingly or carelessly sold excessive  (i.e.", "One of the champions of the replacement cost method was the Dutch professor in Business economics Théodore Limperg."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "BRK-B"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Replacement_value"},
    {"id": "sum-of-parts", "level": "进阶", "category": "估值方法", "title": "Sum-of-the-parts analysis——Sum of the parts analysis (SOTP), or break-up analysis, is a…", "summary": "Sum of the parts analysis (SOTP), or break-up analysis, is a method of valuation of a multi-divisional company, holding company, or a conglomerate. The essence of the method is to determine what divisions would be worth if the conglomerate is broken up and spun off or acquired by another company; see Conglomerate…", "takeaways": ["Sum of the parts analysis (SOTP), or break-up analysis, is a method of valuation of a multi-divisional company, holding company, or a conglomerate.", "The analysis calculates a range of values for a conglomerate's equity by summing the value of its individual business segments or divisions to get the…", "The equity value is then calculated by subtracting net debt and other non-operating adjustments."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "BRK-B"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sum-of-the-parts_analysis"},
    {"id": "residual-income-model", "level": "进阶", "category": "估值方法", "title": "Residual income valuation——Residual income valuation (RIV), also called the residual in…", "summary": "Residual income valuation (RIV), also called the residual income model or residual income method (RIM), is an approach to equity valuation that formally accounts for the cost of equity capital.", "takeaways": ["Residual income valuation (RIV), also called the residual income model or residual income method (RIM), is an approach to equity valuation that formally accounts for the cost of equity capital.", "The approach is largely analogous to the EVA/MVA based approach, with similar logic and advantages."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "BRK-B"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Residual_income_valuation"},
    {"id": "technical-analysis", "level": "入门", "category": "技术分析", "title": "Technical analysis——In finance, technical analysis is an analysis methodology fo…", "summary": "In finance, technical analysis is an analysis methodology for analysing and forecasting the direction of prices through the study of past market data, primarily price and volume. As a type of active management, it stands in contradiction to much of modern portfolio theory.", "takeaways": ["In finance, technical analysis is an analysis methodology for analysing and forecasting the direction of prices through the study of past market data, primarily price and volume.", "As a type of active management, it stands in contradiction to much of modern portfolio theory.", "It is distinguished from fundamental analysis, which considers a company's financial statements, health, and the overall state of the market and economy."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Technical_analysis"},
    {"id": "dow-theory", "level": "入门", "category": "技术分析", "title": "Dow theory——The Dow theory on stock price movement is the precursor to t…", "summary": "The Dow theory on stock price movement is the precursor to technical analysis and is also part of modern technical analysis. The theory was derived from 255 editorials in The Wall Street Journal written by Charles H.", "takeaways": ["The Dow theory on stock price movement is the precursor to technical analysis and is also part of modern technical analysis.", "Following Dow's death,  William Peter Hamilton, Robert Rhea and E.", "The six basic tenets of Dow theory as summarized by Hamilton, Rhea, and Schaefer are described below."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dow_theory"},
    {"id": "elliott-wave", "level": "进阶", "category": "技术分析", "title": "Elliott wave principle——The Elliott wave principle, or Elliott wave theory, is a for…", "summary": "The Elliott wave principle, or Elliott wave theory, is a form of technical analysis that helps financial traders analyze market cycles and forecast market trends by identifying extremes in investor psychology and price levels, such as highs and lows, by looking for patterns in prices.", "takeaways": ["了解Elliott wave principle的基本定义和应用场景", "理解Elliott wave principle在金融市场中的作用和影响", "结合市场数据观察Elliott wave principle的实际表现"], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elliott_wave_principle"},
    {"id": "moving-average", "level": "入门", "category": "技术分析", "title": "Moving average——In statistics, a moving average (rolling average or running …", "summary": "In statistics, a moving average (rolling average or running average or moving mean or rolling mean) is a calculation to analyze data points by creating a series of averages of different selections of the full data set. Variations include: simple, cumulative, or weighted forms.", "takeaways": ["Variations include: simple, cumulative, or weighted forms.", "Given a series of numbers and a fixed subset size, the first element of the moving average is obtained by taking the average of the initial fixed subs…", "Viewed simplistically it can be regarded as smoothing the data."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moving_average"},
    {"id": "death-cross", "level": "入门", "category": "技术分析", "title": "Moving average crossover——In the statistics of time series, and in particular the stoc…", "summary": "In the statistics of time series, and in particular the stock market technical analysis, a moving-average crossover occurs when, on plotting two moving averages each based on different degrees of smoothing, the traces of these moving averages cross. It does not predict future direction but shows trends.", "takeaways": ["It does not predict future direction but shows trends.", "A crossover occurs when a faster moving average (i.e., a shorter period moving average) crosses a slower moving average (i.e.", "Death cross is not a reliable indicator of future market declines."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Death_cross"},
    {"id": "bollinger-bands", "level": "进阶", "category": "技术分析", "title": "Bollinger Bands——Bollinger Bands () are a type of statistical chart character…", "summary": "Bollinger Bands () are a type of statistical chart characterizing the prices and volatility over time of a financial instrument or commodity, using a formulaic method propounded by John Bollinger in the 1980s.", "takeaways": ["Financial traders employ these charts as a methodical tool to inform trading decisions, control automated trading systems, or as a component of techni…", "The default choice for the average is a simple moving average, but other types of averages can be employed as needed.", "Bollinger registered the words \"Bollinger Bands\" as a U.S."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bollinger_Bands"},
    {"id": "macd", "level": "进阶", "category": "技术分析", "title": "MACD——The Moving Average Convergence Divergence (MACD) is a tradin…", "summary": "The Moving Average Convergence Divergence (MACD) is a trading indicator used in technical analysis of securities prices, created by Gerald Appel in the late 1970s. It is designed to reveal changes in the strength, direction, momentum, and duration of a trend in a stock's price.", "takeaways": ["The Moving Average Convergence Divergence (MACD) is a trading indicator used in technical analysis of securities prices, created by Gerald Appel in th…", "As true with most of the technical indicators, MACD also finds its period settings from the old days when technical analysis used to be mainly based o…", "Hence the trends will already be completed or almost done by the time MACD shows the trend."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MACD"},
    {"id": "rsi-indicator", "level": "进阶", "category": "技术分析", "title": "Relative strength index——The relative strength index (RSI) is a technical indicator u…", "summary": "The relative strength index (RSI) is a technical indicator used in the analysis of financial markets. It is intended to chart the current and historical strength or weakness of a stock or market based on the closing prices of a recent trading period. The indicator should not be confused with relative strength.", "takeaways": ["The relative strength index (RSI) is a technical indicator used in the analysis of financial markets.", "The RSI is most typically used on a 14-day timeframe, measured on a scale from 0 to 100, with high and low levels marked at 70 and 30, respectively.", "RSI with recommended parameters and its day-to-day optimization was tested and compared with other strategies in Marek and Šedivá (2017)."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Relative_strength_index"},
    {"id": "stochastic-oscillator", "level": "进阶", "category": "技术分析", "title": "Stochastic oscillator——Stochastic oscillator is a momentum indicator within technic…", "summary": "Stochastic oscillator is a momentum indicator within technical analysis that uses support and resistance levels as an oscillator. George Lane developed this indicator in the late 1950s. The term stochastic refers to the point of a current price in relation to its price range over a period of time.", "takeaways": ["Stochastic oscillator is a momentum indicator within technical analysis that uses support and resistance levels as an oscillator.", "This method attempts to predict price turning points by comparing the closing price of a security to its price range.", "There is only one valid signal in working with %D alone — a divergence between %D and the analyzed security."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stochastic_oscillator"},
    {"id": "average-directional-index", "level": "进阶", "category": "技术分析", "title": "Average directional movement index——The average directional movement index (ADX) was developed i…", "summary": "The average directional movement index (ADX) was developed in 1978 by J. Welles Wilder as an indicator of trend strength in a series of prices of a financial instrument.", "takeaways": ["The average directional movement index (ADX) was developed in 1978 by J.", "Welles Wilder as an indicator of trend strength in a series of prices of a financial instrument.", "ADX has become a widely used indicator for technical analysts, and is provided as a standard in collections of indicators offered by various trading platforms."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Average_directional_movement_index"},
    {"id": "atr", "level": "进阶", "category": "技术分析", "title": "Average true range——Average true range (ATR) is a technical analysis volatility …", "summary": "Average true range (ATR) is a technical analysis volatility indicator originally developed by J. Welles Wilder, Jr. for commodities. The indicator does not provide an indication of price trend, simply the degree of price volatility.", "takeaways": ["Average true range (ATR) is a technical analysis volatility indicator originally developed by J.", "The average true range is an N-period smoothed moving average (SMMA) of the true range values.", "Wilder recommended a 14-period smoothing."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Average_true_range"},
    {"id": "obv", "level": "进阶", "category": "技术分析", "title": "On-balance volume——On-balance volume (OBV) is a technical analysis indicator in…", "summary": "On-balance volume (OBV) is a technical analysis indicator intended to relate price and volume in the stock market. OBV is based on a cumulative total volume.", "takeaways": ["On-balance volume (OBV) is a technical analysis indicator intended to relate price and volume in the stock market.", "OBV is based on a cumulative total volume."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/On-balance_volume"},
    {"id": "ichimoku-cloud", "level": "进阶", "category": "技术分析", "title": "Ichimoku Kinkō Hyō——Ichimoku Kinko Hyo (IKH) (Japanese: 一目均衡表, Hepburn: Ichimoku…", "summary": "Ichimoku Kinko Hyo (IKH) (Japanese: 一目均衡表, Hepburn: Ichimoku Kinkō Hyō), usually shortened to \"Ichimoku\", is a technical analysis method that builds on candlestick charting in an attempt to improve the accuracy of forecast price moves. The chart plots five lines based on recent highs, lows, and closes.", "takeaways": ["The chart plots five lines based on recent highs, lows, and closes.", "Two of the lines create a cloud like image on the chart which gives the technique its name.", "This method is applied across various asset classes and have been used by traders to predict price movements and regime shifts in global markets."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ichimoku_Kink%C5%8D_Hy%C5%8D"},
    {"id": "fibonacci-retracement", "level": "进阶", "category": "技术分析", "title": "Fibonacci retracement——In finance, Fibonacci retracement is a method of technical a…", "summary": "In finance, Fibonacci retracement is a method of technical analysis for determining support and resistance levels. It is named after the Fibonacci sequence of numbers, whose ratios provide price levels to which markets tend to retrace a portion of a move, before a trend continues in the original direction.", "takeaways": ["In finance, Fibonacci retracement is a method of technical analysis for determining support and resistance levels.", "Horizontal lines are drawn in the chart for these price levels to provide support and resistance levels.", "The appearance of retracement can be ascribed to price volatility as described by Burton Malkiel, a Princeton economist in his book A Random Walk Down…"], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_retracement"},
    {"id": "support-and-resistance", "level": "入门", "category": "技术分析", "title": "Support and resistance——In stock market technical analysis, support and resistance a…", "summary": "In stock market technical analysis, support and resistance are certain predetermined levels of the price of a security at which it is thought that the price will tend to stop and reverse. These levels are denoted by multiple touches of price without a breakthrough of the level.", "takeaways": ["In stock market technical analysis, support and resistance are certain predetermined levels of the price of a security at which it is thought that the price will tend to stop and reverse.", "These levels are denoted by multiple touches of price without a breakthrough of the level."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Support_and_resistance"},
    {"id": "head-and-shoulders", "level": "进阶", "category": "技术分析", "title": "Head and shoulders (chart pattern)——On the technical analysis chart, the head and shoulders form…", "summary": "On the technical analysis chart, the head and shoulders formation occurs when a market trend is in the process of reversal either from a bullish or bearish trend; a characteristic pattern takes shape and is recognized as reversal formation.", "takeaways": ["了解Head and shoulders (chart pattern)的基本定义和应用场景", "理解Head and shoulders (chart pattern)在金融市场中的作用和影响", "结合市场数据观察Head and shoulders (chart pattern)的实际表现"], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Head_and_shoulders_%28chart_pattern%29"},
    {"id": "double-top", "level": "进阶", "category": "技术分析", "title": "Double top and double bottom——Double top and double bottom are reversal chart patterns obs…", "summary": "Double top and double bottom are reversal chart patterns observed in the technical analysis of financial trading markets of stocks, commodities, currencies, and other assets.", "takeaways": ["了解Double top and double bottom的基本定义和应用场景", "理解Double top and double bottom在金融市场中的作用和影响", "结合市场数据观察Double top and double bottom的实际表现"], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Double_top_and_double_bottom"},
    {"id": "triangle-pattern", "level": "进阶", "category": "技术分析", "title": "Triangle (chart pattern)——Triangles within technical analysis are chart patterns commo…", "summary": "Triangles within technical analysis are chart patterns commonly found in the price charts of financially traded assets (stocks, bonds, futures, etc.). The pattern derives its name from the fact that it is characterized by a contraction in price range and converging trend lines, thus giving it a triangular shape.", "takeaways": ["Triangles within technical analysis are chart patterns commonly found in the price charts of financially traded assets (stocks, bonds, futures, etc.).", "Triangle patterns can be broken down into three categories: the ascending triangle, the descending triangle, and the symmetrical triangle.", "Lastly, while triangles can sometimes be reversal patterns—meaning a reversal of the prior trend—they are normally seen as continuation patterns (mean…"], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Triangle_%28chart_pattern%29"},
    {"id": "flag-pattern", "level": "进阶", "category": "技术分析", "title": "Flag and pennant patterns——The flag and pennant patterns are commonly found patterns in…", "summary": "The flag and pennant patterns are commonly found patterns in the price charts of financially traded assets (stocks, bonds, futures, etc.). The patterns are characterized by a clear direction of the price trend, followed by a consolidation and rangebound movement, which is then followed by a resumption of the trend.", "takeaways": ["The flag and pennant patterns are commonly found patterns in the price charts of financially traded assets (stocks, bonds, futures, etc.).", "The patterns are characterized by a clear direction of the price trend, followed by a consolidation and rangebound movement, which is then followed by a resumption of the trend.", "They are continuation patterns and form when the asset prices rally or fall sharply."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flag_and_pennant_patterns"},
    {"id": "cup-and-handle", "level": "进阶", "category": "技术分析", "title": "Cup and handle——In the domain of technical analysis of market prices, a cup …", "summary": "In the domain of technical analysis of market prices, a cup and handle or cup with handle formation is a chart pattern consisting of a drop in the price and a rise back up to the original value, followed first by a smaller drop and then a rise past the previous peak.", "takeaways": ["It is interpreted as an indication of bullish sentiment in the market and possible further price increases.", "The drop of the handle part should retrace about 30% to 50% of the rise at the end of the cup.", "The \"cup and handle\" formation was defined by William O'Neil\""], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cup_and_handle"},
    {"id": "candlestick-pattern", "level": "入门", "category": "技术分析", "title": "Candlestick pattern——In financial technical analysis, a candlestick pattern is a …", "summary": "In financial technical analysis, a candlestick pattern is a movement in prices shown graphically on a candlestick chart that some believe can help to identify repeating patterns of a particular market movement.", "takeaways": ["The recognition of the pattern is subjective and programs that are used for charting have to rely on predefined rules to match the pattern.", "There are 42 recognized patterns that can be split into simple and complex patterns."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Candlestick_pattern"},
    {"id": "doji", "level": "进阶", "category": "技术分析", "title": "Doji——The doji (Japanese: どうじ 同事; lit. 'same matter') is a commonl…", "summary": "The doji (Japanese: どうじ 同事; lit. 'same matter') is a commonly found pattern in a candlestick chart of financially traded assets (stocks, bonds, futures, etc.) in technical analysis. A Doji forms when the open and close of a candlestick are equal, or very close to equal.", "takeaways": ["The doji (Japanese: どうじ 同事; lit.", "Length of upper and lower shadows (wicks and tails) may vary giving the appearance of a plus sign, cross, or inverted cross.", "A doji is not as significant if the market is not clearly trending, as non-trending markets are inherently indicative of indecision."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Doji"},
    {"id": "hammer-candlestick", "level": "进阶", "category": "技术分析", "title": "Candlestick pattern——In financial technical analysis, a candlestick pattern is a …", "summary": "In financial technical analysis, a candlestick pattern is a movement in prices shown graphically on a candlestick chart that some believe can help to identify repeating patterns of a particular market movement.", "takeaways": ["The recognition of the pattern is subjective and programs that are used for charting have to rely on predefined rules to match the pattern.", "There are 42 recognized patterns that can be split into simple and complex patterns."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hammer_%28candlestick_pattern%29"},
    {"id": "volume-analysis", "level": "入门", "category": "技术分析", "title": "Volume (finance)——In capital markets, volume, or trading volume, is the amount…", "summary": "In capital markets, volume, or trading volume, is the amount (total number) of a security (or a given set of securities, or an entire market) that was traded during a given period of time.", "takeaways": ["In capital markets, volume, or trading volume, is the amount (total number) of a security (or a given set of securities, or an entire market) that was…", "The average volume of a security over a longer period of time is the total amount traded in that period, divided by the length of the period.", "Higher trading volumes are considered more positive than lower trading volumes because they mean more liquidity and better order execution."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volume_%28finance%29"},
    {"id": "vwap", "level": "进阶", "category": "技术分析", "title": "Volume-weighted average price——In finance, volume-weighted average price (VWAP) is the rati…", "summary": "In finance, volume-weighted average price (VWAP) is the ratio of the total value traded in a security to the total volume of transactions over a defined period, typically a single trading session.", "takeaways": ["In finance, volume-weighted average price (VWAP) is the ratio of the total value traded in a security to the total volume of transactions over a defined period, typically a single trading session.", "It is a measure of the average price at which the security has traded during that period, weighted by transaction size, and is used both as an execution benchmark and as a technical indicator."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volume-weighted_average_price"},
    {"id": "point-and-figure", "level": "进阶", "category": "技术分析", "title": "Point and figure chart——Point and figure (P&F) is a charting technique used in techn…", "summary": "Point and figure (P&F) is a charting technique used in technical analysis. Point and figure charting does not plot price against time as time-based charts do. Instead it plots price against changes in direction by plotting a column of Xs as the price rises and a column of Os as the price falls.", "takeaways": ["Point and figure (P&F) is a charting technique used in technical analysis.", "Point and figure charting does not plot price against time as time-based charts do.", "Instead it plots price against changes in direction by plotting a column of Xs as the price rises and a column of Os as the price falls."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Point_and_figure_chart"},
    {"id": "renko-chart", "level": "进阶", "category": "技术分析", "title": "Renko chart——A Renko chart (Japanese: 練行足, romanized: renkōashi, also wri…", "summary": "A Renko chart (Japanese: 練行足, romanized: renkōashi, also written 練り足 neriashi) is a type of financial chart of Japanese origin used in technical analysis that measures and plots price changes.", "takeaways": ["A Renko chart (Japanese: 練行足, romanized: renkōashi, also written 練り足 neriashi) is a type of financial chart of Japanese origin used in technical analysis that measures and plots price changes.", "A renko chart consists of bricks (煉瓦, renga), which proponents say more clearly show market trends and increase the signal-to-noise ratio compared to typical candlestick charts."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Renko_chart"},
    {"id": "heikin-ashi", "level": "进阶", "category": "技术分析", "title": "Candlestick chart——A candlestick chart (also called Japanese candlestick chart …", "summary": "A candlestick chart (also called Japanese candlestick chart or K-line) is a style of financial chart used to describe price movements of a security, derivative, or currency.", "takeaways": ["A candlestick chart (also called Japanese candlestick chart or K-line) is a style of financial chart used to describe price movements of a security, d…", "Candlestick charts are most often used in technical analysis of equity and currency price patterns.", "They are visually similar to box plots, though box plots show different information."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heikin-Ashi"},
    {"id": "pivot-point", "level": "进阶", "category": "技术分析", "title": "Pivot point (technical analysis)——In financial markets, a pivot point is a price level that is…", "summary": "In financial markets, a pivot point is a price level that is used by traders as a possible indicator of market movement. A pivot point is calculated as an average of significant prices (high, low, close) from the performance of a market in the prior trading period.", "takeaways": ["In financial markets, a pivot point is a price level  that is used by traders as a possible indicator of market movement.", "A pivot point and the associated support and resistance levels are often turning points for the direction of price movement in a market.", "In a declining market, a pivot point and the support levels may represent a low price level of stability or a resistance to further decline."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pivot_point_%28technical_analysis%29"},
    {"id": "parabolic-sar", "level": "进阶", "category": "技术分析", "title": "Parabolic SAR——In stock and securities market technical analysis, parabolic…", "summary": "In stock and securities market technical analysis, parabolic SAR (parabolic stop and reverse) is a method devised by J. Welles Wilder Jr., to find potential reversals in the market price direction of traded goods such as securities or currency exchanges such as forex.", "takeaways": ["In stock and securities market technical analysis, parabolic SAR (parabolic stop and reverse) is a method devised by J.", "Thus, unless a security can continue to generate more profits over time, it should be liquidated.", "A parabola below the price may be used as support, whereas a parabola above the price may represent resistance."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "AAPL", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parabolic_SAR"},
    {"id": "derivative-basics", "level": "入门", "category": "衍生品", "title": "Derivative (finance)——In finance, a derivative is a contract between a buyer and a…", "summary": "In finance, a derivative is a contract between a buyer and a seller. The derivative can take various forms, depending on the transaction, but every derivative has the following four elements: an item (the \"underlier\") that can or must be bought or sold, a future act which must occur (such as a sale or purchase of the…", "takeaways": ["In finance, a derivative is a contract between a buyer and a seller.", "Derivatives can be used to protect lenders against the risk of borrowers defaulting on an obligation.", "Bucket shops, outlawed in 1936 in the US, are a more recent historical example."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "^VIX", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Derivative_%28finance%29"},
    {"id": "option-basics", "level": "入门", "category": "衍生品", "title": "Option (finance)——In finance, an option is a contract which conveys to its own…", "summary": "In finance, an option is a contract which conveys to its owner, the holder, the right, but not the obligation, to buy or sell a specific quantity of an underlying asset or instrument at a specified strike price on or before a specified date, depending on the style of the option.", "takeaways": ["Options are typically acquired by purchase, as a form of compensation, or as part of a complex financial transaction.", "Options may be traded between private parties in over-the-counter (OTC) transactions, or they may be exchange-traded in live, public markets in the form of standardized contracts."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "^VIX", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Option_%28finance%29"},
    {"id": "call-option", "level": "入门", "category": "衍生品", "title": "Call option——In finance, a call option (often simply a \"call\") is an opti…", "summary": "In finance, a call option (often simply a \"call\") is an option contract that gives its buyer the right, but not the obligation, to buy an agreed quantity of a particular commodity, security, or other financial instrument from the seller at a specified price.", "takeaways": ["The asset or instrument to which the option relates is known as the underlying, and the specified purchase price is known as the strike price.", "The buyer pays the seller a premium for this right.", "The term \"call\" comes from the fact that the owner has the right to \"call the stock away\" from the seller."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "^VIX", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Call_option"},
    {"id": "put-option", "level": "入门", "category": "衍生品", "title": "Put option——In finance, a put or put option is a derivative instrument i…", "summary": "In finance, a put or put option is a derivative instrument in financial markets that gives the holder (i.e. the purchaser of the put option) the right to sell an asset (the underlying), at a specified price (the strike), by (or on) a specified date (the expiry or maturity) to the writer (i.e. seller) of the put.", "takeaways": ["In finance, a put or put option is a derivative instrument in financial markets that gives the holder (i.e.", "Put options are most commonly used in the stock market to protect against a fall in the price of a stock below a specified price.", "Another use is for speculation: an investor can take a short position in the underlying stock without trading in it directly."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "^VIX", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Put_option"},
    {"id": "strike-price", "level": "入门", "category": "衍生品", "title": "Strike price——In finance, the strike price (or exercise price) of an optio…", "summary": "In finance, the strike price (or exercise price) of an option is a fixed price at which the owner of the option can buy (in the case of a call), or sell (in the case of a put), the underlying security or commodity.", "takeaways": ["The strike price may be set by reference to the spot price, which is the market price of the underlying security or commodity on the day an option is …", "The strike price is a key variable in a derivatives contract between two parties.", "Where the contract requires delivery of the underlying instrument, the trade will be at the strike price, regardless of the market price of the underl…"], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "^VIX", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Strike_price"},
    {"id": "expiration-date", "level": "入门", "category": "衍生品", "title": "Expiration (options)——In finance, the expiration date of an option contract (repre…", "summary": "In finance, the expiration date of an option contract (represented by Greek letter tau, τ) is the last date on which the holder of the option may exercise it according to its terms.", "takeaways": ["In finance, the expiration date of an option contract (represented by Greek letter tau, τ) is the last date on which the holder of the option may exer…", "However, the holder or the holder's broker may request that the options are not exercised automatically.", "Upon expiration any margin charged held by the clearing firm of the holder or writer of the option is released back to the free balance of the trader'…"], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "^VIX", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Expiration_%28options%29"},
    {"id": "option-premium", "level": "入门", "category": "衍生品", "title": "Valuation of options——In finance, a price (premium) is paid or received for purcha…", "summary": "In finance, a price (premium) is paid or received for purchasing or selling options. The calculation of this premium will require sophisticated mathematics.", "takeaways": ["In finance, a price (premium) is paid or received for purchasing or selling options.", "The calculation of this premium will require sophisticated mathematics."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "^VIX", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Option_premium"},
    {"id": "in-the-money", "level": "入门", "category": "衍生品", "title": "Moneyness——In finance, moneyness is the relative position of the curren…", "summary": "In finance, moneyness is the relative position of the current price (or future price) of an underlying asset (e.g., a stock) with respect to the strike price of a derivative, most commonly a call option or a put option.", "takeaways": ["There are two slightly different definitions, according to whether one uses the current price (spot) or future price (forward), specified as \"at the m…", "A particularly important measure of moneyness is the likelihood that the derivative will expire in the money, in the risk-neutral measure.", "There are other proxies for moneyness, with convention depending on market."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "^VIX", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moneyness"},
    {"id": "intrinsic-value-option", "level": "进阶", "category": "衍生品", "title": "Intrinsic value (finance)——In finance, the intrinsic value of an asset or security is i…", "summary": "In finance, the intrinsic value of an asset or security is its value as calculated with regard to an inherent, objective measure. As a distinction, the asset's price is determined relative to other similar assets.", "takeaways": ["In finance, the intrinsic value of an asset or security is its value as calculated with regard to an inherent, objective measure.", "As a distinction, the asset's price is determined relative to other similar assets.", "The intrinsic approach to valuation may be somewhat simplified, in that it ignores elements other than the measure in question."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "^VIX", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intrinsic_value_%28finance%29"},
    {"id": "time-value-option", "level": "进阶", "category": "衍生品", "title": "Option time value——In finance, the time value (TV) (extrinsic or instrumental v…", "summary": "In finance, the time value (TV) (extrinsic or instrumental value) of an option is the premium a rational investor would pay over its current exercise value (intrinsic value), based on the probability it will increase in value before expiry.", "takeaways": ["For an American option this value is always greater than zero in a fair market, thus an option is always worth more than its current exercise value.", "Time value decays to zero at expiration, with a general rule that it will lose 1⁄3 of its value during the first half of its life and 2⁄3 in the secon…", "As an option moves closer to expiry, moving its price requires an increasingly larger move in the price of the underlying security."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "^VIX", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Option_time_value"},
    {"id": "delta-option", "level": "进阶", "category": "衍生品", "title": "Greeks (finance)——In mathematical finance, the Greeks are the quantities (know…", "summary": "In mathematical finance, the Greeks are the quantities (known in calculus as partial derivatives; first-order or higher) representing the sensitivity of the price of a derivative instrument such as an option to changes in one or more underlying parameters on which the value of an instrument or portfolio of financial…", "takeaways": ["The name is used because the most common of these sensitivities are denoted by Greek letters (as are some other finance measures).", "Collectively these have also been called the risk sensitivities, risk measures or hedge parameters."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "^VIX", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greeks_%28finance%29"},
