    {"id": "implied-volatility", "level": "进阶", "category": "衍生品", "title": "Implied volatility——In financial mathematics, the implied volatility (IV) of an …", "summary": "In financial mathematics, the implied volatility (IV) of an option contract is that value of the volatility of the underlying instrument which, when input in an option pricing model (usually Black–Scholes), will return a theoretical value equal to the price of the option.", "takeaways": ["A non-option financial instrument that has embedded optionality, such as an interest rate cap, can also have an implied volatility.", "Implied volatility is also used as a predictor in models that forecast future realized volatility.", "To understand where implied volatility stands in terms of the underlying, implied volatility rank is used to understand its implied volatility from a …"], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "^VIX", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Implied_volatility"},
    {"id": "volatility-smile", "level": "进阶", "category": "衍生品", "title": "Volatility smile——Volatility smiles are implied volatility patterns that arise…", "summary": "Volatility smiles are implied volatility patterns that arise in pricing financial options. It is a parameter (implied volatility) that needs to be modified for the Black–Scholes formula to fit market prices.", "takeaways": ["Volatility smiles are implied volatility patterns that arise in pricing financial options.", "It is believed that investor reassessments of the probabilities of fat-tail have led to higher prices for out-of-the-money options.", "An implied volatility surface is a 3-D plot that plots volatility smile and term structure of volatility in a consolidated three-dimensional surface f…"], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "^VIX", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volatility_smile"},
    {"id": "covered-call", "level": "进阶", "category": "衍生品", "title": "Covered option——A covered option is a financial transaction in which the hol…", "summary": "A covered option is a financial transaction in which the holder of securities sells (or \"writes\") a type of financial options contract known as a \"call\" or a \"put\" against stock that they own or are shorting.", "takeaways": ["One covered option is sold for every hundred shares the seller wishes to cover.", "A covered option constructed with a call is called a \"covered call\", while one constructed with a put is a \"covered put\".", "This strategy is generally considered conservative because the seller of a covered option reduces both their risk and their return."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "^VIX", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Covered_call"},
    {"id": "protective-put", "level": "进阶", "category": "衍生品", "title": "Protective option——A protective option or married option is a financial transac…", "summary": "A protective option or married option is a financial transaction in which the holder of securities buys a type of financial options contract known as a \"call\" or a \"put\" against stock that they own or are shorting.", "takeaways": ["The buyer of a protective option pays compensation, or \"premium\", for this transaction, which can limit losses on their stock position.", "In equilibrium, a protective put will have the same net payoff as merely buying a call option, and a protective call will have the same net payoff as …", "A protective option could be used instead of a stop-loss order to limit losses on a stock position, especially in a fast-moving market."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "^VIX", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Protective_put"},
    {"id": "bull-spread", "level": "进阶", "category": "衍生品", "title": "Bull spread——In options trading, a bull spread is a vertical spread optio…", "summary": "In options trading, a bull spread is a vertical spread options strategy that is designed to profit from a moderate rise in the price of the underlying security. Because of put–call parity, a bull spread can be constructed using either put options or call options.", "takeaways": ["In options trading, a bull spread is a vertical spread options strategy that is designed to profit from a moderate rise in the price of the underlying…", "If constructed using calls, it is a bull call spread (alternatively call debit spread).", "If constructed using puts, it is a bull put spread (alternatively put credit spread)."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "^VIX", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bull_spread"},
    {"id": "bear-spread", "level": "进阶", "category": "衍生品", "title": "Bear spread——In options trading, a bear spread is a bearish, vertical spr…", "summary": "In options trading, a bear spread is a bearish, vertical spread options strategy that can be used when the options trader is moderately bearish on the underlying security. Because of put–call parity, a bear spread can be constructed using either put options or call options.", "takeaways": ["In options trading, a bear spread is a bearish, vertical spread options strategy that can be used when the options trader is moderately bearish on the…", "If constructed using calls, it is a bear call spread (alternatively call credit spread).", "If constructed using puts, it is a bear put spread (alternatively put debit spread)."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "^VIX", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bear_spread"},
    {"id": "straddle-option", "level": "进阶", "category": "衍生品", "title": "Straddle——In finance, a straddle strategy involves two transactions in…", "summary": "In finance, a straddle strategy involves two transactions in options on the same underlying, with opposite positions. One holds long risk, the other short. As a result, it involves the purchase or sale of particular option derivatives that allow the holder to profit based on how much the price of the underlying…", "takeaways": ["In finance, a straddle strategy involves two transactions in options on the same underlying, with opposite positions.", "If the stock price is close to the strike price at expiration of the options, the straddle leads to a loss.", "A straddle is appropriate when an investor is expecting a large move in a stock price but does not know in which direction the move will be."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "^VIX", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Straddle"},
    {"id": "strangle-option", "level": "进阶", "category": "衍生品", "title": "Strangle (options)——In finance, a strangle is an options strategy involving the …", "summary": "In finance, a strangle is an options strategy involving the purchase or sale of two options, allowing the holder to profit based on how much the price of the underlying security moves, with a neutral exposure to the direction of price movement.", "takeaways": ["A strangle consists of one call and one put with the same expiry and underlying but different strike prices.", "If the options are purchased, the position is known as a long strangle, while if the options are sold, it is known as a short strangle.", "Given the same underlying security, strangle positions can be constructed with a lower cost but lower probability of profit than straddles."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "^VIX", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Strangle_%28options%29"},
    {"id": "iron-condor", "level": "进阶", "category": "衍生品", "title": "Iron condor——The iron condor is an options trading strategy utilizing two…", "summary": "The iron condor is an options trading strategy utilizing two vertical spreads – a put spread and a call spread with the same expiration and four different strikes.", "takeaways": ["The iron condor is an options trading strategy utilizing two vertical spreads – a put spread and a call spread with the same expiration and four diffe…", "Traders often refer to the inner options collectively as the \"body\" and the outer options as the \"wings\".", "This can significantly improve the potential rate of return on capital risked when the trader doesn't expect the underlying instrument's spot price to…"], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "^VIX", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iron_condor"},
    {"id": "butterfly-spread", "level": "进阶", "category": "衍生品", "title": "Butterfly (options)——In finance, a butterfly (or simply fly) is a limited risk, n…", "summary": "In finance, a butterfly (or simply fly) is a limited risk, non-directional options strategy that is designed to have a high probability of earning a limited profit when the future volatility of the underlying asset is expected to be lower (when long the butterfly) or higher (when short the butterfly) than that asset's…", "takeaways": ["了解Butterfly (options)的基本定义和应用场景", "理解Butterfly (options)在金融市场中的作用和影响", "结合市场数据观察Butterfly (options)的实际表现"], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "^VIX", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Butterfly_%28options%29"},
    {"id": "futures-contract", "level": "入门", "category": "衍生品", "title": "Futures contract——In finance, a futures contract (often just called a future) …", "summary": "In finance, a futures contract (often just called a future) is a standardized legal contract to buy or sell something at a predetermined price for delivery at a specified time in the future, between parties not yet known to each other. The item transacted is usually a commodity or financial instrument.", "takeaways": ["The item transacted is usually a commodity or financial instrument.", "For example, in gold futures trading, the margin varies between 2% and 20% depending on the volatility of the spot market.", "The original use of futures contracts mitigates the risk of price or exchange rate movements by allowing parties to fix prices or rates in advance for…"], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "^VIX", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Futures_contract"},
    {"id": "initial-margin", "level": "入门", "category": "衍生品", "title": "Margin (finance)——In finance, margin is the collateral that a holder of a fina…", "summary": "In finance, margin is the collateral that a holder of a financial instrument has to deposit with a counterparty (most often a broker or an exchange) to cover some or all of the credit risk the holder poses for the counterparty.", "takeaways": ["The collateral for a margin account can be the cash deposited in the account or securities provided, and represents the funds available to the account holder for further share trading.", "On United States futures exchanges, margins were formerly called performance bonds."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "^VIX", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Initial_margin"},
    {"id": "mark-to-market", "level": "入门", "category": "衍生品", "title": "Mark-to-market accounting——Mark-to-market (MTM or M2M) or fair value accounting is acco…", "summary": "Mark-to-market (MTM or M2M) or fair value accounting is accounting for the \"fair value\" of an asset or liability based on the current market price, or the price for similar assets and liabilities, or based on another objectively assessed \"fair\" value.", "takeaways": ["Fair value accounting has been a part of Generally Accepted Accounting Principles (GAAP) in the United States since the early 1990s.", "In contrast, historical cost accounting, based on the past transactions, is simpler, more stable, and easier to perform, but does not represent curren…", "Mark-to-market accounting can become volatile if market prices fluctuate greatly or change unpredictably."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "^VIX", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mark-to-market_accounting"},
    {"id": "swap-derivative", "level": "进阶", "category": "衍生品", "title": "Swap (finance)——In finance, a swap is a derivative in which two parties agre…", "summary": "In finance, a swap is a derivative in which two parties agree to exchange one stream of cash flows for another, based on some agreed formula. An example is a floating-for-fixed interest rate swap, which calls for (a) payments by one party based on the product of a floating interest rate and a fixed amount, called the…", "takeaways": ["In finance, a swap is a derivative in which two parties agree to exchange one stream of cash flows for another, based on some agreed formula.", "Swaps are primarily over-the-counter contracts involving sophisticated institutions.", "Bank for International Settlements Credit & Commodity."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "^VIX", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Swap_%28finance%29"},
    {"id": "credit-default-swap", "level": "进阶", "category": "衍生品", "title": "Credit default swap——A credit default swap (CDS) is a financial swap agreement th…", "summary": "A credit default swap (CDS) is a financial swap agreement that the seller of the CDS will compensate the buyer in the event of a debt default (by the debtor) or other credit event. That is, the seller of the CDS insures the buyer against some reference asset defaulting.", "takeaways": ["A credit default swap (CDS) is a financial swap agreement that the seller of the CDS will compensate the buyer in the event of a debt default (by the …", "However, anyone can purchase a CDS, even buyers who do not hold the loan instrument and who have no direct insurable interest in the loan (these are c…", "The payment received is often substantially less than the face value of the loan."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "^VIX", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Credit_default_swap"},
    {"id": "warrant-finance", "level": "进阶", "category": "衍生品", "title": "Warrant (finance)——In finance, a warrant is a security that entitles the holder…", "summary": "In finance, a warrant is a security that entitles the holder to buy or sell stock, typically the stock of the issuing company, at a fixed price called the strike price. Warrants and options are similar in that the two contractual financial instruments allow the holder special rights to buy securities.", "takeaways": ["In finance, a warrant is a security that entitles the holder to buy or sell stock, typically the stock of the issuing company, at a fixed price called…", "Warrants can also be used in private equity deals.", "Warrants are actively traded in some financial markets, such as the German and Hong Kong stock exchanges."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "^VIX", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Warrant_%28finance%29"},
    {"id": "bond-basics", "level": "入门", "category": "固定收益", "title": "Bond (finance)——In finance, a bond is a type of security under which the iss…", "summary": "In finance, a bond is a type of security under which the issuer (debtor) owes the holder (creditor) a debt, and is obliged – depending on the terms – to provide cash flow to the creditor; which usually consists of repaying the principal (the amount borrowed) of the bond at the maturity date, as well as interest…", "takeaways": ["The timing and the amount of cash flow provided varies, depending on the economic value that is emphasized upon, thus giving rise to different types o…", "Another difference is that bonds usually have a defined term, or maturity, after which the bond is redeemed, whereas stocks typically remain outstandi…", "Bonds are often identified by their international securities identification number, or ISIN, which is a 12-digit alphanumeric code that uniquely ident…"], "marketLinks": ["TLT", "IEF", "LQD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bond_%28finance%29"},
    {"id": "treasury-bond", "level": "入门", "category": "固定收益", "title": "United States Treasury security——United States Treasury securities, also called Treasuries or…", "summary": "United States Treasury securities, also called Treasuries or Treasurys, are government debt instruments issued by the United States Department of the Treasury to finance government spending as a supplement to taxation. Since 2012, the U.S.", "takeaways": ["government debt has been managed by the Bureau of the Fiscal Service, succeeding the Bureau of the Public Debt.", "The government sells these securities in auctions conducted by the Federal Reserve Bank of New York, after which they can be traded in secondary marke…", "This low risk gives Treasuries a unique place in the financial system, where they are used as cash equivalents by institutions, corporations, and weal…"], "marketLinks": ["TLT", "IEF", "LQD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_Treasury_security"},
    {"id": "corporate-bond", "level": "入门", "category": "固定收益", "title": "Corporate bond——A corporate bond is a bond issued by a corporation in order …", "summary": "A corporate bond is a bond issued by a corporation in order to raise financing for a variety of reasons such as to fund ongoing operations, mergers & acquisitions, or to expand business.", "takeaways": ["A corporate bond is a bond issued by a corporation in order to raise financing for a variety of reasons such as to fund ongoing operations, mergers & acquisitions, or to expand business.", "It is a longer-term debt instrument indicating that a corporation has borrowed a certain amount of money and promises to repay it in the future under specific terms.", "Corporate debt instruments with maturity shorter than one year are referred to as commercial paper."], "marketLinks": ["TLT", "IEF", "LQD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Corporate_bond"},
    {"id": "municipal-bond", "level": "入门", "category": "固定收益", "title": "Municipal bond——A municipal bond, commonly known as a muni, is a bond issued…", "summary": "A municipal bond, commonly known as a muni, is a bond issued by state or local governments, or entities they create such as authorities and special districts. In the United States, interest income received by holders of municipal bonds is often, but not always, exempt from federal and state income taxation.", "takeaways": ["A municipal bond, commonly known as a muni, is a bond issued by state or local governments, or entities they create such as authorities and special di…", "Taxable equivalent yield calculations are required to make fair comparisons between the two categories.", "Local authorities in many other countries in the world issue similar bonds, sometimes called local authority bonds or other names."], "marketLinks": ["TLT", "IEF", "LQD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Municipal_bond"},
    {"id": "coupon-rate", "level": "入门", "category": "固定收益", "title": "Coupon (finance)——In finance, a coupon is the interest payment that a bond iss…", "summary": "In finance, a coupon is the interest payment that a bond issuer promises to pay a bondholder regularly from the date of issuance until the date of maturity of a bond.", "takeaways": ["In finance, a coupon is the interest payment that a bond issuer promises to pay a bondholder regularly from the date of issuance until the date of mat…", "For example, if a bond has a face value of $1,000 and a coupon rate of 5% (per year), then it pays total coupons of $50 per year.", "Typically, this will consist of two semi-annual payments of $25 each."], "marketLinks": ["TLT", "IEF", "LQD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coupon_%28finance%29"},
    {"id": "yield-to-maturity", "level": "进阶", "category": "固定收益", "title": "Yield to maturity——The yield to maturity (YTM), book yield or redemption yield …", "summary": "The yield to maturity (YTM), book yield or redemption yield of a fixed-interest security is an estimate of the total rate of return anticipated to be earned by an investor who buys it at a given market price, holds it to maturity, and receives all interest payments and the capital redemption on schedule.", "takeaways": ["The YTM is often given in terms of annual percentage rate (APR), but more often market convention is followed.", "In a number of major markets, the convention is to quote annualized yields with semi-annual compounding."], "marketLinks": ["TLT", "IEF", "LQD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yield_to_maturity"},
    {"id": "current-yield", "level": "入门", "category": "固定收益", "title": "Current yield——The current yield, interest yield, income yield, flat yield,…", "summary": "The current yield, interest yield, income yield, flat yield, market yield, mark to market yield or running yield is a financial term used in reference to bonds and other fixed-interest securities such as gilts.", "takeaways": ["了解Current yield的基本定义和应用场景", "理解Current yield在金融市场中的作用和影响", "结合市场数据观察Current yield的实际表现"], "marketLinks": ["TLT", "IEF", "LQD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Current_yield"},
    {"id": "yield-curve", "level": "进阶", "category": "固定收益", "title": "Yield curve——A yield curve shows the relationship between yields and time…", "summary": "A yield curve shows the relationship between yields and time to maturity for a set of comparable debt securities. In practice the term usually refers to curves built from a single issuer or market segment so that credit quality and other features are as similar as possible, for example the U.S.", "takeaways": ["A yield curve shows the relationship between yields and time to maturity for a set of comparable debt securities.", "These families are produced by central banks and data providers from prices of instruments in each market and are kept comparable within a family by c…", "Official sources distinguish several ways to summarize it, including zero-coupon or \"spot\" curves, implied forward curves and par yield curves, each d…"], "marketLinks": ["TLT", "IEF", "LQD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yield_curve"},
    {"id": "inverted-yield-curve", "level": "进阶", "category": "固定收益", "title": "Inverted yield curve——In finance, an inverted yield curve is a yield curve in whic…", "summary": "In finance, an inverted yield curve is a yield curve in which short-term debt instruments (typically bonds) have a greater yield than longer term bonds. An inverted yield curve is an unusual phenomenon; bonds with shorter maturities generally provide lower yields than longer term bonds.", "takeaways": ["In finance, an inverted yield curve is a yield curve in which short-term debt instruments (typically bonds) have a greater yield than longer term bond…", "To determine whether the yield curve is inverted, it is a common practice to compare the yield on the 10-year U.S.", "If the 10-year yield is less than the 2-year or 3-month yield, the curve is inverted."], "marketLinks": ["TLT", "IEF", "LQD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inverted_yield_curve"},
    {"id": "duration-bond", "level": "进阶", "category": "固定收益", "title": "Duration (finance)——In finance, duration is a measure of how the price of a fixe…", "summary": "In finance, duration is a measure of how the price of a fixed-income instrument responds to a change in interest rates. It is used to compare rate risk across bonds and to construct hedges, and is often paired with convexity and the price value of a basis point.", "takeaways": ["In finance, duration is a measure of how the price of a fixed-income instrument responds to a change in interest rates.", "Duration-based estimates work best for small, parallel shifts in the yield curve.", "Modified duration expresses the first-order percentage price change for a stated compounding convention."], "marketLinks": ["TLT", "IEF", "LQD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bond_duration"},
    {"id": "modified-duration", "level": "进阶", "category": "固定收益", "title": "Duration (finance)——In finance, duration is a measure of how the price of a fixe…", "summary": "In finance, duration is a measure of how the price of a fixed-income instrument responds to a change in interest rates. It is used to compare rate risk across bonds and to construct hedges, and is often paired with convexity and the price value of a basis point.", "takeaways": ["In finance, duration is a measure of how the price of a fixed-income instrument responds to a change in interest rates.", "Duration-based estimates work best for small, parallel shifts in the yield curve.", "Modified duration expresses the first-order percentage price change for a stated compounding convention."], "marketLinks": ["TLT", "IEF", "LQD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modified_duration"},
    {"id": "convexity-bond", "level": "进阶", "category": "固定收益", "title": "Bond convexity——In finance, bond convexity is a measure of the non-linear re…", "summary": "In finance, bond convexity is a measure of the non-linear relationship of bond prices to changes in interest rates, and is defined as the second derivative of the price of the bond with respect to interest rates (duration is the first derivative).", "takeaways": ["In general, the higher the duration, the more sensitive the bond price is to the change in interest rates.", "Bond convexity is one of the most basic and widely used forms of convexity in finance.", "Convexity was based on the work of Hon-Fei Lai and popularized by Stanley Diller."], "marketLinks": ["TLT", "IEF", "LQD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bond_convexity"},
    {"id": "credit-rating", "level": "入门", "category": "固定收益", "title": "Credit rating——A credit rating is an evaluation of the credit risk of a pro…", "summary": "A credit rating is an evaluation of the credit risk of a prospective debtor (an individual, a business, company or a government). It is the practice of predicting or forecasting the ability of a supposed debtor to pay back the debt or default.", "takeaways": ["A credit rating is an evaluation of the credit risk of a prospective debtor (an individual, a business, company or a government).", "Credit reporting (or credit score) is a subset of credit rating.", "It is a numeric evaluation of an individual's credit worthiness, which is done by a credit bureau or consumer credit reporting agency."], "marketLinks": ["TLT", "IEF", "LQD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Credit_rating"},
    {"id": "investment-grade", "level": "入门", "category": "固定收益", "title": "Bond credit rating——In investment, the bond credit rating represents the creditw…", "summary": "In investment, the bond credit rating represents the creditworthiness of corporate or government bonds. The ratings are published by credit rating agencies and used by investment professionals to assess the likelihood the debt will be repaid.", "takeaways": ["In investment, the bond credit rating represents the creditworthiness of corporate or government bonds.", "The ratings are published by credit rating agencies and used by investment professionals to assess the likelihood the debt will be repaid."], "marketLinks": ["TLT", "IEF", "LQD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bond_credit_rating"},
    {"id": "high-yield-bond", "level": "进阶", "category": "固定收益", "title": "High-yield debt——In finance, a high-yield bond (non-investment-grade bond, sp…", "summary": "In finance, a high-yield bond (non-investment-grade bond, speculative-grade bond, or junk bond) is a bond that is rated below investment grade by credit rating agencies.", "takeaways": ["In finance, a high-yield bond (non-investment-grade bond, speculative-grade bond, or junk bond) is a bond that is rated below investment grade by credit rating agencies.", "These bonds have a higher risk of default or other adverse credit events but offer higher yields than investment-grade bonds to compensate for the increased risk."], "marketLinks": ["TLT", "IEF", "LQD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/High-yield_debt"},
    {"id": "tips-bond", "level": "入门", "category": "固定收益", "title": "United States Treasury security——United States Treasury securities, also called Treasuries or…", "summary": "United States Treasury securities, also called Treasuries or Treasurys, are government debt instruments issued by the United States Department of the Treasury to finance government spending as a supplement to taxation. Since 2012, the U.S.", "takeaways": ["government debt has been managed by the Bureau of the Fiscal Service, succeeding the Bureau of the Public Debt.", "The government sells these securities in auctions conducted by the Federal Reserve Bank of New York, after which they can be traded in secondary marke…", "This low risk gives Treasuries a unique place in the financial system, where they are used as cash equivalents by institutions, corporations, and weal…"], "marketLinks": ["TLT", "IEF", "LQD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treasury_Inflation-Protected_Securities"},
    {"id": "convertible-bond", "level": "进阶", "category": "固定收益", "title": "Convertible bond——In finance, a convertible bond, convertible note, or convert…", "summary": "In finance, a convertible bond, convertible note, or convertible (or a convertible debenture if it has a maturity of greater than 10 years) is a type of bond that the holder can convert into a specified number of shares of common stock in the issuing company or cash of equal value.", "takeaways": ["It is a hybrid security with debt- and equity-like features.", "The investor receives the potential upside of conversion into equity while protecting downside with cash flow from the coupon payments and the return …", "Convertible notes are also a frequent vehicle for seed investing in startup companies, as a form of debt that converts to equity in a future investing…"], "marketLinks": ["TLT", "IEF", "LQD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convertible_bond"},
    {"id": "callable-bond", "level": "进阶", "category": "固定收益", "title": "Callable bond——A callable bond (also called redeemable bond) is a type of b…", "summary": "A callable bond (also called redeemable bond) is a type of bond (debt security) that allows the issuer of the bond to retain the privilege of redeeming the bond at some point before the bond reaches its date of maturity.", "takeaways": ["In other words, on the call date(s), the issuer has the right, but not the obligation, to buy back the bonds from the bond holders at a defined call p…", "This is comparable to selling (writing) an option — the option writer gets a premium up front, but has a downside if the option is exercised.", "Since call option and put option are not mutually exclusive, a bond may have both options embedded."], "marketLinks": ["TLT", "IEF", "LQD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Callable_bond"},
    {"id": "federal-funds-rate", "level": "入门", "category": "固定收益", "title": "Federal funds rate——The federal funds rate is the interest rate at which deposit…", "summary": "The federal funds rate is the interest rate at which depository institutions (banks and credit unions) lend reserve balances to other depository institutions overnight on an uncollateralized basis. Reserve balances are amounts held at the Federal Reserve.", "takeaways": ["The federal funds rate is the interest rate at which depository institutions (banks and credit unions) lend reserve balances to other depository insti…", "It is published daily by the Federal Reserve Bank of New York.", "The target range is chosen to influence market interest rates generally and in turn ultimately the level of activity, employment and inflation in the …"], "marketLinks": ["TLT", "IEF", "LQD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Federal_funds_rate"},
    {"id": "repo-market", "level": "进阶", "category": "固定收益", "title": "Repurchase agreement——A repurchase agreement, also known as a repo, RP, or sale an…", "summary": "A repurchase agreement, also known as a repo, RP, or sale and repurchase agreement, is a form of secured short-term borrowing, usually, though not always, using government securities as collateral.", "takeaways": ["A repurchase agreement, also known as a repo, RP, or sale and repurchase agreement, is a form of secured short-term borrowing, usually, though not alw…", "Similarly, when the Federal Reserve wishes to add to banking reserves, it can buy a government security with a forward commitment to sell it back.", "During September 2019, the U.S."], "marketLinks": ["TLT", "IEF", "LQD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Repurchase_agreement"},
    {"id": "sofr", "level": "进阶", "category": "固定收益", "title": "SOFR——Secured Overnight Financing Rate (SOFR) is a secured overnig…", "summary": "Secured Overnight Financing Rate (SOFR) is a secured overnight interest rate. SOFR is a reference rate (that is, a rate used by parties in commercial contracts that is outside their direct control) established as an alternative to LIBOR.", "takeaways": ["Secured Overnight Financing Rate (SOFR) is a secured overnight interest rate.", "The Act also grants a safe harbor to LIBOR contracts that transition to SOFR.", "In addition, SOFR is overnight, whereas LIBOR can have longer tenures."], "marketLinks": ["TLT", "IEF", "LQD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SOFR"},
    {"id": "libor", "level": "进阶", "category": "固定收益", "title": "Libor——The London Inter-Bank Offered Rate (Libor LY-bor) was an int…", "summary": "The London Inter-Bank Offered Rate (Libor LY-bor) was an interest rate average calculated from estimates submitted by the leading banks in London. Each bank estimated what it would be charged were it to borrow from other banks.", "takeaways": ["The London Inter-Bank Offered Rate (Libor  LY-bor) was an interest rate average calculated from estimates submitted by the leading banks in London.", "Libor rates were calculated for five currencies and seven borrowing periods, ranging from overnight to one year, and were published each business day …", "The British government regulated Libor through criminal and regulatory laws passed by Parliament."], "marketLinks": ["TLT", "IEF", "LQD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Libor"},
    {"id": "credit-spread", "level": "进阶", "category": "固定收益", "title": "Yield spread——In finance, the yield spread or credit spread is the differe…", "summary": "In finance, the yield spread or credit spread is the difference between the quoted rates of return on two different investments, usually of different credit qualities but similar maturities. It is often an indication of the risk premium for one investment product over another.", "takeaways": ["In finance, the yield spread or credit spread is the difference between the quoted rates of return on two different investments, usually of different …", "There are several measures of yield spread relative to a benchmark yield curve, including interpolated spread (I-spread), zero-volatility spread (Z-sp…", "term structure; curves may also be constructed for credit structure."], "marketLinks": ["TLT", "IEF", "LQD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Credit_spread_%28bond%29"},
    {"id": "immunization-strategy", "level": "进阶", "category": "固定收益", "title": "Immunization (finance)——In finance, interest rate immunization is a portfolio manage…", "summary": "In finance, interest rate immunization is a portfolio management strategy designed to take advantage of the offsetting effects of interest rate risk and reinvestment risk.", "takeaways": ["In finance, interest rate immunization is a portfolio management strategy designed to take advantage of the offsetting effects of interest rate risk a…", "It can also be accomplished by trading in bond forwards, futures, or options.", "If the immunization is complete, these strategies are usually called arbitrage."], "marketLinks": ["TLT", "IEF", "LQD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Immunization_%28finance%29"},
    {"id": "gdp", "level": "入门", "category": "宏观", "title": "Gross domestic product——Gross domestic product (GDP) is a monetary measure of the to…", "summary": "Gross domestic product (GDP) is a monetary measure of the total market value of all of the final goods and services which are produced and rendered during a specific period of time (usually a year) by a country or countries. GDP is often used to measure the economic activity of a country or region.", "takeaways": ["GDP is often used to measure the economic activity of a country or region.", "GDP is often used as a metric for international comparisons as well as a broad measure of economic progress.", "GDP has been criticized for leaving out key externalities, such as resource extraction, environmental impact and unpaid domestic work."], "marketLinks": ["^TNX", "SPY", "CL=F"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gross_domestic_product"},
    {"id": "inflation", "level": "入门", "category": "宏观", "title": "Inflation——In economics, inflation is an increase in the average price …", "summary": "In economics, inflation is an increase in the average price of goods and services in terms of money. This increase is measured using a price index, typically a consumer price index (CPI).", "takeaways": ["In economics, inflation is an increase in the average price of goods and services in terms of money.", "The opposite of inflation is deflation, a decrease in the general price level of goods and services.", "Today, most economists favour a low and steady rate of inflation."], "marketLinks": ["^TNX", "SPY", "CL=F"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inflation"},
    {"id": "cpi", "level": "入门", "category": "宏观", "title": "Consumer price index——A consumer price index (CPI) is a statistical estimate of th…", "summary": "A consumer price index (CPI) is a statistical estimate of the level of prices of goods and services bought for consumption purposes by households. It is calculated as the weighted average price of a market basket of consumer goods and services. Changes in CPI track changes in prices over time.", "takeaways": ["A consumer price index (CPI) is a statistical estimate of the level of prices of goods and services bought for consumption purposes by households.", "The prices of the goods and services in the basket are collected (often monthly) from a sample of retail and service establishments.", "It is one of several price indices calculated by many national statistical agencies."], "marketLinks": ["^TNX", "SPY", "CL=F"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Consumer_price_index"},
    {"id": "ppi", "level": "入门", "category": "宏观", "title": "Producer price index——A producer price index (PPI) is a price index that measures …", "summary": "A producer price index (PPI) is a price index that measures the average changes in prices received by domestic producers for their output. Formerly known as the wholesale price index between 1902 and 1978, the index is made up of over 16,000 establishments providing approximately 64,000 price quotations that the U.S.", "takeaways": ["A producer price index (PPI) is a price index that measures the average changes in prices received by domestic producers for their output.", "Bureau of Labor Statistics (BLS) compiles each month to represent thousands of different goods and services.", "Transferring those costs to consumers, which may boost business profits, but means customers will face higher prices for the goods and services."], "marketLinks": ["^TNX", "SPY", "CL=F"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Producer_price_index"},
    {"id": "core-inflation", "level": "入门", "category": "宏观", "title": "Core inflation——Core inflation is a type of inflation measure which seeks to…", "summary": "Core inflation is a type of inflation measure which seeks to represent the underlying long-run trend of aggregate price levels in the economy. This is achieved by removing certain items exhibiting short-term significant price fluctuations within the overall consumer basket (as typically measured by the headline…", "takeaways": ["Core inflation is a type of inflation measure which seeks to represent the underlying long-run trend of aggregate price levels in the economy.", "The most common approach in accomplishing this is by excluding items frequently subject to volatile price movements, like food and energy.", "Throughout the years, econometricians have likewise devised alternative approaches in computing core inflation using more formal methodologies."], "marketLinks": ["^TNX", "SPY", "CL=F"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Core_inflation"},
    {"id": "unemployment-rate", "level": "入门", "category": "宏观", "title": "Unemployment——Unemployment is the state of not being in paid employment or…", "summary": "Unemployment is the state of not being in paid employment or self-employment but rather currently available for work. Unemployment is measured by the unemployment rate, which is the number of people who are unemployed as a percentage of the labour force (the total number of people employed above a specified age added…", "takeaways": ["了解Unemployment的基本定义和应用场景", "理解Unemployment在金融市场中的作用和影响", "结合市场数据观察Unemployment的实际表现"], "marketLinks": ["^TNX", "SPY", "CL=F"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unemployment"},
    {"id": "labor-force-participation", "level": "进阶", "category": "宏观", "title": "Unemployment——Unemployment is the state of not being in paid employment or…", "summary": "Unemployment is the state of not being in paid employment or self-employment but rather currently available for work. Unemployment is measured by the unemployment rate, which is the number of people who are unemployed as a percentage of the labour force (the total number of people employed above a specified age added…", "takeaways": ["了解Unemployment的基本定义和应用场景", "理解Unemployment在金融市场中的作用和影响", "结合市场数据观察Unemployment的实际表现"], "marketLinks": ["^TNX", "SPY", "CL=F"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Labor_force_participation_rate"},
    {"id": "pmi-manufacturing", "level": "进阶", "category": "宏观", "title": "Purchasing Managers' Index——Purchasing managers' indexes (PMI) are economic indicators d…", "summary": "Purchasing managers' indexes (PMI) are economic indicators derived from monthly surveys of private sector companies. The three principal producers of PMIs are S&P Global (from 2022 merger with IHS Markit), which produces PMIs for over 30 countries worldwide and developed the first service sector PMIs, and the…", "takeaways": ["Purchasing managers' indexes (PMI) are economic indicators derived from monthly surveys of private sector companies.", "SIPMM survey covers just the manufacturing sector.", "Other benefits include the data's timeliness due to it being released shortly after the end of the reference period, and the data is not revised after…"], "marketLinks": ["^TNX", "SPY", "CL=F"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Purchasing_Managers%27_Index"},
    {"id": "ism-index", "level": "进阶", "category": "宏观", "title": "Institute for Supply Management——The Institute for Supply Management (ISM) is the world's old…", "summary": "The Institute for Supply Management (ISM) is the world's oldest and largest supply management association. Founded in 1915, the U.S.-based not-for-profit educational association serves professionals and organizations with interest in supply management, providing education, training, qualifications, publications,…", "takeaways": ["The Institute for Supply Management (ISM) is the world's oldest and largest supply management association.", "ISM serves a community of over 50,000 members in more than 100 countries."], "marketLinks": ["^TNX", "SPY", "CL=F"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Institute_for_Supply_Management"},
    {"id": "retail-sales", "level": "入门", "category": "宏观", "title": "Retail——Retail is the sale of goods and services to consumers, in co…", "summary": "Retail is the sale of goods and services to consumers, in contrast to wholesaling, which is the sale to business or institutional customers. A retailer purchases goods in large quantities from manufacturers, directly from or through a wholesaler, and then sells in smaller quantities to consumers for a profit.", "takeaways": ["Retail is the sale of goods and services to consumers, in contrast to wholesaling, which is the sale to business or institutional customers.", "Day-to-day decisions are often described using the retail marketing mix, commonly summarized as six “Ps”: product, place, promotion, price, personnel,…", "Retailers also expanded omnichannel capabilities, such as buy online and pick up in store, and some firms tested automation, such as cashierless store…"], "marketLinks": ["^TNX", "SPY", "CL=F"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Retail_sales"},
    {"id": "consumer-confidence", "level": "进阶", "category": "宏观", "title": "Consumer confidence index——A consumer confidence index (CCI) is an economic indicator p…", "summary": "A consumer confidence index (CCI) is an economic indicator published by various organizations in several countries. In simple terms, increased consumer confidence indicates economic growth in which consumers are spending money, indicating higher consumption.", "takeaways": ["A consumer confidence index (CCI) is an economic indicator published by various organizations in several countries.", "Decreasing consumer confidence implies slowing economic growth, and so consumers are likely to decrease their spending.", "Declining consumer confidence is a sign of slowing economic growth and may indicate that the economy is headed into trouble."], "marketLinks": ["^TNX", "SPY", "CL=F"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Consumer_confidence_index"},
    {"id": "housing-starts", "level": "进阶", "category": "宏观", "title": "Housing starts——Housing starts is an economic indicator that reflects the nu…", "summary": "Housing starts is an economic indicator that reflects the number of privately owned new houses (technically housing units) on which construction has been started in a given period. This data is divided into three types: single-family houses, townhouses or small condos, and apartment buildings with five or more units.", "takeaways": ["Housing starts is an economic indicator that reflects the number of privately owned new houses (technically housing units) on which construction  has …", "Each apartment unit is considered a single start.", "The construction of a 30-unit apartment building is counted as 30 housing starts."], "marketLinks": ["^TNX", "SPY", "CL=F"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Housing_starts"},
    {"id": "fiscal-policy", "level": "入门", "category": "宏观", "title": "Fiscal policy——In economics and political science, fiscal policy is the use…", "summary": "In economics and political science, fiscal policy is the use of government revenue collection (taxes or tax cuts) and expenditure to influence a country's economy.", "takeaways": ["In economics and political science, fiscal policy is the use of government revenue collection (taxes or tax cuts) and expenditure to influence a count…", "In modern economies, inflation is conventionally considered \"healthy\" in the range of 2%–3%.", "Both fiscal and monetary policies influence a country's economic performance."], "marketLinks": ["^TNX", "SPY", "CL=F"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fiscal_policy"},
    {"id": "monetary-policy", "level": "入门", "category": "宏观", "title": "Monetary policy——Monetary policy is the policy adopted by the monetary author…", "summary": "Monetary policy is the policy adopted by the monetary authority of a nation to affect monetary and other financial conditions to accomplish broader objectives like high employment and price stability (normally interpreted as a low and stable rate of inflation).", "takeaways": ["Further purposes of a monetary policy may be to contribute to economic stability or to maintain predictable exchange rates with other currencies.", "Monetary policy affects the economy through financial channels like interest rates, exchange rates and prices of financial assets.", "How best to conduct monetary policy is an active and debated research area, drawing on fields like monetary economics as well as other subfields withi…"], "marketLinks": ["^TNX", "SPY", "CL=F"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monetary_policy"},
    {"id": "quantitative-easing", "level": "进阶", "category": "宏观", "title": "Quantitative easing——Quantitative easing (QE) is a monetary policy action where a…", "summary": "Quantitative easing (QE) is a monetary policy action where a central bank purchases predetermined amounts of government bonds, company shares, or other financial assets (liquidity) in order to artificially stimulate economic activity.", "takeaways": ["Quantitative easing is a novel form of monetary policy that began in Japan and came into wide application in the US following the 2008 financial crisi…", "This makes it difficult for interest rates to go below zero; monetary authorities may then use quantitative easing to stimulate the economy rather tha…", "QE has also been criticized for raising financial asset prices, and thereby contributing to economic inequality."], "marketLinks": ["^TNX", "SPY", "CL=F"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quantitative_easing"},
    {"id": "quantitative-tightening", "level": "进阶", "category": "宏观", "title": "Quantitative tightening——Quantitative tightening (QT) is a contractionary monetary po…", "summary": "Quantitative tightening (QT) is a contractionary monetary policy tool applied by central banks to decrease the amount of liquidity or money supply in the economy.", "takeaways": ["Quantitative tightening (QT) is a contractionary monetary policy tool applied by central banks to decrease the amount of liquidity or money supply in the economy.", "QT is the reverse of quantitative easing (or QE), where the central bank prints money and uses it to buy assets in order to raise asset prices and stimulate the economy."], "marketLinks": ["^TNX", "SPY", "CL=F"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quantitative_tightening"},
    {"id": "taylor-rule", "level": "进阶", "category": "宏观", "title": "Taylor rule——The Taylor rule is a monetary policy targeting rule. The rul…", "summary": "The Taylor rule is a monetary policy targeting rule. The rule was proposed in 1992 by American economist John B. Taylor for central banks to use to stabilize economic activity by appropriately setting short-term interest rates. The rule considers the federal funds rate, the price level and changes in real income.", "takeaways": ["The Taylor rule is a monetary policy targeting rule.", "The committee attempts to achieve an average inflation rate of 2% (with an equal likelihood of higher or lower inflation).", "This debate between rules and discretion remains central to discussions of monetary policy implementation."], "marketLinks": ["^TNX", "SPY", "CL=F"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taylor_rule"},
    {"id": "phillips-curve", "level": "进阶", "category": "宏观", "title": "Phillips curve——The Phillips curve is a representation of the relationship b…", "summary": "The Phillips curve is a representation of the relationship between unemployment and inflation in the macroeconomy, where a tradeoff between low unemployment and price stability exists.", "takeaways": ["The Phillips curve is a representation of the relationship between unemployment and inflation in the macroeconomy, where a tradeoff between low unempl…", "In 1967 and 1968, Friedman and Phelps asserted that the Phillips curve was only applicable in the short run and that, in the long run, inflationary po…", "Nonetheless, the Phillips curve is still used by central banks in understanding and forecasting inflation."], "marketLinks": ["^TNX", "SPY", "CL=F"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phillips_curve"},
    {"id": "stagflation", "level": "入门", "category": "宏观", "title": "Stagflation——Stagflation is the combination of high inflation, stagnant e…", "summary": "Stagflation is the combination of high inflation, stagnant economic growth, and elevated unemployment. The term stagflation, a portmanteau of \"stagnation\" and \"inflation\", was popularized, and probably coined, by British politician Iain Macleod in the 1960s, during a period of economic distress in the United Kingdom.", "takeaways": ["Stagflation is the combination of high inflation, stagnant economic growth, and elevated unemployment.", "Stagflation challenges traditional economic theories, which suggest that inflation and unemployment are inversely related, as depicted by the Phillips…", "The stagflation of the 1970s led to a reevaluation of Keynesian economic policies and contributed to the rise of alternative economic theories, includ…"], "marketLinks": ["^TNX", "SPY", "CL=F"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stagflation"},
    {"id": "deflation", "level": "进阶", "category": "宏观", "title": "Deflation——In economics, deflation is an increase in the real value of …", "summary": "In economics, deflation is an increase in the real value of the monetary unit of account, as reflected in a decrease in cost of living, measurable by broad price indices. Deflation is a monetary phenomenon, explainable in terms of changes in money supply and velocity relative to spending on output.", "takeaways": ["In economics, deflation is an increase in the real value of the monetary unit of account, as reflected in a decrease in cost of living, measurable by …", "While inflation reduces the value of currency over time, deflation increases it.", "Deflation may also aggravate recessions and lead to a deflationary spiral."], "marketLinks": ["^TNX", "SPY", "CL=F"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deflation"},
    {"id": "hyperinflation", "level": "入门", "category": "宏观", "title": "Hyperinflation——In economics, hyperinflation is a very high and typically ac…", "summary": "In economics, hyperinflation is a very high and typically accelerating inflation. It quickly erodes the real value of the local currency, as the prices of all goods increase. This causes people to minimize their holdings in that currency as they usually switch to more stable foreign currencies.", "takeaways": ["In economics, hyperinflation is a very high and typically accelerating inflation.", "Ineffective implementations of these solutions often exacerbate the situation.", "A sharp decrease in real tax revenue coupled with a strong need to maintain government spending, together with an inability or unwillingness to borrow…"], "marketLinks": ["^TNX", "SPY", "CL=F"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperinflation"},
    {"id": "trade-balance", "level": "入门", "category": "宏观", "title": "Balance of trade——Balance of trade is the difference between the monetary valu…", "summary": "Balance of trade is the difference between the monetary value of a nation's exports and imports of goods over a certain time period. Sometimes, trade in services is also included in the balance of trade but the official IMF definition only considers goods.", "takeaways": ["Balance of trade is the difference between the monetary value of a nation's exports and imports of goods over a certain time period.", "The notion of the balance of trade does not mean that exports and imports are \"in balance\" with each other.", "Economists reject the idea that a trade deficit is detrimental to a nation's economy, and the idea that a bilateral trade deficit is inherently bad."], "marketLinks": ["^TNX", "SPY", "CL=F"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Balance_of_trade"},
    {"id": "current-account", "level": "进阶", "category": "宏观", "title": "Current account (balance of payments)——In macroeconomics and international finance, a country's cur…", "summary": "In macroeconomics and international finance, a country's current account records the value of exports and imports of both goods and services and international transfers of capital. It is one of the two components of the balance of payments, the other being the capital account (also known as the financial account).", "takeaways": ["In macroeconomics and international finance, a country's current account records the value of exports and imports of both goods and services and inter…", "A current account surplus indicates that the value of a country's net foreign assets (i.e.", "It is called the current account because goods and services are generally consumed in the current period."], "marketLinks": ["^TNX", "SPY", "CL=F"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Current_account_%28balance_of_payments%29"},
    {"id": "fiscal-deficit", "level": "进阶", "category": "宏观", "title": "Government budget balance——The government budget balance, also referred to as the gener…", "summary": "The government budget balance, also referred to as the general government balance, public budget balance, or public fiscal balance, is the difference between government revenues and spending.", "takeaways": ["The government budget balance, also referred to as the general government balance,  public budget balance, or public fiscal balance, is the difference…", "The government budget balance can be broken down into the primary balance and interest payments on accumulated government debt; the two together give …", "The cumulative flow of deficits equals the stock of debt when a government employs cash accounting (though not under accrual accounting)."], "marketLinks": ["^TNX", "SPY", "CL=F"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Government_budget_balance"},
    {"id": "national-debt", "level": "入门", "category": "宏观", "title": "National debt of the United States——The national debt of the United States is the total national…", "summary": "The national debt of the United States is the total national debt owed by the federal government of the United States to treasury security holders. At any given point in time, the U.S. national debt is the cumulative face value of all outstanding treasury securities that have been issued by the U.S.", "takeaways": ["The national debt of the United States is the total national debt owed by the federal government of the United States to treasury security holders.", "The federal government generates revenue through taxation before spending on public services, creating a government budget balance.", "Debt held by government (intragovernmental debt): non-marketable Treasury securities held in accounts of programs administered by the federal governme…"], "marketLinks": ["^TNX", "SPY", "CL=F"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_debt_of_the_United_States"},
    {"id": "debt-to-gdp", "level": "进阶", "category": "宏观", "title": "Debt-to-GDP ratio——In economics, the debt-to-GDP ratio is the ratio of a countr…", "summary": "In economics, the debt-to-GDP ratio is the ratio of a country's accumulation of government debt (measured in units of currency) to its gross domestic product (GDP) (measured in units of currency per year).", "takeaways": ["A low debt-to-GDP ratio indicates that an economy produces goods and services sufficient to pay back debts without incurring further debt.", "Geopolitical and economic considerations – including interest rates, war, recessions, and other variables – influence the borrowing practices of a nation and the choice to incur further debt.", "Particularly in macroeconomics, various debt-to-GDP ratios can be calculated."], "marketLinks": ["^TNX", "SPY", "CL=F"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Debt-to-GDP_ratio"},
    {"id": "recession", "level": "入门", "category": "宏观", "title": "Recession——In economics, a recession is a business cycle contraction th…", "summary": "In economics, a recession is a business cycle contraction that occurs when there is a period of broad decline in economic activity. Recessions generally occur when there is a widespread drop in spending (an adverse demand shock).", "takeaways": ["In economics, a recession is a business cycle contraction that occurs when there is a period of broad decline in economic activity.", "There is no official definition of a recession, according to the International Monetary Fund.", "In the United Kingdom and Canada, a recession is defined as negative economic growth in GDP for two consecutive quarters."], "marketLinks": ["^TNX", "SPY", "CL=F"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Recession"},
    {"id": "business-cycle", "level": "入门", "category": "宏观", "title": "Business cycle——Business cycles are intervals of general expansion followed …", "summary": "Business cycles are intervals of general expansion followed by recession in economic performance. The changes in economic activity that characterize business cycles have important implications for the welfare of the general population, government institutions, and private sector firms.", "takeaways": ["Business cycles are intervals of general expansion followed by recession in economic performance.", "They are less related to long-term trends that arise from slowly changing factors, such as technological advances.", "Usually such sources are unpredictable in advance and can be viewed as random shocks to the cyclical pattern, as happened during the 2008 financial cr…"], "marketLinks": ["^TNX", "SPY", "CL=F"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Business_cycle"},
    {"id": "leading-indicator", "level": "进阶", "category": "宏观", "title": "Economic indicator——An economic indicator is a statistic about an economic activ…", "summary": "An economic indicator is a statistic about an economic activity. Economic indicators allow analysis of economic performance and predictions of future performance. One application of economic indicators is the study of business cycles.", "takeaways": ["An economic indicator is a statistic about an economic activity.", "The leading business cycle dating committee in the United States of America is the private National Bureau of Economic Research.", "Other producers of economic indicators includes the United States Census Bureau and United States Bureau of Economic Analysis."], "marketLinks": ["^TNX", "SPY", "CL=F"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leading_indicator"},
    {"id": "sahm-rule", "level": "进阶", "category": "宏观", "title": "Sahm rule——In macroeconomics, the Sahm rule, or Sahm rule recession ind…", "summary": "In macroeconomics, the Sahm rule, or Sahm rule recession indicator, is a heuristic measure by the United States' Federal Reserve for determining when an economy has entered a recession.", "takeaways": ["In macroeconomics, the Sahm rule, or Sahm rule recession indicator, is a heuristic measure by the United States' Federal Reserve for determining when an economy has entered a recession.", "It is useful in real-time evaluation of the business cycle and relies on monthly unemployment data from the Bureau of Labor Statistics (BLS).", "It is named after economist Claudia Sahm, formerly of the Federal Reserve and Council of Economic Advisors."], "marketLinks": ["^TNX", "SPY", "CL=F"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sahm_rule"},
    {"id": "misery-index", "level": "进阶", "category": "宏观", "title": "Misery index (economics)——The misery index is an economic indicator, created by the Am…", "summary": "The misery index is an economic indicator, created by the American economist Arthur Okun. The index helps determine how the average citizen is doing economically and is calculated by adding the seasonally adjusted unemployment rate to the annual inflation rate.", "takeaways": ["The misery index is an economic indicator, created by the American economist Arthur Okun.", "The index helps determine how the average citizen is doing economically and is calculated by adding the seasonally adjusted unemployment rate to the annual inflation rate.", "It is assumed that both a higher rate of unemployment and a worsening of inflation create economic and social costs for a country."], "marketLinks": ["^TNX", "SPY", "CL=F"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Misery_index_%28economics%29"},
    {"id": "real-interest-rate", "level": "进阶", "category": "宏观", "title": "Real interest rate——The real interest rate is the rate of interest an investor, …", "summary": "The real interest rate is the rate of interest an investor, saver or lender receives (or expects to receive) after allowing for inflation. It can be described more formally by the Fisher equation, which states that the real interest rate is approximately the nominal interest rate minus the inflation rate.", "takeaways": ["The real interest rate is the rate of interest an investor, saver or lender receives (or expects to receive) after allowing for inflation.", "The expected real interest rate is not a single number, as different investors have different expectations of future inflation.", "Since the introduction of inflation-indexed bonds, ex-ante real interest rates have become observable."], "marketLinks": ["^TNX", "SPY", "CL=F"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_interest_rate"},
    {"id": "behavioral-econ", "level": "入门", "category": "行为金融", "title": "Behavioral economics——Behavioral economics is the study of the psychological (e.g.…", "summary": "Behavioral economics is the study of the psychological (e.g. cognitive, behavioral, affective, social) factors involved in the decisions of individuals or institutions, and how these decisions deviate from those implied by traditional economic theory.", "takeaways": ["Behavioral economics is the study of the psychological (e.g.", "Behavioral models typically integrate insights from psychology, neuroscience and microeconomic theory.", "The field has become increasingly influential in informing economic analysis and policy design by incorporating empirically observed patterns of human…"], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "^VIX", "BTC-USD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Behavioral_economics"},
    {"id": "loss-aversion", "level": "入门", "category": "行为金融", "title": "Loss aversion——In cognitive science and behavioral economics, loss aversion…", "summary": "In cognitive science and behavioral economics, loss aversion is a cognitive bias in which the same situation is perceived as worse if it is framed as a loss, rather than a gain.", "takeaways": ["In cognitive science and behavioral economics, loss aversion is a cognitive bias in which the same situation is perceived as worse if it is framed as …", "Empirically, losses tend to be treated as if they were twice as large as an equivalent gain.", "Loss aversion was first proposed by Amos Tversky and Daniel Kahneman as an important component of prospect theory."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "^VIX", "BTC-USD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Loss_aversion"},
    {"id": "overconfidence-bias", "level": "进阶", "category": "行为金融", "title": "Overconfidence effect——The overconfidence effect is a cognitive bias in which a per…", "summary": "The overconfidence effect is a cognitive bias in which a person's subjective confidence in their judgments is reliably greater than the objective accuracy of those judgments, especially when confidence is relatively high. Overconfidence is one example of a miscalibration of subjective probabilities.", "takeaways": ["Overconfidence is one example of a miscalibration of subjective probabilities.", "By contrast, the key finding is that confidence exceeds accuracy so long as the subject is answering hard questions about an unfamiliar topic.", "When they were 100% certain of their answer to a question, they were wrong 20% of the time."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "^VIX", "BTC-USD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Overconfidence_effect"},
    {"id": "anchoring-bias", "level": "入门", "category": "行为金融", "title": "Anchoring effect——The anchoring effect is a psychological phenomenon in which …", "summary": "The anchoring effect is a psychological phenomenon in which an individual's judgments or decisions are influenced by a reference point or \"anchor\" which can be completely irrelevant. The original description of the anchoring effect came from psychophysics.", "takeaways": ["The anchoring effect is a psychological phenomenon in which an individual's judgments or decisions are influenced by a reference point or \"anchor\" whi…", "Both numeric and non-numeric anchoring have been reported through research.", "Non-numeric anchoring has been observed in physical judgments involving length, weight, and volume."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "^VIX", "BTC-USD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anchoring_%28cognitive_bias%29"},
    {"id": "confirmation-bias", "level": "入门", "category": "行为金融", "title": "Confirmation bias——Confirmation bias (also confirmatory bias, myside bias, or c…", "summary": "Confirmation bias (also confirmatory bias, myside bias, or congeniality bias) is the tendency to search for, interpret, favor and recall information in a way that confirms or supports one's prior beliefs, values, or decisions.", "takeaways": ["People display this bias when they select information that supports their views, ignoring contrary information or when they interpret ambiguous eviden…", "Explanations for the observed biases include wishful thinking and the limited human capacity to process information.", "A medical practitioner may prematurely focus on a particular disorder early in a diagnostic session, and then seek only confirming evidence."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "^VIX", "BTC-USD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confirmation_bias"},
    {"id": "endowment-effect", "level": "进阶", "category": "行为金融", "title": "Endowment effect——In psychology and behavioral economics, the endowment effect…", "summary": "In psychology and behavioral economics, the endowment effect, also known as divestiture aversion, is the finding that people are more likely to retain an object they own than acquire that same object when they do not own it.", "takeaways": ["In an exchange paradigm, people given a good are reluctant to trade it for another good of similar value.", "The distinction between this paradigm and the first two is that it is not incentive-compatible.", "However, this model has come under recent criticism as potentially inaccurate."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "^VIX", "BTC-USD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Endowment_effect"},
    {"id": "mental-accounting", "level": "进阶", "category": "行为金融", "title": "Mental accounting——Mental accounting (or psychological accounting) is a model o…", "summary": "Mental accounting (or psychological accounting) is a model of consumer behaviour developed by Richard Thaler that attempts to describe the process whereby people code, categorize and evaluate economic outcomes.", "takeaways": ["People are presumed to make mental accounts as a self control strategy to manage and keep track of their spending and resources.", "Through an increased understanding of mental accounting differences in decision making based on different resources, and different reactions based on …", "People can even have multiple mental accounts for the same kind of resource."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "^VIX", "BTC-USD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mental_accounting"},
    {"id": "framing-effect", "level": "进阶", "category": "行为金融", "title": "Framing effect (psychology)——Framing effect is a cognitive bias where people's decisions …", "summary": "Framing effect is a cognitive bias where people's decisions change depending on how options or statements are framed, even when they are logically identical. Studies show that when both choices are framed positively as gains, the majority of people prefer a certain gain over a probable gain.", "takeaways": ["Framing effect is a cognitive bias where people's decisions change depending on how options or statements are framed, even when they are logically ide…", "Gain and loss are defined within the scenario as outcomes, for example, lives lost or saved, patients treated or not treated, monetary gains or losses…", "The effect is reduced, or even eliminated, if ample credible information is provided to people."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "^VIX", "BTC-USD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Framing_effect_%28psychology%29"},
    {"id": "sunk-cost-fallacy", "level": "入门", "category": "行为金融", "title": "Sunk cost——In economics and business decision-making, a sunk cost (also…", "summary": "In economics and business decision-making, a sunk cost (also known as retrospective cost) is a cost that has already been incurred and cannot be recovered. Sunk costs are contrasted with prospective costs, which are future costs that may be avoided if action is taken.", "takeaways": ["In economics and business decision-making, a sunk cost (also known as retrospective cost) is a cost that has already been incurred and cannot be recovered.", "Sunk costs are contrasted with prospective costs, which are future costs that may be avoided if action is taken.", "In other words, a sunk cost is a sum paid in the past that should no longer be relevant to decisions about the future."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "^VIX", "BTC-USD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sunk_cost"},
    {"id": "regret-aversion", "level": "进阶", "category": "行为金融", "title": "Regret (decision theory)——In decision theory, regret aversion (or anticipated regret) …", "summary": "In decision theory, regret aversion (or anticipated regret) describes how the human emotional response of regret can influence decision-making under uncertainty. When individuals make choices without complete information, they often experience regret if they later discover that a different choice would have produced a…", "takeaways": ["In decision theory, regret aversion (or anticipated regret) describes how the human emotional response of regret can influence decision-making under u…", "This regret can be quantified as the difference in value between the actual decision made and what would have been the optimal decision in hindsight.", "Regret is a powerful negative emotion with significant social and reputational implications, playing a central role in how humans learn from experienc…"], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "^VIX", "BTC-USD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regret_%28decision_theory%29"},
    {"id": "gamblers-fallacy", "level": "入门", "category": "行为金融", "title": "Gambler's fallacy——The gambler's fallacy, also known as the Monte Carlo fallacy…", "summary": "The gambler's fallacy, also known as the Monte Carlo fallacy or the fallacy of the maturity of chances, is the belief that an independent and equally probable outcome which happened less frequently than expected is more likely to happen in the future (or vice versa).", "takeaways": ["了解Gambler's fallacy的基本定义和应用场景", "理解Gambler's fallacy在金融市场中的作用和影响", "结合市场数据观察Gambler's fallacy的实际表现"], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "^VIX", "BTC-USD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gambler%27s_fallacy"},
    {"id": "hindsight-bias", "level": "进阶", "category": "行为金融", "title": "Hindsight bias——Hindsight bias, also known as the knew-it-all-along phenomen…", "summary": "Hindsight bias, also known as the knew-it-all-along phenomenon or creeping determinism, is the common tendency for people to perceive past events as having been more predictable than they were.", "takeaways": ["Hindsight bias, also known as the knew-it-all-along phenomenon or creeping determinism, is the common tendency for people to perceive past events as having been more predictable than they were.", "After an event has occurred, people often believe that they could have predicted or perhaps even known with a high degree of certainty what the outcome of the event would be before it occurred."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "^VIX", "BTC-USD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hindsight_bias"},
    {"id": "availability-heuristic", "level": "入门", "category": "行为金融", "title": "Availability heuristic——The availability heuristic, also known as availability bias,…", "summary": "The availability heuristic, also known as availability bias, is a mental shortcut that relies on immediate examples that come to a given person's mind when evaluating a specific topic, concept, method, or decision.", "takeaways": ["The mental availability of an action's consequences is positively related to those consequences' perceived magnitude.", "In other words, the easier it is to recall the consequences of something, the greater those consequences are often perceived to be.", "Most notably, people often rely on the content of their recall if its implications are not called into question by the difficulty they have in recalling it."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "^VIX", "BTC-USD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Availability_heuristic"},
    {"id": "representativeness-heuristic", "level": "进阶", "category": "行为金融", "title": "Representativeness heuristic——The representativeness heuristic is used when making judgmen…", "summary": "The representativeness heuristic is used when making judgments about the probability of an event being representational in character and essence of a known prototypical event.", "takeaways": ["The representativeness heuristic is used when making judgments about the probability of an event being representational in character and essence of a …", "For example, if we only see a small sample of people from a particular group, we might overestimate the degree to which they are representative of the…", "Thus, it can result in neglect of relevant base rates and other cognitive biases."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "^VIX", "BTC-USD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Representativeness_heuristic"},
    {"id": "status-quo-bias", "level": "进阶", "category": "行为金融", "title": "Status quo bias——A status quo bias or default bias is a cognitive bias which …", "summary": "A status quo bias or default bias is a cognitive bias which results from a preference for the maintenance of one's existing state of affairs. The current baseline (or status quo) is taken as a reference point, and any change from that baseline is perceived as a loss or gain.", "takeaways": ["A status quo bias or default bias is a cognitive bias which results from a preference for the maintenance of one's existing state of affairs.", "The bias intersects with other non-rational cognitive processes such as loss aversion, in which losses comparative to gains are weighed to a greater e…", "Behaviour in regard to economics, retirement plans, health, and ethical choices show evidence of the status quo bias."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "^VIX", "BTC-USD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Status_quo_bias"},
    {"id": "ambiguity-aversion", "level": "进阶", "category": "行为金融", "title": "Ambiguity aversion——In decision theory and economics, ambiguity aversion (also k…", "summary": "In decision theory and economics, ambiguity aversion (also known as uncertainty aversion) is a preference for known risks over unknown risks. An ambiguity-averse individual would rather choose an alternative where the probability distribution of the outcomes is known over one where the probabilities are unknown.", "takeaways": ["In decision theory and economics, ambiguity aversion (also known as uncertainty aversion) is a preference for known risks over unknown risks.", "Risky events have a known probability distribution over outcomes while in ambiguous events the probability distribution is not known.", "The concept is expressed in the English proverb: \"Better the devil you know than the devil you don't.\""], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "^VIX", "BTC-USD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ambiguity_aversion"},
    {"id": "prospect-theory", "level": "进阶", "category": "行为金融", "title": "Prospect theory——Prospect theory is a theory of behavioral economics, judgmen…", "summary": "Prospect theory is a theory of behavioral economics, judgment and decision making that was developed by Daniel Kahneman and Amos Tversky in 1979. The theory was cited in the decision to award Kahneman the 2002 Nobel Memorial Prize in Economics.", "takeaways": ["Prospect theory is a theory of behavioral economics, judgment and decision making that was developed by Daniel Kahneman and Amos Tversky in 1979.", "Thus, contrary to the expected utility theory (which models the decision that perfectly rational agents would make), prospect theory aims to describe …", "It has since become one of the most influential frameworks in behavioral economics and behavioral finance, reshaping research on decision-making under…"], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "^VIX", "BTC-USD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prospect_theory"},
    {"id": "modern-portfolio-theory", "level": "进阶", "category": "组合管理", "title": "Modern portfolio theory——Modern portfolio theory (MPT), or mean-variance analysis, is…", "summary": "Modern portfolio theory (MPT), or mean-variance analysis, is a mathematical framework for assembling a portfolio of assets such that the expected return is maximized for a given level of risk.", "takeaways": ["Modern portfolio theory (MPT), or mean-variance analysis, is a mathematical framework for assembling a portfolio of assets such that the expected retu…", "Often, the historical variance and covariance of returns is used as a proxy for the forward-looking versions of these quantities, but other, more soph…", "The paper was obscure and only became known to economists of the English-speaking world in 2006."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "TLT", "GLD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modern_portfolio_theory"},
    {"id": "efficient-frontier", "level": "进阶", "category": "组合管理", "title": "Efficient frontier——In modern portfolio theory, the efficient frontier (or portf…", "summary": "In modern portfolio theory, the efficient frontier (or portfolio frontier) is an investment portfolio which occupies the \"efficient\" parts of the risk–return spectrum.", "takeaways": ["In modern portfolio theory, the efficient frontier (or portfolio frontier) is an investment portfolio which occupies the \"efficient\" parts of the risk–return spectrum.", "Formally, it is the set of portfolios which satisfy the condition that no other portfolio exists with a higher expected return but with the same standard deviation of return (i.e., the risk).", "The efficient frontier was first formulated by Harry Markowitz in 1952; \nsee Markowitz model."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "TLT", "GLD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Efficient_frontier"},
    {"id": "capital-allocation-line", "level": "进阶", "category": "组合管理", "title": "Capital allocation line——Capital allocation line (CAL) is a graph created by investor…", "summary": "Capital allocation line (CAL) is a graph created by investors to measure the risk of risky and risk-free assets. The graph displays the return to be made by taking on a certain level of risk. Its slope is known as the \"reward-to-variability ratio\".", "takeaways": ["Capital allocation line (CAL) is a graph created by investors to measure the risk of risky and risk-free assets.", "The graph displays the return to be made by taking on a certain level of risk.", "Its slope is known as the \"reward-to-variability ratio\"."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "TLT", "GLD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_allocation_line"},
    {"id": "capital-market-line", "level": "进阶", "category": "组合管理", "title": "Capital market line——Capital market line (CML) is the tangent line drawn from the…", "summary": "Capital market line (CML) is the tangent line drawn from the point of the risk-free asset to the feasible region for risky assets. The tangency point M represents the market portfolio, so named since all rational investors (minimum variance criterion) should hold their risky assets in the same proportions as their…", "takeaways": ["了解Capital market line的基本定义和应用场景", "理解Capital market line在金融市场中的作用和影响", "结合市场数据观察Capital market line的实际表现"], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "TLT", "GLD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_market_line"},
    {"id": "sortino-ratio", "level": "进阶", "category": "组合管理", "title": "Sortino ratio——The Sortino ratio measures the risk-adjusted return of an in…", "summary": "The Sortino ratio measures the risk-adjusted return of an investment asset, portfolio, or strategy. It is a modification of the Sharpe ratio but penalizes only those returns falling below a user-specified target or required rate of return, while the Sharpe ratio penalizes both upside and downside volatility equally.", "takeaways": ["The Sortino ratio measures the risk-adjusted return of an investment asset, portfolio, or strategy.", "The Sortino ratio is used as a way to compare the risk-adjusted performance of programs with differing risk and return profiles.", "In general, risk-adjusted returns seek to normalize the risk across programs and then see which has the higher return unit per risk."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "TLT", "GLD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sortino_ratio"},
    {"id": "treynor-ratio", "level": "进阶", "category": "组合管理", "title": "Treynor ratio——In finance, the Treynor reward-to-volatility model (sometime…", "summary": "In finance, the Treynor reward-to-volatility model (sometimes called the reward-to-volatility ratio or Treynor measure), named after American economist Jack L. Treynor, is a measurement of the returns earned in excess of that which could have been earned on an investment that has no risk that can be diversified (e.g.,…", "takeaways": ["In finance, the Treynor reward-to-volatility model (sometimes called the reward-to-volatility ratio or Treynor measure), named after American economist Jack L.", "The Treynor ratio relates excess return over the risk-free rate to the additional risk taken; however, systematic risk is used instead of total risk.", "The higher the Treynor ratio, the better the performance of the portfolio under analysis."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "TLT", "GLD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treynor_ratio"},
    {"id": "information-ratio", "level": "进阶", "category": "组合管理", "title": "Information ratio——The information ratio measures and compares the active retur…", "summary": "The information ratio measures and compares the active return of an investment (e.g., a security or portfolio) compared to a benchmark index relative to the volatility of the active return (also known as active risk or benchmark tracking risk).", "takeaways": ["It represents the additional amount of return that an investor receives per unit of increase in risk.", "The higher the information ratio, the higher the active return of the portfolio, given the amount of risk taken, and the better the manager.", "The Sharpe ratio is useful for an attribution of the absolute returns of a portfolio, and the information ratio is useful for an attribution of the re…"], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "TLT", "GLD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Information_ratio"},
    {"id": "alpha-finance", "level": "进阶", "category": "组合管理", "title": "Alpha (finance)——Alpha is a measure of the active return on an investment, th…", "summary": "Alpha is a measure of the active return on an investment, the performance of that investment compared with a suitable market index. An alpha of 1% means the investment's return on investment over a selected period of time was 1% better than the market during that same period; a negative alpha means the investment…", "takeaways": ["Alpha is a measure of the active return on an investment, the performance of that investment compared with a suitable market index.", "Historically, the vast majority of traditional funds have had negative alphas, which has led to a flight of capital to index funds and non-traditional…", "This is useful for non-traditional or highly focused funds, where a single stock index might not be representative of the investment's holdings."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "TLT", "GLD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alpha_%28finance%29"},
    {"id": "r-squared", "level": "进阶", "category": "组合管理", "title": "Coefficient of determination——In statistics, the coefficient of determination, denoted R2 …", "summary": "In statistics, the coefficient of determination, denoted R2 or r2 and pronounced \"R squared\", is the proportion of the variation in the dependent variable that is predictable from the independent variable(s).", "takeaways": ["It is a statistic used in the context of statistical models whose main purpose is either the prediction of future outcomes or the testing of hypothese…", "In both such cases, the coefficient of determination is always smaller than 1 and usually greater than 0.", "When evaluating the goodness-of-fit of simulated (Ypred) versus measured (Yobs) values, it is not appropriate to base this on the R2 of the linear reg…"], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "TLT", "GLD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coefficient_of_determination"},
    {"id": "max-drawdown", "level": "进阶", "category": "组合管理", "title": "Drawdown (economics)——The drawdown is the measure of the decline from a historical…", "summary": "The drawdown is the measure of the decline from a historical peak in some variable (typically the cumulative profit or total open equity of a financial trading strategy).", "takeaways": ["了解Drawdown (economics)的基本定义和应用场景", "理解Drawdown (economics)在金融市场中的作用和影响", "结合市场数据观察Drawdown (economics)的实际表现"], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "TLT", "GLD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maximum_drawdown"},
    {"id": "calmar-ratio", "level": "进阶", "category": "组合管理", "title": "Calmar ratio——Calmar ratio (or Drawdown ratio) is a performance measuremen…", "summary": "Calmar ratio (or Drawdown ratio) is a performance measurement used to evaluate Commodity Trading Advisors and hedge funds. It was created by Terry W. Young and first published in 1991 in the trade journal Futures.", "takeaways": ["Calmar ratio (or Drawdown ratio) is a performance measurement used to evaluate Commodity Trading Advisors and hedge funds.", "Young owned California Managed Accounts, a firm in Santa Ynez, California, which managed client funds and published the newsletter CMA Reports.", "Later versions of the Calmar ratio introduce the risk free rate into the numerator to create a Sharpe type ratio."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "TLT", "GLD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calmar_ratio"},
    {"id": "risk-parity", "level": "进阶", "category": "组合管理", "title": "Risk parity——Risk parity (or risk premia parity) is an approach to invest…", "summary": "Risk parity (or risk premia parity) is an approach to investment management which focuses on allocation of risk, usually defined as volatility, rather than allocation of capital.", "takeaways": ["Risk parity (or risk premia parity) is an approach to investment management which focuses on allocation of risk, usually defined as volatility, rather…", "In recent years many investment companies have begun offering risk parity funds to their clients.", "Interest in the risk parity approach has increased since the 2008 financial crisis as the risk parity approach fared better than traditionally constru…"], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "TLT", "GLD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Risk_parity"},
    {"id": "black-litterman", "level": "进阶", "category": "组合管理", "title": "Black–Litterman model——In finance, the Black–Litterman model is a mathematical mode…", "summary": "In finance, the Black–Litterman model is a mathematical model for portfolio allocation developed in 1990 at Goldman Sachs by Fischer Black and Robert Litterman. It seeks to overcome problems that institutional investors have encountered in applying modern portfolio theory in practice.", "takeaways": ["In finance, the Black–Litterman model is a mathematical model for portfolio allocation developed in 1990 at Goldman Sachs by Fischer Black and Robert Litterman.", "It seeks to overcome problems that institutional investors have encountered in applying modern portfolio theory in practice."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "TLT", "GLD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Black%E2%80%93Litterman_model"},
    {"id": "rebalancing-portfolio", "level": "入门", "category": "组合管理", "title": "Rebalancing investments——In finance and investing, rebalancing of investments (or con…", "summary": "In finance and investing, rebalancing of investments (or constant mix) is a strategy of bringing a portfolio that has deviated away from one's target asset allocation back into line.", "takeaways": ["了解Rebalancing investments的基本定义和应用场景", "理解Rebalancing investments在金融市场中的作用和影响", "结合市场数据观察Rebalancing investments的实际表现"], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "TLT", "GLD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rebalancing_investments"},
    {"id": "asset-allocation", "level": "入门", "category": "组合管理", "title": "Asset allocation——Asset allocation is the implementation of an investment stra…", "summary": "Asset allocation is the implementation of an investment strategy that attempts to balance risk versus reward by adjusting the percentage of each asset in an investment portfolio according to the investor's risk tolerance, goals and investment time frame. The focus is on the characteristics of the overall portfolio.", "takeaways": ["The focus is on the characteristics of the overall portfolio.", "Such a strategy contrasts with an approach that focuses on individual assets."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "TLT", "GLD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Asset_allocation"},
    {"id": "diversification", "level": "入门", "category": "组合管理", "title": "Diversification (finance)——In finance, diversification is the process of allocating cap…", "summary": "In finance, diversification is the process of allocating capital in a way that reduces the exposure to any one particular asset or risk. A common path towards diversification is to reduce risk or volatility by investing in a variety of assets.", "takeaways": ["In finance, diversification is the process of allocating capital in a way that reduces the exposure to any one particular asset or risk.", "A common path towards diversification is to reduce risk or volatility by investing in a variety of assets.", "Diversification is one of two general techniques for reducing investment risk."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "TLT", "GLD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diversification_%28finance%29"},
    {"id": "barbell-strategy", "level": "进阶", "category": "组合管理", "title": "Barbell strategy——In finance, a barbell strategy is formed when a trader inves…", "summary": "In finance, a barbell strategy is formed when a trader invests in long- and short-duration bonds, but does not invest in intermediate-duration bonds. This strategy is useful when interest rates are rising; as the short term maturities are rolled over they receive a higher interest rate, raising the value.", "takeaways": ["In finance, a barbell strategy is formed when a trader invests in long- and short-duration bonds, but does not invest in intermediate-duration bonds.", "This strategy is useful when interest rates are rising; as the short term maturities are rolled over they receive a higher interest rate, raising the value.", "A contrasting strategy is the bullet strategy, which involves investing only in intermediate-term bonds."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "TLT", "GLD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barbell_strategy"},
    {"id": "factor-investing", "level": "进阶", "category": "因子投资", "title": "Factor investing——Factor investing is an investment approach that targets meas…", "summary": "Factor investing is an investment approach that targets measurable characteristics of securities, known as factors, which help explain differences in risk and return. Commonly studied equity factors include size, value, momentum, quality, and low volatility.", "takeaways": ["Factor investing is an investment approach that targets measurable characteristics of securities, known as factors, which help explain differences in …", "A factor-based investment strategy typically involves tilting portfolios toward or away from these characteristics in an attempt to capture long-term …", "Factor investing has been documented not only in equities but also in corporate bonds, government bonds, currencies, and commodities."], "marketLinks": ["VTV", "MTUM", "QUAL"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Factor_investing"},
    {"id": "value-factor", "level": "进阶", "category": "因子投资", "title": "Value investing——Value investing is an investment paradigm that involves buyi…", "summary": "Value investing is an investment paradigm that involves buying securities that appear underpriced by some form of fundamental analysis. Modern value investing derives from the investment philosophy taught by Benjamin Graham and David Dodd at Columbia Business School starting in 1928 and subsequently developed in their…", "takeaways": ["Value investing is an investment paradigm that  involves buying securities that appear underpriced by some form of fundamental analysis.", "Hedge fund manager Seth Klarman has described value investing as rooted in a rejection of the efficient-market hypothesis (EMH).", "The term has also led to misinterpretation of his principles - most notably the notion that Graham simply recommended cheap stocks."], "marketLinks": ["VTV", "MTUM", "QUAL"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Value_investing"},
    {"id": "momentum-factor", "level": "进阶", "category": "因子投资", "title": "Momentum investing——Momentum investing is a system of buying stocks or other sec…", "summary": "Momentum investing is a system of buying stocks or other securities that have had high returns over the past three-to-twelve months, and selling those that have had poor returns over the same period.", "takeaways": ["Momentum investing is a system of buying stocks or other securities that have had high returns over the past three-to-twelve months, and selling those…", "Seasonal or calendar effects may help to explain some of the reason for success in the momentum investing strategy.", "Once the reason for tax selling is eliminated, the stock's price tends to recover."], "marketLinks": ["VTV", "MTUM", "QUAL"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Momentum_investing"},
    {"id": "size-factor", "level": "进阶", "category": "因子投资", "title": "Size premium——The size premium is the historical tendency for the stocks o…", "summary": "The size premium is the historical tendency for the stocks of firms with smaller market capitalizations to outperform the stocks of firms with larger market capitalizations. It is one of the factors in the Fama–French three-factor model.", "takeaways": ["The size premium is the historical tendency for the stocks of firms with smaller market capitalizations to outperform the stocks of firms with larger market capitalizations.", "It is one of the factors in the Fama–French three-factor model."], "marketLinks": ["VTV", "MTUM", "QUAL"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Size_premium"},
    {"id": "quality-factor", "level": "进阶", "category": "因子投资", "title": "Quality investing——Quality investing is an investment strategy based on a set o…", "summary": "Quality investing is an investment strategy based on a set of clearly defined fundamental criteria that seeks to identify companies with outstanding quality characteristics. The quality assessment is made based on soft (e.g. management credibility) and hard criteria (e.g. balance sheet stability).", "takeaways": ["Quality investing is an investment strategy based on a set of clearly defined fundamental criteria that seeks to identify companies with outstanding q…", "management credibility) and hard criteria (e.g.", "Quality investing supports best overall rather than best-in-class approach."], "marketLinks": ["VTV", "MTUM", "QUAL"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quality_investing"},
    {"id": "low-volatility-factor", "level": "进阶", "category": "因子投资", "title": "Low-volatility investing——Low-volatility investing is an investment style that buys st…", "summary": "Low-volatility investing is an investment style that buys stocks or securities with low volatility and avoids those with high volatility. This investment style exploits the low-volatility anomaly. According to financial theory risk and return should be positively related, however in practice this is not true.", "takeaways": ["Low-volatility investing is an investment style that buys stocks or securities with low volatility and avoids those with high volatility.", "According to financial theory risk and return should be positively related, however in practice this is not true.", "This investment style is also referred to as minimum volatility, minimum variance, managed volatility, smart beta, defensive and conservative investin…"], "marketLinks": ["VTV", "MTUM", "QUAL"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Low-volatility_investing"},
    {"id": "smart-beta", "level": "进阶", "category": "因子投资", "title": "Smart beta——Smart beta investment portfolios are long-only rules-based i…", "summary": "Smart beta investment portfolios are long-only rules-based investment strategies that aim to outperform a capitalization-weighted benchmark. A comprehensive analysis of smart beta strategies has found that smart beta strategies have underperformed by 1% on average since launch.", "takeaways": ["Smart beta investment portfolios are long-only rules-based investment strategies that aim to outperform a capitalization-weighted benchmark.", "A comprehensive analysis of smart beta strategies has found that smart beta strategies have underperformed by 1% on average since launch.", "The term smart beta was originally coined by Willis Towers Watson in 2006 referring to the fundamental index."], "marketLinks": ["VTV", "MTUM", "QUAL"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Smart_beta"},
    {"id": "fama-french", "level": "进阶", "category": "因子投资", "title": "Fama–French three-factor model——In asset pricing and portfolio management, the Fama–French t…", "summary": "In asset pricing and portfolio management, the Fama–French three-factor model is a statistical model designed in 1992 by Eugene Fama and Kenneth French to describe stock returns. Fama and French were colleagues at the University of Chicago Booth School of Business, where Fama still works.", "takeaways": ["In asset pricing and portfolio management, the Fama–French three-factor model is a statistical model designed in 1992 by Eugene Fama and Kenneth French to describe stock returns.", "Fama and French were colleagues at the University of Chicago Booth School of Business, where Fama still works.", "In 2013, Fama shared the Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences for his empirical analysis of asset prices."], "marketLinks": ["VTV", "MTUM", "QUAL"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fama%E2%80%93French_three-factor_model"},
    {"id": "carhart-four-factor", "level": "进阶", "category": "因子投资", "title": "Carhart four-factor model——In portfolio management, the Carhart four-factor model is an…", "summary": "In portfolio management, the Carhart four-factor model is an extra factor addition in the Fama–French three-factor model, proposed by Mark Carhart. The Fama-French model, developed in the 1990s, argued most stock market returns are explained by three factors: market beta (stocks more volatile than the broad market…", "takeaways": ["In portfolio management, the Carhart four-factor model is an extra factor addition in the Fama–French three-factor model, proposed by Mark Carhart.", "The Four Factor Model is also known in the industry as the Monthly Momentum Factor (MOM).", "Momentum is the speed or velocity of price changes in a stock, security, or tradable instrument."], "marketLinks": ["VTV", "MTUM", "QUAL"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carhart_four-factor_model"},
    {"id": "factor-crowding", "level": "进阶", "category": "因子投资", "title": "Factor investing——Factor investing is an investment approach that targets meas…", "summary": "Factor investing is an investment approach that targets measurable characteristics of securities, known as factors, which help explain differences in risk and return. Commonly studied equity factors include size, value, momentum, quality, and low volatility.", "takeaways": ["Factor investing is an investment approach that targets measurable characteristics of securities, known as factors, which help explain differences in …", "A factor-based investment strategy typically involves tilting portfolios toward or away from these characteristics in an attempt to capture long-term …", "Factor investing has been documented not only in equities but also in corporate bonds, government bonds, currencies, and commodities."], "marketLinks": ["VTV", "MTUM", "QUAL"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Factor_investing"},
    {"id": "factor-timing", "level": "进阶", "category": "因子投资", "title": "Market timing——Market timing is the strategy of making buying or selling de…", "summary": "Market timing is the strategy of making buying or selling decisions of financial assets (often stocks) by attempting to predict future market price movements (market trends). The prediction may be based on an outlook of market or economic conditions resulting from technical or fundamental analysis.", "takeaways": ["Market timing is the strategy of making buying or selling decisions of financial assets (often stocks) by attempting to predict future market price mo…", "This is an investment strategy based on the outlook for an aggregate market rather than for a particular financial asset.", "The efficient-market hypothesis is an assumption that asset prices reflect all available information, meaning that it is theoretically impossible to s…"], "marketLinks": ["VTV", "MTUM", "QUAL"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Market_timing"},
    {"id": "fundamental-indexing", "level": "进阶", "category": "因子投资", "title": "Fundamentally based indexes——Fundamentally based indexes or fundamental indexes, also cal…", "summary": "Fundamentally based indexes or fundamental indexes, also called fundamentally weighted indexes, are indexes in which stocks are weighted according to factors related to their fundamentals such as earnings, dividends and assets, commonly used when performing corporate valuations.", "takeaways": ["Indexes that use a composite of several fundamental factors attempt to average out sector biases that may arise from relying on a single fundamental f…", "Fundamental indices are often contrasted to capitalization-weighted indices.", "a capitalization-weighted index, which is for example explicitly shown in a Swedish context by Olof Andersson (2009) in his Thesis \"Irrational Indexat…"], "marketLinks": ["VTV", "MTUM", "QUAL"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fundamental_indexing"},
    {"id": "cap-weighted-index", "level": "入门", "category": "因子投资", "title": "Capitalization-weighted index——A capitalization-weighted (or cap-weighted) index, also call…", "summary": "A capitalization-weighted (or cap-weighted) index, also called a market-value-weighted index is a stock market index whose components are weighted according to the total market value of their outstanding shares. Every day an individual stock's price changes and thereby changes a stock index's value.", "takeaways": ["Every day an individual stock's price changes and thereby changes a stock index's value.", "The weighting of each component shifts with changes to each securities' price and the number of shares outstanding.", "Stock market indices are a type of economic index."], "marketLinks": ["VTV", "MTUM", "QUAL"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capitalization-weighted_index"},
    {"id": "foreign-exchange", "level": "入门", "category": "外汇", "title": "Foreign exchange market——The foreign exchange market (forex, FX, or currency market) …", "summary": "The foreign exchange market (forex, FX, or currency market) is a global decentralized or over-the-counter (OTC) market for the trading of currencies. This market determines foreign exchange rates for every currency. By trading volume, it is by far the largest market in the world, followed by the credit market.", "takeaways": ["The foreign exchange market (forex, FX, or currency market) is a global decentralized or over-the-counter (OTC) market for the trading of currencies.", "Because of the sovereignty issue when involving two currencies, Forex has little supervisory entity regulating its actions.", "Measured by value, foreign exchange swaps were traded more than any other instrument in 2025, at US$4 trillion per day, followed by spot trading at US…"], "marketLinks": ["DX-Y.NYB", "EURUSD=X", "JPY=X"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Foreign_exchange_market"},
    {"id": "currency-pair", "level": "入门", "category": "外汇", "title": "Currency pair——A currency pair is the quotation of the relative value of a …", "summary": "A currency pair is the quotation of the relative value of a currency unit against the unit of another currency in the foreign exchange market. The currency that is used as the reference is called the counter currency, quote currency, or currency and the currency that is quoted in relation is called the base currency…", "takeaways": ["A currency pair is the quotation of the relative value of a currency unit against the unit of another currency in the foreign exchange market.", "The quotation EUR/USD 1.2500 means that one euro is exchanged for 1.2500 US dollars.", "They involve the currencies euro, US dollar, pound sterling, Australian dollar, Canadian dollar, and the Swiss franc."], "marketLinks": ["DX-Y.NYB", "EURUSD=X", "JPY=X"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Currency_pair"},
    {"id": "exchange-rate", "level": "入门", "category": "外汇", "title": "Exchange rate——In finance, an exchange rate is the rate at which one curren…", "summary": "In finance, an exchange rate is the rate at which one currency will be exchanged for another currency. Currencies are most commonly national currencies, but may be sub-national as in the case of Hong Kong or supra-national as in the case of the euro.", "takeaways": ["In  finance, an exchange rate is the rate at which one currency will be exchanged for another currency.", "There is no agreement in the economic literature on the optimal national exchange rate policy (unlike on the subject of trade where free trade is cons…", "On the other hand, cash is available for resale immediately, but incurs security, storage, and transportation costs, and the cost of tying up capital …"], "marketLinks": ["DX-Y.NYB", "EURUSD=X", "JPY=X"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exchange_rate"},
    {"id": "fixed-exchange-rate", "level": "进阶", "category": "外汇", "title": "Fixed exchange rate system——A fixed exchange rate, often called a pegged exchange rate o…", "summary": "A fixed exchange rate, often called a pegged exchange rate or pegging, is a type of exchange rate regime in which a currency's value is fixed, or pegged, by a monetary authority against the value of another currency, a basket of other currencies, or another measure of value, such as gold or silver.", "takeaways": ["There are benefits and risks to using a fixed exchange rate system.", "In addition, according to the Mundell–Fleming model, with perfect capital mobility, a fixed exchange rate prevents a government from using domestic mo…", "The European Exchange Rate Mechanism is also used on a temporary basis to establish a final conversion rate against the euro from the local currencies…"], "marketLinks": ["DX-Y.NYB", "EURUSD=X", "JPY=X"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fixed_exchange_rate_system"},
    {"id": "floating-exchange-rate", "level": "进阶", "category": "外汇", "title": "Floating exchange rate——In macroeconomics and economic policy, a floating exchange r…", "summary": "In macroeconomics and economic policy, a floating exchange rate (also known as a fluctuating or flexible exchange rate) is a type of exchange rate regime in which a currency's value is allowed to fluctuate in response to international events affecting exchange rates.", "takeaways": ["A currency that uses a floating exchange rate is known as a floating currency.", "The Canadian dollar has not seen interference by the Canadian national bank with its price since September 1998.", "When a currency floats, quantities other than the exchange rate itself are used to administer monetary policy (see open-market operations)."], "marketLinks": ["DX-Y.NYB", "EURUSD=X", "JPY=X"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Floating_exchange_rate"},
    {"id": "purchasing-power-parity", "level": "进阶", "category": "外汇", "title": "Purchasing power parity——Purchasing power parity (PPP) is a measure of the price of s…", "summary": "Purchasing power parity (PPP) is a measure of the price of specific goods in different countries and is used to compare the absolute purchasing power of the countries' currencies.", "takeaways": ["Purchasing power parity (PPP) is a measure of the price of specific goods in different countries and is used to compare the absolute purchasing power …", "The PPP inflation and exchange rate may differ from the market exchange rate because of tariffs and other transaction costs.", "People in different countries typically consume different quantities of goods so it is necessary to compare the cost of quantities of goods and servic…"], "marketLinks": ["DX-Y.NYB", "EURUSD=X", "JPY=X"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Purchasing_power_parity"},
    {"id": "interest-rate-parity", "level": "进阶", "category": "外汇", "title": "Interest rate parity——Interest rate parity is a no-arbitrage condition representin…", "summary": "Interest rate parity is a no-arbitrage condition representing an equilibrium state under which investors compare interest rates available on bank deposits in two countries. The fact that this condition does not always hold allows for potential opportunities to earn riskless profits from covered interest arbitrage.", "takeaways": ["Interest rate parity is a no-arbitrage condition representing an equilibrium state under which investors compare interest rates available on bank depo…", "Each form of the parity condition demonstrates a unique relationship with implications for the forecasting of future exchange rates: the forward excha…", "This relationship generally holds strongly over longer terms and among emerging market countries."], "marketLinks": ["DX-Y.NYB", "EURUSD=X", "JPY=X"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Interest_rate_parity"},
    {"id": "carry-trade", "level": "进阶", "category": "外汇", "title": "Carry (investment)——The carry of an asset is the return obtained from holding it…", "summary": "The carry of an asset is the return obtained from holding it (if positive), or the cost of holding it (if negative) (see also Cost of carry). For instance, commodities are usually negative carry assets, as they incur storage costs or may suffer from depreciation.", "takeaways": ["The carry of an asset is the return obtained from holding it (if positive), or the cost of holding it (if negative) (see also Cost of carry).", "For instance, commodities are usually negative carry assets, as they incur storage costs or may suffer from depreciation.", "Carry trades are not usually arbitrages: pure arbitrages make money no matter what; carry trades make money only if nothing changes against the carry's favor."], "marketLinks": ["DX-Y.NYB", "EURUSD=X", "JPY=X"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carry_%28investment%29"},
    {"id": "forex-reserves", "level": "入门", "category": "外汇", "title": "Foreign exchange reserves——Foreign exchange reserves (also called forex reserves or FX …", "summary": "Foreign exchange reserves (also called forex reserves or FX reserves) are cash and other reserve assets such as gold and silver held by a central bank or other monetary authority that are primarily available to balance payments of the country, influence the foreign exchange rate of its currency, and to maintain…", "takeaways": ["Reserves are held in one or more reserve currencies, mostly the United States dollar and to a lesser extent the euro.", "From time to time they may be physically moved to the home or another country.", "The central bank also incurs opportunity costs from holding the reserve assets (especially cash holdings) and from their storage, security costs, etc."], "marketLinks": ["DX-Y.NYB", "EURUSD=X", "JPY=X"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Foreign_exchange_reserves"},
    {"id": "currency-intervention", "level": "进阶", "category": "外汇", "title": "Currency intervention——Currency intervention, also known as foreign exchange market…", "summary": "Currency intervention, also known as foreign exchange market intervention or currency manipulation, is a monetary policy operation. It occurs when a government or central bank buys or sells foreign currency in exchange for its own domestic currency, generally with the intention of influencing the exchange rate and…", "takeaways": ["Currency intervention, also known as foreign exchange market intervention or currency manipulation, is a monetary policy operation.", "Policymakers may intervene in foreign exchange markets in order to advance a variety of economic objectives: controlling inflation, maintaining compet…", "The most complete type of currency intervention is the imposition of a fixed exchange rate with respect to some other currency or to a weighted averag…"], "marketLinks": ["DX-Y.NYB", "EURUSD=X", "JPY=X"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Currency_intervention"},
    {"id": "devaluation", "level": "进阶", "category": "外汇", "title": "Devaluation——In macroeconomics and modern monetary policy, a devaluation …", "summary": "In macroeconomics and modern monetary policy, a devaluation is an official lowering of the value of a country's currency within a fixed exchange rate system, in which a monetary authority formally sets a lower exchange rate of the national currency in relation to a foreign reference currency or currency basket.", "takeaways": ["The opposite of devaluation, a change in the exchange rate making the domestic currency more expensive, is called a revaluation.", "Related but distinct concepts include inflation, which is a market-determined decline in the value of the currency in terms of goods and services (related to its purchasing power).", "Altering the face value of a currency without reducing its exchange rate is a redenomination, not a devaluation or revaluation."], "marketLinks": ["DX-Y.NYB", "EURUSD=X", "JPY=X"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Devaluation"},
    {"id": "currency-peg", "level": "进阶", "category": "外汇", "title": "Fixed exchange rate system——A fixed exchange rate, often called a pegged exchange rate o…", "summary": "A fixed exchange rate, often called a pegged exchange rate or pegging, is a type of exchange rate regime in which a currency's value is fixed, or pegged, by a monetary authority against the value of another currency, a basket of other currencies, or another measure of value, such as gold or silver.", "takeaways": ["There are benefits and risks to using a fixed exchange rate system.", "In addition, according to the Mundell–Fleming model, with perfect capital mobility, a fixed exchange rate prevents a government from using domestic mo…", "The European Exchange Rate Mechanism is also used on a temporary basis to establish a final conversion rate against the euro from the local currencies…"], "marketLinks": ["DX-Y.NYB", "EURUSD=X", "JPY=X"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fixed_exchange_rate_system"},
    {"id": "forex-swap", "level": "进阶", "category": "外汇", "title": "Foreign exchange swap——In finance, a foreign exchange swap, forex swap, or FX swap …", "summary": "In finance, a foreign exchange swap, forex swap, or FX swap is a simultaneous purchase and sale of identical amounts of one currency for another with two different value dates (normally spot to forward) and may use foreign exchange derivatives.", "takeaways": ["An FX swap allows sums of a certain currency to be used to fund charges designated in another currency without acquiring foreign exchange risk.", "It permits companies that have funds in different currencies to manage them efficiently."], "marketLinks": ["DX-Y.NYB", "EURUSD=X", "JPY=X"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Foreign_exchange_swap"},
    {"id": "britton-woods", "level": "入门", "category": "外汇", "title": "Bretton Woods system——The Bretton Woods system of monetary management established …", "summary": "The Bretton Woods system of monetary management established the rules for commercial relations among 44 countries, including the United States, Canada, European countries, and Australia, after the 1944 Bretton Woods Agreement until the Jamaica Accords in 1976.", "takeaways": ["The Bretton Woods system was the first example of a fully negotiated monetary order intended to govern monetary relations among independent states.", "These organizations became operational in 1945 after a sufficient number of countries had ratified the agreement.", "They also note that the IMF and World Bank often imposed policy conditions that placed significant strain on developing countries and restrict the fle…"], "marketLinks": ["DX-Y.NYB", "EURUSD=X", "JPY=X"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bretton_Woods_system"},
    {"id": "special-drawing-rights", "level": "进阶", "category": "外汇", "title": "Special drawing rights——Special drawing rights (SDRs, code XDR) are a supplementary …", "summary": "Special drawing rights (SDRs, code XDR) are a supplementary foreign exchange reserve asset defined and maintained by the International Monetary Fund (IMF). SDRs are the units of account for the IMF, and not a currency; rather, SDR value is based on a basket of currencies; the currency choice is reviewed every five…", "takeaways": ["Special drawing rights (SDRs, code XDR) are a supplementary foreign exchange reserve asset defined and maintained by the International Monetary Fund (…", "During the 2008 financial crisis, an additional XDR 182.6 billion was allocated to \"provide liquidity to the global economic system and supplement mem…", "dollar 43.38%, euro 29.31%, Chinese yuan 12.28%, Japanese yen 7.59%, British pound sterling 7.44%."], "marketLinks": ["DX-Y.NYB", "EURUSD=X", "JPY=X"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special_drawing_rights"},
    {"id": "commodity-market", "level": "入门", "category": "商品", "title": "Commodity market——A commodity market is a market that trades in the primary ec…", "summary": "A commodity market is a market that trades in the primary economic sector rather than manufactured products. The primary sector includes agricultural products, energy products, and metals. Soft commodities may be perishable and harvested, while hard commodities are usually mined, such as gold and oil.", "takeaways": ["A commodity market is a market that trades in the primary economic sector rather than manufactured products.", "Derivatives are either exchange-traded or over-the-counter (OTC).", "According to the World Gold Council, ETFs allow investors to be exposed to the gold market without the risk of price volatility associated with gold a…"], "marketLinks": ["CL=F", "GC=F", "DBC"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Commodity_market"},
    {"id": "spot-price", "level": "入门", "category": "商品", "title": "Spot contract——In finance, a spot contract, spot transaction, or simply spo…", "summary": "In finance, a spot contract, spot transaction, or simply spot, is a contract of buying or selling a commodity, security or currency for immediate settlement (payment and delivery) on the spot date, which is normally two business days after the trade date.", "takeaways": ["The settlement price (or rate) is called spot price (or spot rate).", "A spot contract is in contrast with a forward contract or futures contract where contract terms are agreed now but delivery and payment will occur at a future date."], "marketLinks": ["CL=F", "GC=F", "DBC"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spot_contract"},
    {"id": "futures-price", "level": "入门", "category": "商品", "title": "Futures exchange——A futures exchange or futures market is a central financial …", "summary": "A futures exchange or futures market is a central financial exchange where people can trade standardized futures contracts defined by the exchange. Futures contracts are derivatives contracts to buy or sell specific quantities of a commodity or financial instrument at a specified price with delivery set at a specified…", "takeaways": ["A futures exchange or futures market is a central financial exchange where people can trade standardized futures contracts defined by the exchange.", "Futures exchanges can be organized as non-profit member-owned organizations or as for-profit organizations.", "For-profit futures exchanges earn most of their revenue from trading and clearing fees, and are often public corporations."], "marketLinks": ["CL=F", "GC=F", "DBC"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Futures_exchange"},
    {"id": "contango", "level": "进阶", "category": "商品", "title": "Contango——Contango is a situation in which the futures price (or forwa…", "summary": "Contango is a situation in which the futures price (or forward price) of a commodity is higher than the spot price. In a contango situation, arbitrageurs or speculators are \"willing to pay more for a commodity at some point in the future than to purchase the commodity immediately.", "takeaways": ["Contango is a situation in which the futures price (or forward price) of a commodity is higher than the spot price.", "The futures or forward curve would typically be upward sloping (i.e., \"normal\"), since contracts for further dates would typically trade at even highe…", "For perishable commodities, price differences between near and far delivery are not a contango."], "marketLinks": ["CL=F", "GC=F", "DBC"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Contango"},
    {"id": "backwardation", "level": "进阶", "category": "商品", "title": "Backwardation——Backwardation is a market condition where the price of a com…", "summary": "Backwardation is a market condition where the price of a commodity's forward or futures contract price is trading below the spot price. The opposite of backwardation is contango, when the futures price is higher than the spot price.", "takeaways": ["Backwardation is a market condition where the price of a commodity's forward or futures contract price is trading below the spot price.", "However, the forward price may be lower than this positive basis (unless storage is difficult or impossible), and may even be negative (backwardation)…", "Negative lease rates for silver may indicate bullion banks require a risk premium for selling silver futures into the market."], "marketLinks": ["CL=F", "GC=F", "DBC"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Backwardation"},
    {"id": "crude-oil-types", "level": "入门", "category": "商品", "title": "Benchmark (crude oil)——A benchmark crude or marker crude is a crude oil that serves…", "summary": "A benchmark crude or marker crude is a crude oil that serves as a reference price for buyers and sellers of crude oil. There are three primary benchmarks, West Texas Intermediate (WTI), Brent Blend, and Dubai Crude.", "takeaways": ["A benchmark crude or marker crude is a crude oil that serves as a reference price for buyers and sellers of crude oil.", "Benchmarks are used because there are many different varieties and grades of crude oil.", "This is the price that controls world oil market price."], "marketLinks": ["CL=F", "GC=F", "DBC"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Benchmark_%28crude_oil%29"},
    {"id": "opec", "level": "入门", "category": "商品", "title": "OPEC——The Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC …", "summary": "The Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC OH-pek) is an intergovernmental cartel enabling the co-operation of leading oil-producing and oil-dependent countries in order to collectively influence the global oil market and maximize profit.", "takeaways": ["It was founded on 14 September 1960 in Baghdad by the first five members: Iran, Iraq, Kuwait, Saudi Arabia and Venezuela.", "Economists have characterized OPEC as a textbook example of a cartel, a group whose members cooperate to reduce market competition and obtain monopoly…", "The United Arab Emirates left both OPEC and OPEC+ in 2026."], "marketLinks": ["CL=F", "GC=F", "DBC"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/OPEC"},
    {"id": "gold-reserve", "level": "入门", "category": "商品", "title": "Gold reserve——A gold reserve is the gold held by a national central bank, …", "summary": "A gold reserve is the gold held by a national central bank, mostly in a country, intended mainly as a guarantee to redeem promises to pay depositors, note holders (e.g. paper money), or trading peers, during the eras of the gold standard, and also as a store of value, or to support the value of the national currency.", "takeaways": ["A gold reserve is the gold held by a national central bank, mostly in a country, intended mainly as a guarantee to redeem promises to pay depositors, …", "The World Gold Council estimates that all the gold ever mined, and that is accounted for, totalled 190,040 tonnes in 2019 but other independent estima…", "The total value of all gold ever mined, and that is accounted for, would exceed $27 trillion at that valuation and using WGC 2017 estimates."], "marketLinks": ["CL=F", "GC=F", "DBC"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gold_reserve"},
    {"id": "london-metal-exchange", "level": "进阶", "category": "商品", "title": "London Metal Exchange——The London Metal Exchange (LME) is a futures and forwards ex…", "summary": "The London Metal Exchange (LME) is a futures and forwards exchange in London, United Kingdom with the world's largest market in standardised forward contracts, futures contracts and options on base metals. The exchange also offers contracts on ferrous metals and precious metals.", "takeaways": ["The exchange also offers contracts on ferrous metals and precious metals.", "The company also allows for cash trading.", "It offers hedging, worldwide reference pricing, and the option of physical delivery to settle contracts."], "marketLinks": ["CL=F", "GC=F", "DBC"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/London_Metal_Exchange"},
    {"id": "agricultural-commodities", "level": "入门", "category": "商品", "title": "Commodity market——A commodity market is a market that trades in the primary ec…", "summary": "A commodity market is a market that trades in the primary economic sector rather than manufactured products. The primary sector includes agricultural products, energy products, and metals. Soft commodities may be perishable and harvested, while hard commodities are usually mined, such as gold and oil.", "takeaways": ["A commodity market is a market that trades in the primary economic sector rather than manufactured products.", "Derivatives are either exchange-traded or over-the-counter (OTC).", "According to the World Gold Council, ETFs allow investors to be exposed to the gold market without the risk of price volatility associated with gold a…"], "marketLinks": ["CL=F", "GC=F", "DBC"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Commodity_market"},
    {"id": "roll-yield", "level": "进阶", "category": "商品", "title": "Roll yield——The roll yield is the difference between the profit or loss …", "summary": "The roll yield is the difference between the profit or loss of a futures contract and the change in the spot price of the underlying asset of that futures contract.", "takeaways": ["The roll yield is the difference between the profit or loss of a futures contract and the change in the spot price of the underlying asset of that futures contract.", "Unlike fixed income or dividend yields, a roll yield does not provide a cash payment, and may not be counted as a profit in certain cases if it accounts for the underlying asset's cost-of-carry.", "Nonetheless, the roll yield is often characterized as a return that a futures investor capture in addition to the price change of the underlying asset of a futures contract."], "marketLinks": ["CL=F", "GC=F", "DBC"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roll_yield"},
    {"id": "carbon-credit", "level": "进阶", "category": "商品", "title": "Carbon emission trading——Carbon emission trading (also called carbon market, emission…", "summary": "Carbon emission trading (also called carbon market, emission trading scheme (ETS) or cap and trade) is a type of emissions trading scheme designed for carbon dioxide (CO2) and other greenhouse gases (GHGs).", "takeaways": ["A form of carbon pricing, its purpose is to limit climate change by creating a market with limited allowances for emissions.", "Instead, carbon emissions trading may accelerate investments into renewable energy, such as wind power and solar power.", "It can speed up emissions reduction seven-fold in all participating countries, while delivering $200 billion per year for clean-energy and social prog…"], "marketLinks": ["CL=F", "GC=F", "DBC"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carbon_emission_trading"},
    {"id": "strategic-petroleum-reserve", "level": "进阶", "category": "商品", "title": "Strategic Petroleum Reserve (United States)——The Strategic Petroleum Reserve (SPR) is an emergency stockp…", "summary": "The Strategic Petroleum Reserve (SPR) is an emergency stockpile of petroleum maintained by the United States Department of Energy (DOE). It is the largest publicly known emergency supply in the world; its underground tanks in Louisiana and Texas have capacity for 714 million barrels (113,500,000 m3).", "takeaways": ["The Strategic Petroleum Reserve (SPR) is an emergency stockpile of petroleum maintained by the United States Department of Energy (DOE).", "Since 2015, Congress has mandated sales of oil from the reserve to fund federal spending.", "As part of this effort, President Trump authorized the Department of Energy to release 172 million barrels from the Strategic Petroleum Reserve, begin…"], "marketLinks": ["CL=F", "GC=F", "DBC"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Strategic_Petroleum_Reserve_%28United_States%29"},
    {"id": "commodity-super-cycle", "level": "进阶", "category": "商品", "title": "Commodity price shocks——Commodity price shocks are times when the prices for commodi…", "summary": "Commodity price shocks are times when the prices for commodities have drastically increased or decreased over a short span of time.", "takeaways": ["了解Commodity price shocks的基本定义和应用场景", "理解Commodity price shocks在金融市场中的作用和影响", "结合市场数据观察Commodity price shocks的实际表现"], "marketLinks": ["CL=F", "GC=F", "DBC"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Commodity_price_shocks"},
    {"id": "blockchain", "level": "入门", "category": "加密资产", "title": "Blockchain——A blockchain is a distributed ledger with growing lists of r…", "summary": "A blockchain is a distributed ledger with growing lists of records (blocks) that are securely linked together via cryptographic hashes. Each block contains a cryptographic hash of the previous block, a timestamp, and transaction data (generally represented as a Merkle tree, where data nodes are represented by leaves).", "takeaways": ["A blockchain is a distributed ledger with growing lists of records (blocks) that are securely linked together via cryptographic hashes.", "Scott Stornetta, and Dave Bayer.", "Private blockchains have been proposed for business use."], "marketLinks": ["BTC-USD", "ETH-USD", "SOL-USD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blockchain"},
    {"id": "bitcoin", "level": "入门", "category": "加密资产", "title": "Bitcoin——Bitcoin (abbreviation: BTC; sign: ₿) is the first decentrali…", "summary": "Bitcoin (abbreviation: BTC; sign: ₿) is the first decentralized cryptocurrency. Based on a free-market ideology, bitcoin was invented in 2008 when an unknown person published a white paper under the pseudonym of Satoshi Nakamoto.", "takeaways": ["Bitcoin (abbreviation: BTC; sign: ₿) is the first decentralized cryptocurrency.", "As bitcoin is pseudonymous, its use by criminals has attracted the attention of regulators, leading to its ban by several countries.", "Consensus between nodes about the content of the blockchain is achieved using a computationally intensive process based on proof of work, called minin…"], "marketLinks": ["BTC-USD", "ETH-USD", "SOL-USD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bitcoin"},
    {"id": "ethereum", "level": "入门", "category": "加密资产", "title": "Ethereum——Ethereum is a decentralized blockchain with smart contract f…", "summary": "Ethereum is a decentralized blockchain with smart contract functionality. Ether (abbreviation: ETH) is the native cryptocurrency of the platform. Among cryptocurrencies, ether is second only to bitcoin in market capitalization. It is open-source software. Ethereum was conceived in 2013 by programmer Vitalik Buterin.", "takeaways": ["Ethereum is a decentralized blockchain with smart contract functionality.", "Other founders include Gavin Wood, Charles Hoskinson, Anthony Di Iorio, and Joseph Lubin.", "Ethereum allows users to create fungible (e.g."], "marketLinks": ["BTC-USD", "ETH-USD", "SOL-USD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ethereum"},
    {"id": "proof-of-work", "level": "入门", "category": "加密资产", "title": "Proof of work——Proof of work (also written as proof-of-work, and abbreviate…", "summary": "Proof of work (also written as proof-of-work, and abbreviated PoW) is a form of cryptographic proof in which one party (the prover) proves to others (the verifiers) that a certain amount of a specific computational effort has been expended.", "takeaways": ["Verifiers can subsequently confirm this expenditure with minimal effort on their part.", "PoW and PoS (proof of stake) remain the two best known Sybil deterrence mechanisms.", "The interruptible load characteristics of proof-of-work mining provide demand-response services and support the integration of variable renewable ener…"], "marketLinks": ["BTC-USD", "ETH-USD", "SOL-USD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proof_of_work"},
    {"id": "proof-of-stake", "level": "入门", "category": "加密资产", "title": "Proof of stake——Proof-of-stake (PoS) protocols are a class of consensus mech…", "summary": "Proof-of-stake (PoS) protocols are a class of consensus mechanisms for blockchains that work by selecting validators in proportion to their quantity of holdings in the associated cryptocurrency. This is done to avoid the computational cost of proof-of-work (PoW) schemes.", "takeaways": ["Proof-of-stake (PoS) protocols are a class of consensus mechanisms for blockchains that work by selecting validators in proportion to their quantity of holdings in the associated cryptocurrency.", "This is done to avoid the computational cost of proof-of-work (PoW) schemes.", "The first functioning use of PoS for cryptocurrency was Peercoin in 2012, although its scheme, on the surface, still resembled a PoW."], "marketLinks": ["BTC-USD", "ETH-USD", "SOL-USD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proof_of_stake"},
    {"id": "defi", "level": "进阶", "category": "加密资产", "title": "Decentralized finance——Decentralized finance (often stylized as DeFi) provides fina…", "summary": "Decentralized finance (often stylized as DeFi) provides financial instruments and services through smart contracts on a programmable, permissionless blockchain. This approach reduces the need for intermediaries such as brokerages, exchanges, or banks.", "takeaways": ["Decentralized finance (often stylized as DeFi) provides financial instruments and services through smart contracts on a programmable, permissionless b…", "While some applications offer high interest rates, they carry high risks.", "Developers can create interoperable financial products by combining different DeFi protocols like building blocks, a concept often referred to as \"mon…"], "marketLinks": ["BTC-USD", "ETH-USD", "SOL-USD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decentralized_finance"},
    {"id": "stablecoin", "level": "入门", "category": "加密资产", "title": "Stablecoin——A stablecoin is a type of cryptocurrency that aims to mainta…", "summary": "A stablecoin is a type of cryptocurrency that aims to maintain a stable value relative to a specified asset, a pool or basket of assets. The specified asset might refer to fiat currency, commodity, or other cryptocurrencies. Despite the name, stablecoins are not necessarily stable.", "takeaways": ["A stablecoin is a type of cryptocurrency that aims to maintain a stable value relative to a specified asset, a pool or basket of assets.", "Stablecoins rely on stabilization tools such as reserve assets or algorithms that match supply and demand to try to maintain a stable value.", "With a growing number of market transactions involving stablecoins, their issuance and usage are increasingly regulated by governments around the worl…"], "marketLinks": ["BTC-USD", "ETH-USD", "SOL-USD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stablecoin"},
    {"id": "nft", "level": "入门", "category": "加密资产", "title": "Non-fungible token——A non-fungible token (NFT) is a unique digital identifier th…", "summary": "A non-fungible token (NFT) is a unique digital identifier that is recorded on a blockchain and is used to certify ownership and authenticity. They typically contain references to digital files such as artworks, photos, videos, and audio.", "takeaways": ["A non-fungible token (NFT) is a unique digital identifier that is recorded on a blockchain and is used to certify ownership and authenticity.", "Its market was occasionally compared to an economic bubble or a Ponzi scheme.", "NFTs have been used as speculative investments and have drawn criticism for the energy cost and carbon footprint associated with some types of blockch…"], "marketLinks": ["BTC-USD", "ETH-USD", "SOL-USD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Non-fungible_token"},
    {"id": "crypto-exchange", "level": "进阶", "category": "加密资产", "title": "Cryptocurrency exchange——A cryptocurrency exchange, or a digital currency exchange (D…", "summary": "A cryptocurrency exchange, or a digital currency exchange (DCE), is a business that allows customers to trade cryptocurrencies or digital currencies for other assets, such as conventional fiat money or other digital currencies.", "takeaways": ["Exchanges may accept credit card payments, wire transfers or other forms of payment in exchange for digital currencies or cryptocurrencies.", "A cryptocurrency exchange can be a market maker that typically takes the bid–ask spreads as a transaction commission for its service or, as a matching platform, simply charges fees."], "marketLinks": ["BTC-USD", "ETH-USD", "SOL-USD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cryptocurrency_exchange"},
    {"id": "crypto-wallet", "level": "入门", "category": "加密资产", "title": "Cryptocurrency wallet——A cryptocurrency wallet is a device, physical medium, progra…", "summary": "A cryptocurrency wallet is a device, physical medium, program or an online service which stores the public and/or private keys for cryptocurrency transactions. In addition to this basic function of storing the keys, a cryptocurrency wallet more often offers the functionality of encrypting and/or signing information.", "takeaways": ["A cryptocurrency wallet is a device, physical medium, program or an online service which stores the public and/or private keys for cryptocurrency transactions.", "In addition to this basic function of storing the keys, a cryptocurrency wallet more often offers the functionality of encrypting and/or signing information."], "marketLinks": ["BTC-USD", "ETH-USD", "SOL-USD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cryptocurrency_wallet"},
    {"id": "smart-contract", "level": "进阶", "category": "加密资产", "title": "Smart contract——A smart contract is a computer program or a transaction prot…", "summary": "A smart contract is a computer program or a transaction protocol that is intended to automatically execute, control or document events and actions according to the terms of a contract or an agreement.", "takeaways": ["The objectives of smart contracts are the reduction of need for trusted intermediators, arbitration costs, and fraud losses, as well as the reduction of malicious and accidental exceptions.", "Since then, various cryptocurrencies have supported programming languages which allow for more advanced smart contracts between untrusted parties."], "marketLinks": ["BTC-USD", "ETH-USD", "SOL-USD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Smart_contract"},
    {"id": "bitcoin-halving", "level": "进阶", "category": "加密资产", "title": "Bitcoin protocol——The bitcoin protocol is the set of rules that govern the fun…", "summary": "The bitcoin protocol is the set of rules that govern the functioning of bitcoin. Its key components and principles are: a peer-to-peer decentralized network with no central oversight; the blockchain technology, a public ledger that records all bitcoin transactions; mining and proof of work, the process to create new…", "takeaways": ["The bitcoin protocol is the set of rules that govern the functioning of bitcoin.", "Mining packages groups of transactions into blocks, and produces a hash code that follows the rules of the bitcoin protocol.", "The bitcoin protocol has inspired the creation of numerous other digital currencies and blockchain-based technologies, making it a foundational techno…"], "marketLinks": ["BTC-USD", "ETH-USD", "SOL-USD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bitcoin_halving"},
    {"id": "ethereum-gas", "level": "进阶", "category": "加密资产", "title": "Ethereum——Ethereum is a decentralized blockchain with smart contract f…", "summary": "Ethereum is a decentralized blockchain with smart contract functionality. Ether (abbreviation: ETH) is the native cryptocurrency of the platform. Among cryptocurrencies, ether is second only to bitcoin in market capitalization. It is open-source software. Ethereum was conceived in 2013 by programmer Vitalik Buterin.", "takeaways": ["Ethereum is a decentralized blockchain with smart contract functionality.", "Other founders include Gavin Wood, Charles Hoskinson, Anthony Di Iorio, and Joseph Lubin.", "Ethereum allows users to create fungible (e.g."], "marketLinks": ["BTC-USD", "ETH-USD", "SOL-USD"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ethereum"},
    {"id": "etf-structure", "level": "入门", "category": "基金", "title": "Exchange-traded fund——An exchange-traded fund (ETF) is a type of investment fund t…", "summary": "An exchange-traded fund (ETF) is a type of investment fund that is also an exchange-traded product; i.e., it is bought and sold on stock exchanges. ETFs own financial assets such as stocks, bonds, currencies, cryptocurrency, debt, futures contracts, and/or commodities such as gold bars.", "takeaways": ["An exchange-traded fund (ETF) is a type of investment fund that is also an exchange-traded product; i.e., it is bought and sold on stock exchanges.", "Unlike mutual funds, ETFs are priced continuously throughout the trading day.", "ETFs are regulated by governmental bodies and are subject to securities laws."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "QQQ", "IWM"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exchange-traded_fund"},
    {"id": "tracking-error", "level": "进阶", "category": "基金", "title": "Tracking error——In finance, tracking error or active risk is a measure of th…", "summary": "In finance, tracking error or active risk is a measure of the risk in an investment portfolio that is due to active management decisions made by the portfolio manager; it indicates how closely a portfolio follows the index to which it is benchmarked.", "takeaways": ["The best measure is the standard deviation of the difference between the portfolio and index returns.", "Thus the tracking error does not include any risk (return) that is merely a function of the market's movement.", "Dividing portfolio active return by portfolio tracking error gives the information ratio, which is a risk adjusted performance measure."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "QQQ", "IWM"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tracking_error"},
    {"id": "expense-ratio", "level": "入门", "category": "基金", "title": "Expense ratio——The expense ratio is a term used in investment management or…", "summary": "The expense ratio is a term used in investment management or corporate finance to analyze the annual cost of owning an investment fund or operating a business or nonprofit organization.", "takeaways": ["了解Expense ratio的基本定义和应用场景", "理解Expense ratio在金融市场中的作用和影响", "结合市场数据观察Expense ratio的实际表现"], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "QQQ", "IWM"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Expense_ratio"},
    {"id": "etf-premium-discount", "level": "进阶", "category": "基金", "title": "Exchange-traded fund——An exchange-traded fund (ETF) is a type of investment fund t…", "summary": "An exchange-traded fund (ETF) is a type of investment fund that is also an exchange-traded product; i.e., it is bought and sold on stock exchanges. ETFs own financial assets such as stocks, bonds, currencies, cryptocurrency, debt, futures contracts, and/or commodities such as gold bars.", "takeaways": ["An exchange-traded fund (ETF) is a type of investment fund that is also an exchange-traded product; i.e., it is bought and sold on stock exchanges.", "Unlike mutual funds, ETFs are priced continuously throughout the trading day.", "ETFs are regulated by governmental bodies and are subject to securities laws."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "QQQ", "IWM"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exchange-traded_fund"},
    {"id": "mutual-fund", "level": "入门", "category": "基金", "title": "Mutual fund——A mutual fund is an investment fund that pools money from ma…", "summary": "A mutual fund is an investment fund that pools money from many investors to purchase securities. The term is typically used in the United States, Canada, and India, while similar structures across the globe include the SICAV in Europe ('investment company with variable capital'), and the open-ended investment company…", "takeaways": ["A mutual fund is an investment fund that pools money from many investors to purchase securities.", "The advantages of mutual funds include economies of scale, diversification, liquidity, and professional management.", "Hedge funds and exchange-traded funds are not typically referred to as mutual funds, and each is targeted at different investors, with hedge funds bei…"], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "QQQ", "IWM"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mutual_fund"},
    {"id": "index-fund", "level": "入门", "category": "基金", "title": "Index fund——An index fund is a mutual fund or exchange-traded fund (ETF)…", "summary": "An index fund is a mutual fund or exchange-traded fund (ETF) designed to follow certain preset rules so that it can replicate the performance of a specified basket of underlying securities (most often a stock market index or a bond market index).", "takeaways": ["The main advantage of index funds for investors is that they are difficult to outperform consistently.", "Bogle, Jack Brennan, Paul Samuelson, Burton Malkiel, David Swensen, Benjamin Graham, Gene Fama, William J.", "Index funds are widely available at low cost for retail investors worldwide, but especially so in the United States, Canada, and Europe."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "QQQ", "IWM"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Index_fund"},
    {"id": "hedge-fund", "level": "进阶", "category": "基金", "title": "Hedge fund——A hedge fund is a pooled investment fund that holds liquid a…", "summary": "A hedge fund is a pooled investment fund that holds liquid assets and that makes use of complex trading and risk management techniques to aim to improve investment performance and insulate returns from market risk. Among these portfolio techniques are short selling and the use of leverage and derivative instruments.", "takeaways": ["Among these portfolio techniques are short selling and the use of  leverage and derivative instruments.", "It is common for hedge fund investment strategies to aim to achieve a positive return on investment regardless of whether markets are rising or fallin…", "They have now grown to be a substantial portion of the asset management industry, with assets totaling around $3.8 trillion as of 2021."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "QQQ", "IWM"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hedge_fund"},
    {"id": "private-equity", "level": "进阶", "category": "基金", "title": "Private equity——Private equity (PE) is stock in a private company that does …", "summary": "Private equity (PE) is stock in a private company that does not offer stock to the general public. Instead, it is offered to specialized investment funds and limited partnerships that take an active role in managing and structuring the companies.", "takeaways": ["Private equity (PE) is stock in a private company that does not offer stock to the general public.", "In colloquial usage, \"private equity\" can refer to these investment firms rather than the companies in which they invest.", "Evaluations of the returns of private equity are mixed: some find that it outperforms public equity, but others find otherwise."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "QQQ", "IWM"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Private_equity"},
    {"id": "venture-capital", "level": "进阶", "category": "基金", "title": "Venture capital——Venture capital (VC) is a form of private equity financing p…", "summary": "Venture capital (VC) is a form of private equity financing provided by firms or funds to startup, early-stage, and emerging companies, that have been deemed to have high growth potential or that have demonstrated high growth in terms of number of employees, annual revenue, scale of operations, etc.", "takeaways": ["Venture capital firms or funds invest in these early-stage companies in exchange for equity, or an ownership stake.", "Seed funding is often used to validate the concept, build a prototype, or conduct market research.", "Venture capitalists also often provide strategic advice to the company's executives on its business model and marketing strategies."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "QQQ", "IWM"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Venture_capital"},
    {"id": "closed-end-fund", "level": "进阶", "category": "基金", "title": "Closed-end fund——A closed-end fund (CEF), also known as a closed-end mutual f…", "summary": "A closed-end fund (CEF), also known as a closed-end mutual fund, is an investment vehicle fund that raises capital by issuing a fixed number of shares at its inception, and then invests that capital in financial assets such as stocks and bonds.", "takeaways": ["After inception it is closed to new capital, although fund managers sometimes employ leverage.", "In the United States, closed-end funds sold publicly must be registered under both the Securities Act of 1933 and the Investment Company Act of 1940.", "Some funds invest in stocks, others in bonds, and some in very specific assets (for instance, tax-exempt bonds issued by the state of Florida in the U…"], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "QQQ", "IWM"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Closed-end_fund"},
    {"id": "leveraged-etf", "level": "进阶", "category": "基金", "title": "Exchange-traded fund——An exchange-traded fund (ETF) is a type of investment fund t…", "summary": "An exchange-traded fund (ETF) is a type of investment fund that is also an exchange-traded product; i.e., it is bought and sold on stock exchanges. ETFs own financial assets such as stocks, bonds, currencies, cryptocurrency, debt, futures contracts, and/or commodities such as gold bars.", "takeaways": ["An exchange-traded fund (ETF) is a type of investment fund that is also an exchange-traded product; i.e., it is bought and sold on stock exchanges.", "Unlike mutual funds, ETFs are priced continuously throughout the trading day.", "ETFs are regulated by governmental bodies and are subject to securities laws."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "QQQ", "IWM"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leveraged_ETF"},
    {"id": "inverse-etf", "level": "进阶", "category": "基金", "title": "Inverse exchange-traded fund——An inverse exchange-traded fund is an exchange-traded fund (…", "summary": "An inverse exchange-traded fund is an exchange-traded fund (ETF), traded on a public stock market, which is designed to perform as the inverse of whatever index or benchmark it is designed to track.", "takeaways": ["An inverse exchange-traded fund is an exchange-traded fund (ETF), traded on a public stock market, which is designed to perform as the inverse of what…", "Because their value rises in a declining market environment, they are popular investments in bear markets.", "Another advantage of inverse ETFs is that they may be held in Individual Retirement Accounts, while short sales are not permitted in these accounts."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "QQQ", "IWM"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inverse_exchange-traded_fund"},
    {"id": "money-market-fund", "level": "入门", "category": "基金", "title": "Money market fund——A money market fund (also called a money market mutual fund)…", "summary": "A money market fund (also called a money market mutual fund) is an open-end mutual fund that invests in short-term debt securities such as US Treasury bills and commercial paper.", "takeaways": ["A money market fund (also called a money market mutual fund) is an open-end mutual fund that invests in short-term debt securities such as US Treasury…", "Although they are not insured against loss, actual losses have been quite rare in practice.", "Regulated in the United States under the Investment Company Act of 1940, and in Europe under Regulation 2017/1131, money market funds are important pr…"], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "QQQ", "IWM"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Money_market_fund"},
    {"id": "target-date-fund", "level": "入门", "category": "基金", "title": "Target date fund——A target date fund (TDF), also known as a lifecycle fund, dy…", "summary": "A target date fund (TDF), also known as a lifecycle fund, dynamic-risk fund, or age-based fund, is a collective investment scheme, often a mutual fund or a collective trust fund, designed to provide a simple investment solution through a portfolio whose asset allocation mix becomes more conservative as the target date…", "takeaways": ["了解Target date fund的基本定义和应用场景", "理解Target date fund在金融市场中的作用和影响", "结合市场数据观察Target date fund的实际表现"], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "QQQ", "IWM"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Target_date_fund"},
    {"id": "reit", "level": "入门", "category": "房地产", "title": "Real estate investment trust——A real estate investment trust (REIT, pronounced \"reet\") is …", "summary": "A real estate investment trust (REIT, pronounced \"reet\") is a company that owns, and in most cases operates, income-producing real estate. REITs own many types of real estate, including office and apartment buildings, studios, warehouses, hospitals, shopping centers, hotels and commercial forests.", "takeaways": ["A real estate investment trust (REIT, pronounced \"reet\") is a company that owns, and in most cases operates, income-producing real estate.", "Most countries' laws governing REITs entitle a real estate company to pay less corporation tax and capital gains tax.", "The key statistics to examine the financial position and operation of a REIT include net asset value (NAV), funds from operations (FFO), and adjusted …"], "marketLinks": ["VNQ", "PLD", "O"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_estate_investment_trust"},
    {"id": "ffo", "level": "进阶", "category": "房地产", "title": "Funds from operations——Funds from operations (FFO) is the term that investors use t…", "summary": "Funds from operations (FFO) is the term that investors use to describe the cash flow of a real estate company or a real estate investment trust (REIT). FFO is a performance indicator created by the National Association of Real Estate Investment Trusts (NAREIT) that is recognized by the SEC to be the standard non-GAAP…", "takeaways": ["Funds from operations (FFO) is the term that investors use to describe the cash flow of a real estate company or a real estate investment trust (REIT)…", "Investors can use the FFO to determine the financial performance of a real estate company.", "Investors frequently utilize the FFO per-share ratio much like they would utilize the EPS of a company."], "marketLinks": ["VNQ", "PLD", "O"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Funds_from_operations"},
    {"id": "capitalization-rate", "level": "进阶", "category": "房地产", "title": "Capitalization rate——Capitalization rate (or \"cap rate\") is a real estate valuati…", "summary": "Capitalization rate (or \"cap rate\") is a real estate valuation measure used to compare different real estate investments. Although there are many variations, the cap rate is generally calculated as the ratio between the annual rental income produced by a real estate asset to its current market value.", "takeaways": ["Capitalization rate (or \"cap rate\") is a real estate valuation measure used to compare different real estate investments.", "Although there are many variations, the cap rate is generally calculated as the ratio between the annual rental income produced by a real estate asset to its current market value."], "marketLinks": ["VNQ", "PLD", "O"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capitalization_rate"},
    {"id": "net-operating-income", "level": "进阶", "category": "房地产", "title": "Earnings before interest and taxes——In accounting and finance, earnings before interest and taxe…", "summary": "In accounting and finance, earnings before interest and taxes (EBIT) is a measure of a firm's profit that includes all incomes and expenses (operating and non-operating) except interest expenses and income tax expenses.", "takeaways": ["了解Earnings before interest and taxes的基本定义和应用场景", "理解Earnings before interest and taxes在金融市场中的作用和影响", "结合市场数据观察Earnings before interest and taxes的实际表现"], "marketLinks": ["VNQ", "PLD", "O"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Net_operating_income"},
    {"id": "commercial-real-estate", "level": "入门", "category": "房地产", "title": "Commercial property——Commercial property, also called commercial real estate, inv…", "summary": "Commercial property, also called commercial real estate, investment property or income property, is real estate (buildings or land) intended to generate a profit, either from capital gains or rental income.", "takeaways": ["Commercial property includes office buildings, medical centers, hotels, malls, retail stores, multifamily housing buildings, farm land, warehouses, an…", "convenience stores, 'big box' stores, and shopping malls).", "When space allocated to multiple functions is significant, these buildings can be called multi-use."], "marketLinks": ["VNQ", "PLD", "O"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Commercial_property"},
    {"id": "residential-real-estate", "level": "入门", "category": "房地产", "title": "Real estate economics——Real estate economics is the application of economic techniq…", "summary": "Real estate economics is the application of economic techniques to real estate markets. It aims to describe and predict economic patterns of supply and demand. The closely related field of housing economics is narrower in scope, concentrating on residential real estate markets, while the research on real estate trends…", "takeaways": ["Real estate economics is the application of economic techniques to real estate markets.", "It aims to describe and predict economic patterns of supply and demand.", "Both draw on partial equilibrium analysis (supply and demand), urban economics, spatial economics, basic and extensive research, surveys, and finance."], "marketLinks": ["VNQ", "PLD", "O"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_estate_economics"},
    {"id": "mortgage-backed-security", "level": "进阶", "category": "房地产", "title": "Mortgage-backed security——A mortgage-backed security (MBS) is a type of asset-backed s…", "summary": "A mortgage-backed security (MBS) is a type of asset-backed security (an \"instrument\") which is secured by a mortgage or collection of mortgages. The mortgages are aggregated and sold to a group of individuals (a government agency or investment bank) that securitizes, or packages, the loans together into a security…", "takeaways": ["A mortgage-backed security (MBS) is a type of asset-backed security (an \"instrument\") which is secured by a mortgage or collection of mortgages.", "More generally, bonds which are secured by the pledge of specific assets are called mortgage bonds.", "This decrease in face value is measured by the MBS's \"factor\", the percentage of the original \"face\" that remains to be repaid."], "marketLinks": ["VNQ", "PLD", "O"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mortgage-backed_security"},
    {"id": "subprime-mortgage", "level": "进阶", "category": "房地产", "title": "Subprime lending——In finance, subprime lending (also referred to as near-prime…", "summary": "In finance, subprime lending (also referred to as near-prime, subpar, non-prime, and second-chance lending) is the provision of loans to people who may have difficulty maintaining the repayment schedule.", "takeaways": ["Subprime loans are characterized by higher interest rates, poor quality collateral, and less favorable terms in order to compensate for higher credit risk.", "During the early to mid-2000s, many subprime loans were packaged into mortgage-backed securities (MBS) and ultimately defaulted, contributing to the 2008 financial crisis.", "Proponents of subprime lending maintain that the practice extends credit to people who would otherwise not have access to the credit market."], "marketLinks": ["VNQ", "PLD", "O"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Subprime_lending"},
    {"id": "home-equity", "level": "入门", "category": "房地产", "title": "Home equity——Home equity is the homeowner's financial interest in their p…", "summary": "Home equity is the homeowner's financial interest in their property, calculated as the difference between the property's current market value and the total outstanding balances of all loans secured by the home.", "takeaways": ["了解Home equity的基本定义和应用场景", "理解Home equity在金融市场中的作用和影响", "结合市场数据观察Home equity的实际表现"], "marketLinks": ["VNQ", "PLD", "O"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Home_equity"},
    {"id": "real-estate-bubble", "level": "进阶", "category": "房地产", "title": "Real-estate bubble——A real-estate bubble or property bubble (or housing bubble f…", "summary": "A real-estate bubble or property bubble (or housing bubble for residential markets) is a type of economic bubble that occurs periodically in local or global real estate markets, and it typically follows a land boom or reduced interest rates.", "takeaways": ["A land boom is a rapid increase in the market price of real property, such as housing, until prices reach unsustainable levels and then decline.", "Housing price busts are less frequent, but last nearly twice as long and lead to output losses that are twice as large (IMF World Economic Outlook, 20…", "The 2008 financial crisis was caused by the bursting of real estate bubbles that had begun in various countries during the 2000s."], "marketLinks": ["VNQ", "PLD", "O"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real-estate_bubble"},
    {"id": "compound-interest", "level": "入门", "category": "个人理财", "title": "Compound interest——Compound interest is interest accumulated from a principal s…", "summary": "Compound interest is interest accumulated from a principal sum and previously accumulated interest. It is the result of reinvesting or retaining interest that would otherwise be paid out, or of the accumulation of debts from a borrower.", "takeaways": ["Compound interest is interest accumulated from a principal sum and previously accumulated interest.", "Compound interest is contrasted with simple interest, where previously accumulated interest is not added to the principal amount of the current period…", "Compounded interest depends on the simple interest rate applied and the frequency at which the interest is compounded."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "SCHD", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Compound_interest"},
    {"id": "ira-account", "level": "入门", "category": "个人理财", "title": "Individual retirement account——An individual retirement account (IRA) in the United States …", "summary": "An individual retirement account (IRA) in the United States is a type of retirement savings plan offered by many financial institutions that provides tax advantages for retirement savings.", "takeaways": ["An individual retirement account (IRA) in the United States is a type of retirement savings plan offered by many financial institutions that provides …", "An individual retirement account is a type of individual retirement arrangement as described in IRS Publication 590, Individual Retirement Arrangement…", "Other arrangements include individual retirement annuities and employer-established benefit trusts."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "SCHD", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Individual_retirement_account"},
    {"id": "roth-ira", "level": "入门", "category": "个人理财", "title": "Roth IRA——A Roth IRA is an individual retirement account (IRA) under U…", "summary": "A Roth IRA is an individual retirement account (IRA) under United States law that is generally not taxed upon distribution, provided certain conditions are met. The principal difference between Roth IRAs and most other tax-advantaged retirement plans is that rather than granting an income tax reduction for…", "takeaways": ["A Roth IRA is an individual retirement account (IRA) under United States law that is generally not taxed upon distribution, provided certain conditions are met.", "The Roth IRA was introduced as part of the Taxpayer Relief Act of 1997 and is named for Senator William Roth."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "SCHD", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roth_IRA"},
    {"id": "traditional-ira", "level": "入门", "category": "个人理财", "title": "Traditional IRA——A traditional IRA is an individual retirement arrangement (I…", "summary": "A traditional IRA is an individual retirement arrangement (IRA), established in the United States by the Employee Retirement Income Security Act of 1974 (ERISA) (Pub. L. 93–406, 88 Stat. 829, enacted September 2, 1974, codified in part at 29 U.S.C. ch. 18). Normal IRAs also existed before ERISA.", "takeaways": ["A traditional IRA is an individual retirement arrangement (IRA), established in the United States by the Employee Retirement Income Security Act of 1974 (ERISA) (Pub.", "829, enacted September 2, 1974, codified in part at 29 U.S.C.", "Normal IRAs also existed before ERISA."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "SCHD", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Traditional_IRA"},
    {"id": "floor-401k", "level": "入门", "category": "个人理财", "title": "401(k)——In the United States, a 401(k) plan is an employer-sponsored…", "summary": "In the United States, a 401(k) plan is an employer-sponsored, defined-contribution, personal pension (savings) account, as defined in subsection 401(k) of the U.S. Internal Revenue Code. Periodic employee contributions come directly out of their paychecks, and may be matched by the employer.", "takeaways": ["In the United States, a 401(k) plan is an employer-sponsored, defined-contribution, personal pension (savings) account, as defined in subsection 401(k…", "There are two types of 401(k) plans: traditional and Roth.", "In 2019, 401(k) plans had US$6.4 trillion in assets."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "SCHD", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/401%28k%29"},
    {"id": "capital-gains-tax", "level": "入门", "category": "个人理财", "title": "Capital gains tax——A capital gains tax (CGT) is the tax on profits realised on …", "summary": "A capital gains tax (CGT) is the tax on profits realised on the sale of a non-inventory asset. The most common capital gains are realised from the sale of stocks, bonds, precious metals, real estate, and property.", "takeaways": ["A capital gains tax (CGT) is the tax on profits realised on the sale of a non-inventory asset.", "Antiques, shares, precious metals and second homes could be all subject to the tax if the profit is large enough.", "For equities, national and state legislation often has a large array of fiscal obligations that must be respected regarding capital gains."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "SCHD", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_gains_tax"},
    {"id": "wash-sale-rule", "level": "进阶", "category": "个人理财", "title": "Wash sale——A wash sale is the sale of stock (or securities more general…", "summary": "A wash sale is the sale of stock (or securities more generally) at a loss when substantially identical securities were acquired shortly before or after the date of sale. Wash sale regulations disallow most investors from using the value of a loss realized in a wash sale as a tax deduction.", "takeaways": ["A wash sale is the sale of stock (or securities more generally) at a loss when substantially identical securities were acquired shortly before or afte…", "That is, for an investor to receive the tax benefit of a realized capital loss, they must have changed their economic position in a \"meaningful way\".", "Such losses are typically added to the basis of the securities acquired in the wash sale period, essentially deferring the tax benefits until a non-wa…"], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "SCHD", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wash_sale"},
    {"id": "withdrawal-rule-four-percent", "level": "进阶", "category": "个人理财", "title": "Trinity study——In finance, investment advising, and retirement planning, th…", "summary": "In finance, investment advising, and retirement planning, the Trinity study is an informal name used to refer to an influential 1998 paper by three professors of finance at Trinity University in the US.", "takeaways": ["了解Trinity study的基本定义和应用场景", "理解Trinity study在金融市场中的作用和影响", "结合市场数据观察Trinity study的实际表现"], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "SCHD", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trinity_study"},
    {"id": "emergency-fund", "level": "入门", "category": "个人理财", "title": "Rainy day fund——A rainy day or rainy day fund is a reserved amount of money …", "summary": "A rainy day or rainy day fund is a reserved amount of money to be used in times when regular income is disrupted or decreased in order for typical operations to continue. In the United States, the term is usually used to apply to the funds maintained by most U.S.", "takeaways": ["A rainy day  or rainy day fund is a reserved amount of money to be used in times when regular income is disrupted or decreased in order for typical op…", "The Massachusetts rainy day fund has been the focus of tussles between the governor of Massachusetts and the Massachusetts General Court.", "Some research suggests developing a national rainy day fund for states might improve state credit ratings and reduce capital financing costs for state…"], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "SCHD", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rainy_day_fund"},
    {"id": "dollar-cost-averaging", "level": "入门", "category": "个人理财", "title": "Dollar cost averaging——Dollar cost averaging (DCA) is an investment strategy which …", "summary": "Dollar cost averaging (DCA) is an investment strategy which aims to apply value investing principles to regular investment. The term was coined by Benjamin Graham in his 1949 book The Intelligent Investor.", "takeaways": ["Dollar cost averaging (DCA) is an investment strategy which aims to apply value investing principles to regular investment.", "It should not be confused with the constant dollar plan, which is a form of rebalancing investments.", "A major advantage of DCA is its long-term investment horizon, a simplification which promotes fiscal discipline; given its clockwork like methods, con…"], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "SCHD", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dollar_cost_averaging"},
    {"id": "credit-score", "level": "入门", "category": "个人理财", "title": "Credit score——A credit score is a numerical expression based on a level an…", "summary": "A credit score is a numerical expression based on a level analysis of a person's credit files, to represent the creditworthiness of an individual. A credit score is primarily based on a credit report, information typically sourced from credit bureaus.", "takeaways": ["A credit score is a numerical expression based on a level analysis of a person's credit files, to represent the creditworthiness of an individual.", "Lenders also use credit scores to determine which customers are likely to bring in the most revenue.", "Digital finance companies such as online lenders also use alternative data sources to calculate the creditworthiness of borrowers."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "SCHD", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Credit_score"},
    {"id": "inflation-hedge", "level": "入门", "category": "个人理财", "title": "Inflation hedge——Inflation hedge is an asset, contract or strategy that aims …", "summary": "Inflation hedge is an asset, contract or strategy that aims to preserve purchasing power when the general price level rises (that is, inflation). Definitions differ. Research separates expected inflation, which may already be priced, from unexpected inflation which is an unanticipated change.", "takeaways": ["Inflation hedge is an asset, contract or strategy that aims to preserve purchasing power when the general price level rises (that is, inflation).", "The effectiveness of any hedge depends on horizon and regime.", "No single asset class provides a permanent hedge against unexpected inflation."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "SCHD", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inflation_hedge"},
    {"id": "rule-of-72", "level": "入门", "category": "个人理财", "title": "Rule of 72——In finance, the rule of 72, the rule of 70 and the rule of 6…", "summary": "In finance, the rule of 72, the rule of 70 and the rule of 69.3 are methods for estimating an investment's doubling time. The rule number (e.g., 72) is divided by the interest percentage per period (usually years) to obtain the approximate number of periods required for doubling.", "takeaways": ["In finance, the rule of 72, the rule of 70 and the rule of 69.3 are methods for estimating an investment's doubling time.", "The choice of number is mostly a matter of preference: 69 is more accurate for continuous compounding, while 72 works well in common interest situatio…", "As another example, if one wants to know the number of periods it takes for the initial value to rise by 35%, replace the constant 2 with 1.35."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "SCHD", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rule_of_72"},
    {"id": "fiduciary-duty", "level": "进阶", "category": "个人理财", "title": "Fiduciary——A fiduciary is a person who holds a legal or ethical relatio…", "summary": "A fiduciary is a person who holds a legal or ethical relationship of trust with one or more other parties (legal person or group of persons). Typically, a fiduciary prudently takes care of money or other assets for another person.", "takeaways": ["A fiduciary is a person who holds a legal or ethical relationship of trust with one or more other parties (legal person or group of persons).", "A fiduciary duty is the highest standard of care in equity or law.", "A fiduciary ideally would not have a conflict of interest."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "SCHD", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fiduciary"},
    {"id": "estate-planning", "level": "进阶", "category": "个人理财", "title": "Estate planning——Estate planning or inheritance planning is the process of an…", "summary": "Estate planning or inheritance planning is the process of anticipating and arranging for the management of a person's estate or net worth during the person's life in preparation for future incapacity or death.", "takeaways": ["The planning includes the bequest of assets to heirs, loved ones, and/or charity, and may include legal tax avoidance.", "The estate owner's specific goals determine the ultimate goal of estate planning and may be as simple or as complex as the owner's wishes and needs dictate.", "Guardians are often designated for minor children and beneficiaries with incapacity."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "SCHD", "QQQ"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Estate_planning"},
    {"id": "value-at-risk", "level": "进阶", "category": "风险管理", "title": "Value at risk——Value at risk (VaR) is a measure of the risk of loss of inve…", "summary": "Value at risk (VaR) is a measure of the risk of loss of investment/capital. It estimates how much a set of investments might lose (with a given probability), given normal market conditions, in a set time period such as a day.", "takeaways": ["Value at risk (VaR) is a measure of the risk of loss of investment/capital.", "For instance, assume someone makes a bet that flipping a coin seven times will not give seven heads.", "Important related ideas are economic capital, backtesting, stress testing, expected shortfall, and tail conditional expectation."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "^VIX", "TLT"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Value_at_risk"},
    {"id": "expected-shortfall", "level": "进阶", "category": "风险管理", "title": "Expected shortfall——Expected shortfall (ES) is a risk measure—a concept used in …", "summary": "Expected shortfall (ES) is a risk measure—a concept used in the field of financial risk measurement to evaluate the market risk or credit risk of a portfolio. The \"expected shortfall at q% level\" is the expected return on the portfolio in the worst q % {\\displaystyle q\\%} of cases.", "takeaways": ["Expected shortfall (ES) is a risk measure—a concept used in the field of financial risk measurement to evaluate the market risk or credit risk of a po…", "ES is an alternative to value at risk that is more sensitive to the shape of the tail of the loss distribution.", "These definitions coincide in many cases, but may differ for certain types of loss distributions."], "marketLinks": ["SPY", "^VIX", "TLT"], "sourceName": "Wikipedia / CC BY-SA 4.0", "sourceUrl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Expected_shortfall"},
